<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Politics     07-11 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Politics,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Andreotti Begins His Effort To Form New Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti has begun his
effort to become the premier of Italy for a sixth time.
   He received the mandate to try to form Italy's 49th postwar
government from President Francesco Cossiga on Sunday and met Monday
with caretaker Premier Ciriaco De Mita.
   Andreotti was expected to begin his consultations with various
party leaders today.
   The president turned to Andreotti, who like De Mita belongs to
the dominant Christian Democrats, after De Mita said last week that
he could not revive the five-party coalition he led for 13 months
until resigning May 19.
   De Mita's government collapsed following criticism of his
leadership from the Socialists, the second largest party after the
Christian Democrats in the governing coalition.
   Italian newspapers have reported that Socialist leader Bettino
Craxi, who blocked De Mita's effort to revive his coalition, has
pledged not to oppose Andreotti.
   Andreotti said he would work to revive the five party coalition _
Christian Democrats, Socialists, and the small Republican, Liberal
and Social Democrat parties _ which has governed in recent years.
   He predicted the negotiations to form a new government would be
delayed by preparations for the annual meeting of the seven major
industrialized nations, to be held in Paris this weekend.
   Andreotti served as premier twice in 1972-73 and three times
successively in 1976-79.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
