<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ThirdWorldDebt     07-11 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Third World Debt,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Cool to FDIC Chief's Third World Debt Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady is giving
a chilly reception to a top bank regulator's plan that would rival
his own initiative for easing Third World debt problems.
   L. William Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., says his proposal to partially protect banks from defaults by
debtor nations complements the Brady plan.
   But Brady told reporters Monday, ``We don't think that is
necessary at this point in time.''
   After debt-sparked riots in Venezuela, the treasury secretary
launched an effort in March to persuade banks to reduce the crushing
$1.3 trillion debt borne by Third World nations in Latin America,
Asia and Africa. It was a marked departure from Reagan
administration policy which emphasized new lending rather than debt
reduction.
   Seidman would take the Brady plan one step further by
establishing an International Debt Insurer to encourage banks to
forego repayment of part of the debt by guaranteeing repayment of a
large part of the remaining loans.
   It also would seek to start new money flowing into cash-starved
countries by partly guaranteeing new loans to countries that enact
economic reforms.
   The new agency would be funded by premiums from the banks
themselves, depending on how much debt they held, and by
contributions from the World Bank and International Monetary Fund,
which are supported by member governments.
   Brady, who leaves this week for an economic summit meeting of the
world's seven largest industrial powers, said the group has
previously rejected the creation of an international organization to
deal with the debt problem.
   ``It has been thought about before and not seen to be as good a
way as the way we are going,'' Brady said.
   John Haseltine of the Institute for International Finance, which
represents U.S. and foreign commercial banks, said it is unclear to
what extent the banks' participation will be voluntary, an important
feature if banks are to remain willing to continue lending to
debtors.
   The Seidman plan would give insured debt ``senior'' status to
other debt as a way of discouraging banks from being ``free
riders.'' Thus, banks that didn't go along with debt reduction would
be the first to lose money in the event of a default.
   Seidman first raised his idea publicly in a March speech to the
Bretton Woods Committee, a group of former top government officials
who study international financial issues. He plans to present the
detailed plan at a Bretton Woods dinner on Thursday.
   Seidman's outline describes the current debt reduction process as
a stalemate, but Brady said he was encouraged by progress in talks
between Mexico and its creditor banks in what is seen as the first
test of his plan.
   The two sides reportedly have agreed to the major elements of a
plan to provide Mexico with $3 billion in debt relief, but some
issues remain to be settled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CowboyFreedom     07-11 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cowboy Freedom,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rancher-Lawmaker Fights for Cowboy Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM CRANDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While pinstriped city slickers haggle
over taxes, insurance and ``serious'' issues in the Legislature,
cowboy-legislator John Carpenter keeps a vigil for varmints who try
to bushwack cowboys' rights.
   ``There aren't too many of us left anymore,'' Carpenter said.
``We've got to try and preserve our way of life.''
   When a bill to regulate sale and possession of assault rifles
came up for a vote in the Assembly, the cow county Republican rose
in opposition.
   He wasn't against banning assault rifles. He was against a clause
in the bill aimed at Las Vegas gangs that would have outlawed knives
with 4-inch blades.
   Holding his trusty ``old timer'' pocketknife aloft during floor
debate, he drawled, ``If you passed this law as is, every cowboy in
the state would be a lawbreaker.
   ``Besides,'' he added with a Gary Cooper grin, ``there are a few
little operations we have to perform out there on the ranch,''
referring to the castration of bulls.
   The bill was amended in favor of the cowboys, and passed
unanimously.
   The 59-year-old Fallon native also lauded a bill that would fence
off ``devil's holes,'' abandoned mine shafts that dot the Nevada
landscape, because ``cowboys and their horses could fall down one of
those holes.''
   Carpenter, first elected from Elko County to the Assembly in
1985, has applied his own version of horse sense to other matters.
   He suggested castration as an apt punishment for sex offenders.
When someone said sex crimes were more of a mental problem,
Carpenter said, ``Then maybe we should cut off that part of their
anatomy.''
   Carpenter's biggest showdown came over a measure about wild
horses. The bill, backed by animal rights activists, would have made
it a felony to shoot a wild horse. It also would have given the
activists the upper hand over ranchers on a Commission for the
Preservation of Wild Horses.
   The bill was in response to recent shootings of more than 1,000
wild horses on Nevada's northern and central ranges. Animal rights
advocates often blame ranchers for such killings because ranchers
believe the mustangs rob cows and sheep of valuable forage.
   Environmentalists and animal lovers rose with heartfelt speeches
about the beauty of wild horses and their inherent right to roam the
range.
   Carpenter stood in opposition, and when the dust cleared, he won
two victories: the penalty for shooting a wild horse was reduced to
a gross misdemeanor, and ranchers would have as much say as wild
horse advocates on the commission.
   During the peak of his ranching career, Carpenter said, he has
``paid taxes in eight Nevada counties'' where he ran 20,000 sheep
and 7,000 cows on ranches near Austin, Fallon, Ely, and Elko.
   ``In the old days,'' Carpenter said, ``they used to round up the
wild horses, keep the good ones, and sell the other ones at auction.
A lot of the old ones went for dog food. But it kept the population
under control.''
   A year and a half ago, Carpenter sold the last of his livestock
operations. Now, he works out of his Rancher's Realty in Elko, where
he owns a few businesses.
   But he's getting tired of town life.
   ``Once you're a rancher, you're always a rancher,'' Carpenter
said. ``You can't get it out of your blood ... or off your boots.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
