<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TreasuryBills     07-11 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Hit Eight-Month Low</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities are at their lowest level in eight months.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.6 billion in three-month bills in
Monday's auction at an average discount rate of 7.76 percent, down
from 7.96 percent last week. Another $6.6 billion was sold in
six-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.50 percent, down
from 7.63 percent last week.
   The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 7.54
percent last Nov. 7 and six-month bills averaged 7.48 percent last
Oct. 31.
   The discount rates understate the actual return to investors _
8.03 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,803.80 and 7.90 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,620.80.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 7.97
percent last week, down from 8.28 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
