<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings     07-11 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor `Stunned' by Hastings Action in Racketeering Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prosecutor says the decision by Miami
Judge Alcee L. Hastings to return $845,000 in confiscated cash to a
pair of convicted racketeers shocked him.
   ``I was stunned by the forfeiture,'' James Deichert of the
federal organized crime strike force in Atlanta said Monday at the
start of hearings on Hastings' Senate impeachment trial. ``...Out of
the blue he was reversing himself.''
   House members who are serving as prosecutors at the impeachment
trial say the decision to return the money came just days after an
agreement was cemented for a $150,000 payoff to the federal judge.
   Hastings is accused of plotting with Washington attorney William
Borders to get the payoff in exchange for returning the forfeited
cash and keeping the defendants out of prison.
   Impeachment charges approved a year ago by the House also accuse
Hastings of lying to the jury that acquitted him at his 1983
bribery-conspiracy trial and improperly disclosing information
obtained from a federal wiretap.
   Hastings attorney Terence Anderson of Miami contends his client
was the innocent dupe of Borders, an old law school classmate who
was an influential lawyer in Washington in the late 1970s.
   Borders was convicted in the bribery case and went to prison.
Anderson called him ``a big-time rainmaker'' who in order to get
payoffs claimed to have influence with Hastings.
   ``Alcee L. Hastings was, is and will forever be an innocent
man,'' Anderson said.
   Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, told the Senate panel Monday that
Hastings' actions ``present a pattern of misconduct which cannot be
tolerated in a United States district judge.''
   Bryant said the Senate should expel Hastings from the bench even
though he was found innocent in criminal court. ``That acquittal was
the product of repeated lies and the production of fabricated
evidence at his criminal trial,'' he said.
   ``Judge Hastings cannot be prosecuted again. But he can be
removed from office,'' Bryant said.
   Evidence is being heard by a 12-member panel because senators do
not want to tie up the floor and slow the pace of legislation for
weeks. The proceedings are being videotaped for viewing at the
convenience of lawmakers who are not members of the committee.
   Committee Chairman Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., hopes to wrap up work
by Aug. 4, two days before Congress plans to leave for the summer.
However, there's no guarantee the complicated legal battle won't
drag on longer for the 12-member panel while other senators go on
vacation.
   Hastings, himself, told reporters on Monday that he is growing
impatient at hearing the same charges against him.
   ``It's deja vu all over again,'' Hastings told reporters after
Monday's first session.
   In a hallway outside the hearing, Hastings called the proceedings
``an abomination'' because they consisted of ``the same old stuff,
and I really resent it, quite frankly.''
</TEXT>
