<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Honoraria     07-11 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honoraria,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Interests Pay Dearly to Hear Lawmakers' Speak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Special interests that lobby the same lawmakers
they pay for speaking engagements are undermining the debate in
Congress, Common Cause says in its latest study of congressional
speechmaking-for-hire.
   Defense contractors directed speaking fees last year to members
of the armed services committees. Tobacco, fertilizer and grocery
interests heard from members of the agriculture committees. Bankers,
the securities industry and home builders listened to the banking
committee members.
   ``Millions of dollars in special interest honoraria fees are
undermining the integrity and credibility of Congress,'' Common
Cause President Fred Wertheimer said Monday, releasing the
congressional watchdog's study of 1988 honoraria giving.
   The group's annual report takes on new urgency this year with
clamor growing for an end to lawmakers' outside income.
   President Bush on July 7 sent Congress legislation to end the
honoraria system by Jan. 1, 1991. Numerous lawmakers have called for
the same thing, but the price would be a politically risky
congressional pay raise that would compensate for the loss of
speaking fee income.
   When lawmakers considered boosting their salaries by 51 percent
earlier this year, the plan was killed after a public outcry.
   Task forces in both houses are expected to consider the pay issue
again along with reform of House and Senate rules. Some members
suggest a salary increase be phased in over several years.
   Common Cause said 20 groups gave at least $50,000 in honoraria to
members of Congress in 1988, led by The Tobacco Institute's spending
of $123,400; the National Association of Broadcasters' $113,500 and
the $106,550 spent by the American Bankers Association.
   The study found the 11 leading givers among defense contractors
paid a combined $457,387 to all members of Congress, with 67 percent
directed to members of the House and Senate Armed Services
Committees and lawmakers on the defense appropriations subcommittees.
   The National Association of Broadcasters paid 60 percent of its
$113,500 in honoraria to members of committees dealing with
communications _ the House Energy and Commerce and the Senate
Commerce committees, the study said.
   Twenty-nine House and Senate members reported NAB honoraria and
travel reimbursement for appearances in Las Vegas and seven for
appearances in Hawaii.
   The National Venture Capital Association, which favors a lower
capital gains tax, paid 88 percent of its $33,000 in honoraria to 22
members of the tax-writing House Ways and Means and Senate Finance
committees, according to the study.
   The National Cable Television Association gave 69 percent of its
$53,700 in honoraria to committee members dealing with legislation
affecting the cable industry, including copyright bills.
   A similar pattern emerged for individual lawmakers.
   Rep. Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., chairman of the Energy and
Commerce health and the environment subcommittee, received 76
percent of his total $71,750 in honoraria from commerce and
health-related interests.
   Rep. William Dickinson, R-Ala., ranking Republican on the House
Armed Services Committee, received 96 percent of his $32,250
honoraria from defense-related interests.
   The chairman of the House Agriculture Committee, Rep. Kika de la
Garza, D-Texas, earned $29,800 in total honoraria, 97 percent of it
from agriculture-related interests.
   The Tobacco Institute spread its speaking fees around, paying 85
House members and eight senators. RJR@Nabisco, Philip Morris and
the Smokeless Tobacco Council gave another $138,000 to lawmakers,
Common Cause found.
   House members can keep up to $26,850 in outside income, mainly
honoraria, and must donate the rest to charity. Senators can keep up
to $35,800.
   Members of Congress can keep up to $2,000 for any single
appearance, speech or article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
