<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     07-11 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Rests In Night Stalker Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense rested its case in the ``Night
Stalker'' mass murder trial Monday, nearly four years after
defendant Richard Ramirez was arrested in connection with a spree of
nocturnal attacks.
   Defense attorneys, seeking to prove that Ramirez was a victim of
mistaken identity, wrapped up their case with two witnesses who
testified Ramirez was in Texas at the time of two of the 15 attacks
for which he is charged.
   Ramirez' sister-in-law, Maria Torres, told jurors that she saw
Ramirez in El Paso, Texas, on May 25 and May 29, 1985, and that her
memory was clear because May 29 was ``the one-month anniversary
after I separated from my husband.''
   Raymundo Pantoja, a friend of Ramirez' father, also testified
that he saw Ramirez on May 25, 1985.
   Ramirez, a 29-year-old drifter and self-described devil worshiper
from El Paso, is charged with 13 murders and 30 related felonies in
a crime wave that terrorized California during the summer of 1985.
   Pentagrams, a symbol of devil worship, were found at some murder
scenes and the assailant gouged out the eyes of one victim.
   The defense called 37 witnesses, many of them testifying that
lighting and other conditions made it difficult to identify the
attacker. Ramirez did not testify.
   Ramirez was arrested Aug. 31, 1985, after a crowd of East Los
Angeles residents recognized him from news photographs and captured
him as he allegedly tried to steal a car.
   Closing arguments were scheduled for Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
