<FIRST>u a AM-INSChanges     07-11 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-INS Changes,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ezell Resigns, Regrets Attending Marcos Party; Gustafson Retires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Ezell was ousted as regional
immigration commissioner Monday, saying his only regret was
attending a party for deposed Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
and his wife, Imelda.
   ``In hindsight, there's no way I would have gone to that
reception knowing what I know today,'' he told a news conference on
his last day with the federal Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   ``Although nothing happened that was illegal or immoral, I regret
the perception it created,'' the INS' outgoing Western regional
commissioner said of the August 1988 party in Honolulu at which he
was videotaped.
   At the gathering, Ezell led partygoers in a prayer asking for the
Marcoses' safe return to the Philippines, which would be against
President Corazon Aquino's wishes and U.S. policy.
   Asked what he knows now that he didn't know then, he said, ``We
didn't know they were going to be indicted. We would not have gone
knowing that.''
   The Marcoses were indicted on charges they plundered billions
from the Philippines.
   Ezell said, however, that he believed the incident had nothing to
do with the acceptance of his resignation.
   Ezell, who has served as western region commissioner since 1983,
said last month that he expected to be replaced after INS National
Commissioner Alan Nelson resigned.
   He had submitted his resignation in March after George Bush
became president, but said as late as May that he wanted to keep the
job until late next year.
   He acknowledged Monday that he would have preferred to stay until
November 1990, the end of the second phase of the immigration
amnesty program. As commissioner, Ezell coordinated the INS amnesty
program in the Western region, where about half of the nearly 3
million immigrants who applied for amnesty live.
   Ezell, 52, headed a region that encompassed California, Nevada,
Arizona, Hawaii and Guam.
   But while he was given good marks for the smooth operation of the
program, Ezell often drew fire for remarks that some considered
tasteless.
   Ezell said he suffered ``great pain'' from public perceptions of
him as anti-Hispanic, an allegation he said was untrue.
   ``If you speak out strongly, the cheapest shot they can use is to
say a person is anti- one group or another,'' he said.
   Ezell said he was proud of his accomplishments with the INS,
declaring, ``We have served our country and our people the best
(way) possible.''
   Ezell said he would return to the private sector.
   Acting INS Commissioner James Buck named Robert Moschorak,
associate regional commissioner for operations in the western
region, to replace Ezell temporarily.
</TEXT>
