<FIRST>r a PM-PiranhaProwl     07-11 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Piranha Prowl,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parks Officials Hoping Pond Piranhas Weren't Frisky Fishies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just when people thought it was safe
to go near a city park's pond, word comes that two piranhas caught
there were male and female.
   ``There could be eggs,'' said Jared Dow, who along with his
friend Jason Kraus, both 16, hooked the second of the piranhas
Sunday night from Alice Keck Park Memorial Gardens' pond.
   Park officials, though, are keeping their fingers crossed that
nothing fishy was going on between the piranhas.
   ``Chances are, they hadn't been acclimated to the pond where they
were reproducing,'' said park superintendent Jeff Cope. ``Hopefully,
we've closed this chapter.''
   The story began earlier this month when people noticed that some
of the shallow pond's fish and turtles had been viciously attacked.
Two piranhas were spotted.
   The pond, in the center of the city, is a popular dumping ground
for unwanted fish.
   The first piranha, a female, was caught Friday by park officials
fishing with liver as bait. The second eluded capture. Officials
tried everything, including electronic shock equipment.
   Fishermen, meanwhile, lined the pond until late at night, to the
dismay of parks officials who said the fishermen were harming fish
and other wildlife.
   Among the outlaw anglers were Dow and Kraus, who hooked the
16-inch, 2-pound male fugitive Sunday night with liver bait.
   ``I thought it was a bass because it was jumping out of the water
at first,'' said Dow, a gas station attendant. ``Then we saw the
teeth. The teeth on this one were a quarter-inch long.''
   Dow kept the fish in an aquarium overnight, and hauled it Monday
in a water-filled ice chest to the city Park Department for positive
identification. Since Dow cooperated, no citations were issued for
illegal fishing.
   ``They just told me not to do it again,'' he said.
   The fish was taken to a taxidermist for stuffing and will be
mounted next to its partner in the department's offices.
</TEXT>
