<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-11 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>See Cuts Coal Pollutants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pollutants from burning coal could be cut by
more than half at older power plants linked to acid rain, according
to a study.
   The study was produced Monday by the Energy Department as part of
a $5 billion program with private industry to develop ``clean coal''
technologies.
   A draft analysis of the environment effects of the new
technologies concludes that they could reduce national emissions of
sulfur dioxide from existing coal plants by as much as 45 percent by
the year 2010, the study said. Nitrogen oxide emissions could be cut
by as much as 33 percent over the same period.
   Both are precursors of the acids that form and fall as acid rain
when smokestack gases are carried long distances by the wind.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>USDA Says Donated Apples Will Be Safe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donated apples may contain traces of Alar but
still will be safe, according to the Agriculture Department.
   The USDA announced last week it would spend up to $15 million in
an effort to help reduce a huge surplus of apples created when
consumers stopped buying amid fears over the use of Alar. The plan
was for the USDA to give the apples to schools, prisons, public
assistance food programs and others.
   But the USDA now says growers will donate the apples to various
groups and then be reimbursed.
   The industry has estimated that 5 million to 7 million boxes of
apples from last year's crop, valued at between $40 million and $56
million, remain unsold with this year's harvest only weeks away.
   Alar is used to enhance apple color, ease of harvesting and life
in storage.
   The controversy began in late February when a private
environmental advocacy group, the Natural Resources Defense Council,
said eating apples treated with the chemical substantially increases
the risk of cancer in children. The Environmental Protection Agency
and the Food and Drug Administration disputed the report as a major
exaggeration of the risk.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>SEC Again Proposing New Capital Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a trip back to the drawing board, the
Securities and Exchange Commission is again proposing a rules change
that would make it easier for corporations to raise capital through
the private sale of securities.
   The commission voted 5-0 Monday to seek another round of public
comment on revisions to its controversial proposal to eliminate some
restrictions on the resale of securities offered privately.
   The rule would create what the SEC terms a ``safe harbor'' from
registration and disclosure rules for the resale of privately
offered securities to big institutional investors.
   Supporters of the change say it would lower financing costs for
companies and would attract foreign companies to raise capital in
the United States. But critics claim it would increase the power of
large institutional investors, such as banks and insurance
companies, while cutting into the business of stock exchanges.
</TEXT>
