<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-11 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Nikkei Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen on
Tuesday, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose moderately.
   The dollar finished trading at 139.62 yen, up 0.34 yen from the
previous day's close of 139.28 yen. It opened at 139.47 yen and
ranged between 139.47 yen and 139.78 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 70.75
points, or 0.21 percent, closing at 33,746.77. The index had shed
27.95 points Monday.
   The index rose as participants were reassured after morning gains
and a stability in the dollar-yen rate within the 139-140 yen range,
dealers said.
   A Nomura Securities dealer said, however, the volume was still
small due to participants' concerns over the election for the upper
house of the parliament, scheduled for July 23. He spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Analysts have predicted the governing Liberal Democratic Party
will lose badly in the election, hurt by the Recruit Co.
influence-peddling scandal, an unpopular sales tax imposed in April
and reports that Prime Minister Sousuke Uno has kept several paid
mistresses.
   In recent days the LDP has been further hit by reaction to
reports of remarks by Agriculture Minister Hisao Horinouchi that
``women are useless in politics.'' Next came politically damaging
reports that Minister of Home Affairs Shigenobu Sakano said Monday
that the 3 percent consumption tax should be raised at a time that
many people are calling for its repeal.
   The Nomura dealer said participants have been avoiding buying
issues before the election, fearing a major LDP loss, which might
cause share prices to plunge.
   In currrency dealings, traders attributed the dollar's strength
to a similar trend in New York despite the currency's declines
against several other foreign currencies.
   Lacking major market-affecting news, participants were concerned
over the release of the U.S. wholesale index Friday, said a dealer
at the Bank of Tokyo who spoke anonymously.
</TEXT>
