<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-KhmerRouge 1stLd-Writethru a0462 07-11 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Khmer Rouge Leader Asks to Resign</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CLARIFY source of report. Picks up 3rd,
`Nuon Chea ...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nuon Chea, who for years held the No. 2
spot in the Khmer Rouge power hierarchy in Cambodia, has asked to
retire, a radio report said.
   The clandestine Khmer Rouge radio on Sunday quoted a letter from
Nuon Chea to Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan saying he wished to
retire once Vietnamese troops pull out of Cambodia. A transcript of
the report was seen today.
   Nuon Chea, 63, was among the small circle of communist
revolutionaries who brutalized Cambodia during their 1975-78 rule,
when hundreds of thousands of people died from Khmer Rouge
executions, famine and civil unrest.
   A Vietnamese invasion ousted the Khmer Rouge from power and the
movement has since waged guerrilla war from bases along the
Thai-Cambodian border.
   In June, Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot asked to resign from his last
official post but Western analysts were skeptical that he had really
called it quits.
   Negotiations on a Cambodian peace settlement have focused on the
need to remove Pol Pot and other of its top leaders before allowing
the Khmer Rouge it to share power with the Vietnamese-installed
government in Phnom Penh and the non-communist groups with whom it
has forged a loose resistance coalition.
   Nuon Chea formally held the No. 2 position after Pol Pot and
briefly replaced the latter as prime minister in 1976.
   Others in this inner circle, which continues to dominate the
Khmer Rouge, were Ieng Sary, Son Sen, Ta Mok, Khieu Samphan and the
wives of Pol Pot, Ieng Sary and Son Sen.
   Nuon Chea reportedly continued to have a key role after the Khmer
Rouge ouster from Phnom Penh although little is known about the
inner workings of the secretive leadership.
   The letter, dated June 7, said Nuon Chea had reached the
retirement age of 60 in 1986 but had continued to ``take part in the
resistance struggle to fight the Hanoi Vietnamese for national
liberation.''
   It did not say what position he had held.
   Vietnam has said it will pull its troops out of Cambodia by the
end of September, but Khmer Rouge media have accused Hanoi of
secretly planning to disguise Vietnamese soldiers as Cambodians
after the withdrawal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
