<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Wedtech-Wallach     07-11 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wedtech-Wallach,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meese Testifies at Wedtech Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution was given more time to prepare to
cross-examine Edwin Meese III after the former U.S. attorney general
testified that longtime friend E. Robert Wallach never sought favors
for the Wedtech Corp.
   Meese took the stand at Wallach's racketeering trial in federal
court Monday.
   Meese, who resigned as attorney general in July 1988, was faulted
in an internal Justice Department report released in January for his
efforts to help Wallach in an ill-fated, Mideast oil pipeline
proposal and to assist him with Wedtech.
   The department's Office of Professional Responsibility found
Meese had violated internal departmental standards of conduct and an
executive order on ethics.
   Meese has never been charged with any crimes in connection with
the Wedtech case.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Baruch Weiss's cross-examination of Meese
was put off until Thursday after Weiss complained to U.S. District
Judge Richard Owen that he didn't know about Meese's appearance
until 10:30 p.m. Sunday and needed more.
   During his hour-long testimony, Meese appeared relaxed.
   ``Did Mr. Wallach ask you to intervene in any way, shape or form
in the Wedtech investigation?'' asked Wallach's attorney, Gary
Neftalis.
   ``No, absolutely not,'' Meese said.
   ``Did you intervene in any way in the Wedtech investigation?''
Neftalis asked.
   ``No, I did not in any way,'' he replied.
   Wedtech, now defunct, was a small South Bronx machine shop that
grew into a $100 million defense contractor through a Small Business
Administration program that set aside contracts without competitive
bidding for minority-controlled companies.
   Evidence at earlier trials has shown that Wedtech continued to
receive the no-bid contracts through bribes even after it ceased to
be minority-owned.
   Wallach; W. Franklyn Chinn, 47, a former Wedtech board member and
onetime Meese financial adviser; and a business associate of theirs,
R. Kent London, are charged in a 21-count racketeering indictment
with extracting almost $2 million in illegal payoffs and payments
from Wedtech, including some $525,000 in alleged bribes to Wallach
to influence Meese and other government officials.
   Meese said Wallach, 55, told him in 1981 _ when Meese was a
high-ranking adviser to President Reagan _ that Wedtech would be a
good company for the administration to spotlight in its proposals
for urban enterprise zones.
   Wallach also told him about the company's efforts in 1981 to
secure an Army contract to build small engines, Meese said. Wallach
said company officials felt they were not being treated fairly by
the Army.
   Meese said he passed on the problem of the Army contract to his
staff, who referred the matter to the Office of Cabinet Affairs at
the White House. He said he had received ``probably dozens'' of
similar complaints during his time at the White House. He said he
did nothing further.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
