<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0509EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NAACP     07-11 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NAACP,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Wants Campaign to Revitalize Urban Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp
told black leaders he'd like to see a campaign to revitalize the
nation's urban neighborhoods.
   ``I think we should start right here in Motown, take those 15,000
boarded-up houses and fix them up,'' he told 3,000 NAACP delegates
Monday. ``We should ask General Motors and Chrysler and Ford to
help.''
   His speech, during the second day of civil rights group's annual
convention, only briefly touched on the investigation of alleged
influence-peddling and theft at HUD. Kemp promised the scandal would
not be used as an excuse to gut housing subsidies for low-and
moderate-income Americans.
   ``We're not going to allow it to be a reason to close down the
programs of HUD,'' he said.
   In an address marked by three standing ovations, Kemp praised the
organization as the central mover in the fight for equality for
minorities.
   Kemp, a leader in Republican efforts to recruit blacks, described
the civil rights fight as a two-step process that is half completed.
   ``Chapter One is a proud part of our country's history,'' Kemp
said. But the United States can't effectively promote itself as a
model for the world until it finishes the next stage _ achieving
economic racial equality, he said.
   Speaking next, United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber said he
was a lifetime member of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, and credited the 80-year-old group
with helping the union get a foothold in the auto industry 50 years
ago.
   The convention is drawing an array of politicians and
entertainment figures, including Vice President Dan Quayle, who
speaks Wednesday. Also appearing are 1988 Democratic presidential
aspirant Jesse Jackson, Health and Human Services Secretary Louis
Sullivan, national Democratic Chairman Ron Brown and television talk
show host Oprah Winfrey.
</TEXT>
