<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0524EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-StealthTest     07-11 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stealth Test,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stealth Watchers Celebrate Testing With Beer, Dogs and Awe</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALMDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a barren desert highway intersection,
an informal gathering of aviation buffs celebrated the B-2 stealth
bomber's first power tests with foaming beer and a rally round the
American flag.
   For weeks, an assortment of people fascinated with the all-wing,
radar-evading bomber from Northrop Corp. have been turning up around
sunrise, waiting in expectation of a glimpse of the costliest
warplane in history.
   Monday, they were satisfied, when the approximately $500
million-a-copy B-2 rolled ponderously from its secure hangar and
taxied down the Air Force Plant 42 runway at about 100 mph.
   ``It was an awesome sight to see,'' said hot dog vendor Norm
Masten as he offered up a breakfast frank and sauerkraut to a B-2
watcher. ``If I were an enemy of this country and I saw that I would
be shaking in my boots.''
   The sleek, manta-shaped strategic bomber successfully conducted
taxi and engine tests for the first time, and in public view,
stopping traffic on Sierra Highway, the main desert thoroughfare
alongside Air Force Plant 42.
   Air Force officials say more ground tests will be conducted this
week, and first flight within the next two weeks.
   People at the intersection drank beer, sipped soft drinks and
munched Brooklyn hot dogs with Coney Island onion sauce ladled out
by vendor Masten from his Little New Yorker hot dog franchise. A
large American flag whipped in the breeze from above the trailer as
Masten fixed franks and dug deep for mustard, sauerkraut and pickles.
   Masten was doing a land-office business at the corner of Sierra
Highway and Avenue `N.' An hour after the test, motorists were still
stopping to investigate the commotion where rarely anyone stirs
among the spiny Joshua trees and desert sagebrush.
   Hundreds gathered at various times, wheeling in with motor homes,
sports cars and Harley-Davidson motorcycles.
   Chief among the watchers was retired Marine John MacWhirter, who
had been out on the highway before dawn each morning for two weeks
for a glimpse of the stealth from his yellow step-van, which was
decorated with patriotic slogans, peppered with salty observations
about actress Jane Fonda and Iran.
   ``It looked like a Volkswagen with wings,'' MacWhirter declared
happily, adjusting his red USMC baseball cap. ``It looks like Buck
Rogers. It looks like Flash Gordon. I wouldn't have any anxiety at
all about it flying tomorrow.''
   Cars stopped for about a mile along the highway so people could
gawk at the strange sight of the bomber in the bright desert
sunshine.
   Jake Brown, a rangy Navy boatswains mate formerly assigned to the
battleship USS New Jersey, said that when he heard the stealth was
emerging from its hangar he telephoned work to say he'd be late.
   ``I called my boss and boogied,'' said Brown, who arrived at the
area's favorite aircraft-watching corner just in time to see the
V-shaped bomber enter the taxi way and get up to speed.
   ``We're into airplanes out here,'' Brown declared as he gazed at
familiar skies where planes such as the B-1, the U-2 and the SR-71
Blackbird often conduct tests.
   The stealth is the nation's most expensive and controversial,
coming into the Pentagon arsenal during a period of increasing
budget cuts.
   Although many congressional critics have argued that the plane is
either unnecessary or too expensive at a $70 billion program cost,
Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney has declared the stealth bomber a
linchpin of America's strategic defense policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
