<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MolestationCase     07-11 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Molestation Case,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charges Dismissed in Case Involving Right to Face Accusers in Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAVENPORT, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge dismissed child molestation
charges against a man whose conviction in the case was overturned by
the U.S. Supreme Court because he was not allowed to face his
accusers in court.
   Judge C.H. Pelton on Monday dismissed charges against Jon Avery
Coy, 38, on the recommendation of a prosecutor who cited the
reluctance of two girls to testify and the weakening of physical
evidence. The new trial was to have begun Monday.
   Coy was convicted in 1985 of two counts of lascivious acts with a
child for allegedly entering a makeshift tent where two 13-year-old
girls were camping and forcing them to perform sexual acts with him.
   Coy's attorney, John J. Wolfe, appealed on the grounds Coy was
denied his constitutional right to confront his accusers.
   When the case was first tried, a one-way screen was used to keep
the girls from seeing Coy while they testified.
   The U.S. Supreme Court voted 6-2 in 1988 to overturn the
conviction, agreeing that Coy had been denied the right to confront
his accusers. The court returned the case for a new trial.
   Following the dismissal, Coy said, ``I still maintain that I was
not the man they were looking for.''
   He has been living in Pennsylvania since his release.
   ``I'm glad it's over,'' Coy said. ``It's caused me a lot of
heartache.''
   Clinton County Attorney Larry Schultz, who entered the motion to
dismiss the case, said although his office had worked with the girls
for several months, they were reluctant to testify.
   ``The victims believe that their identities are generally unknown
at this time, and that they will, if the trial proceeds, become the
subject of some curiosity and have their lives become the subject of
some public scrutiny,'' Schultz said.
   ``The victims are now 17 years old. They have spent the past four
years attempting to put the tragedy of August 1985 behind them,''
Schultz said.
   He said the request for expanded media coverage made by two
television stations added to the state's decision. The request would
have allowed cameras to film part of the trial, although not the
girls' testimony.
   The death of Clinton Police Sgt. Lyle Smith made the state's job
more difficult, prosecutors said. The motion said Smith's testimony
was critical in establishing the location of certain physical
evidence against Coy.
   The state also discovered that hair specimens located at the
scene have disappeared since the trial.
   In the trial, the girls testified they could not see the face of
their attacker because he wore a mask and shined a flashlight in
their eyes.
   According to testimony, Coy's fingerprints were found on the
flashlight.
</TEXT>
