<FIRST>r a PM-Kemp-Pushers     07-11 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kemp-Pushers,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Opposes Law Protecting Pushers' Families</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Jack
F. Kemp has asked Congress to repeal a new law that protects the
families of drug dealers against eviction from public housing, The
New York Times reported today.
   The law jeopardizes HUD's efforts to simplify evicting the actual
drug dealers by making it ``harder for a housing authority to evict
a tenant for drug-related criminal activity than for non-payment of
rent or other violations of the tenant lease,'' Kemp wrote to
members of the House and Senate appropriations committees.
   The law poses ``a significant setback to our efforts to establish
drug-free public housing,'' the letter said.
   The law was attached to a spending bill that was passed hurriedly
last month in time for the Independence Day holiday. It took effect
June 30 when President Bush signed the spending bill.
   Congressional leaders said most members did not even realize they
had voted to require housing authorities to make sure that evictions
of drug dealers did not affect innocent members of the same
household, the Times said.
   ``The chances for reversal are excellent,'' said Rep. Bob
Traxler, D-Mich., chairman of the House Appropriations Subcommittee
on HUD and Independent Agencies.
   The eviction provision apparently was agreed to in negotiations
between Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House
Banking Committee, and Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., a member of the
Senate Appropriations Committee, the Times said.
   The newspaper quoted unidentified Congressional aides as saying
Gonzalez had been concerned that the streamlined eviction process
for drug dealers might penalize innocent people.
</TEXT>
