<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Romania 1stLd-Writethru   07-11 0698</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Romania, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0466,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Diplomat: Romania Making Military Threats</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS four grafs after 17th, `Most of...' to UPDATE with foreign
minister commenting on details of Saturday talks; Picks up 18th pvs: `The
Hungarian...'; Minor editing to trim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania is making military threats
against Hungary and soon could become a threat to the security of
its Soviet bloc neighbor, Hungary's foreign minister says.
   The allegation was the latest sign of worsening relations between
the countries, whose leaders met informally Saturday to discuss
their differences but apparently only worsened the huge rift between
them.
   Foreign Minister Gyula Horn, speaking at a news conference in
advance of President Bush's visit today to Hungary, said Romanian
media had carried ``certain military types of threats'' against
Hungary.
   Horn refused to be more specific. Romanian military publications
have reportedly devoted considerable space recently to deteriorating
Romanian-Hungarian relations.
   Horn also implied that Romania might one day threaten nuclear
action.
   He said that if a nation's leaders claim ``they are capable of
producing nuclear weapons and that in the not-too-distant future
they will start on the manufacture of medium-range missiles, this .
.. will have an impact on the neighboring nation, in this case
Hungary.''
   In April, President Nicolae Ceausescu of Romania said his country
has the potential to make nuclear weapons.
   Ceausescu and Rezso Nyers, chairman of the Hungarian Communist
Party, were involved in a ``very sharp'' round of talks on Saturday
in Bucharest, where the leaders had gathered to attend a Warsaw Pact
summit, Horn said.
   Horn had said Saturday, after he attended that meeting, that
relations between the two nations were now at ``a bottom point.''
   ``We took stock of all problems affecting our relations and the
only area where agreement was reached was that we are neighbors and
better relations are in (our mutual) interest,'' Horn had said after
the meeting.
   Horn was quoted Saturday by the state-run Hungarian news agency
MTI as saying that ``the emergence of certain military threats in
recent months also affect heavily our relations. We see such
manifestations as if the Romanians were deliberately attempting to
incite hostility.''
   However, on Monday, Horn said, ``We do not want to overdramatize
this, but we cannot let it pass either.''
   The nations have been engaged in an escalating war of words over
Hungary's allegations that Romania is mistreating its 1.7
million-member ethnic Hungarian minority.
   Hungary also is strongly opposed to a Romanian rural resettlement
plan that it says could destroy ethnic culture and tradition by
moving Hungarians out of their native villages, thousands of which
are being razed.
   Relations have been further worsened by Hungary's decision more
than one year ago to accept refugees from Romania. About 30,000
people have since fled to Hungary, most of them ethnic Hungarians.
   Romanian media have increasingly charged that Hungary is seeking
to reverse the borders established by the 1920 Treaty of Trianon,
which granted Romania the territory of Transylvania.
   Most of the ethnic Hungarians live there. For centuries, the area
was ruled by Hungary.
   However, Horn quoted an unidentified Romanian general as having
described the Trianon treaty as unjust because Hungary still retains
territories inhabited by Romanians. About 20,000 ethnic Romanians
live in Hungary, mostly in its southeast.
   Horn also said Monday that Ceausescu had ruled out a fact-finding
mission to Romania by an impartial international delegation, but
confirmed that a low-level Hungarian delegation could visit Romania.
   He said the Hungarian side at the talks asked that the delegation
be allowed to study the village-razing scheme but that Ceausescu
said the Romanians would determine the delegation's itinerary.
   Horn also said Hungary was prepared to hold a meeting of the two
premiers, but only ``if we can discuss all of the problems and
achieve some kind of agreement on their solutions.''
   The Hungarian foreign minister told reporters that no third
country, including the Soviet Union, had been asked to help improve
relations between the countries.
   Referring to Bush's visit, Horn said officials hope to give the
president ``a realistic picture of our country's politics and
economy.''
   Hungary has embraced political and economic reform and closer
ties to the West, while Romania has maintained hard-line adherence
to communism.
</TEXT>
