<FIRST>r a PM-RevampedBug     07-11 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Revamped Bug,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Happy Purloined Car is Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car thief probably didn't envision he would
become a good Samaritan by stealing a dilapidated convertible, then
fixing it up and painting it.
   The owners of the classic 1976 Volkswagen recovered it more than
three months after it was stolen from a parking lot outside their
north Dallas apartment. But Charlie and Sharon Reed hardly
recognized their beloved ``Bugaloo.''
   The banana yellow VW had undergone about $1,200 worth of repairs,
including new bumpers and fenders and other improvements. Police in
Corsicana, 45 miles southeast of Dallas, called the Reeds on
Saturday after the car was found at a used car lot there.
   ``I think they aligned the front end, too,'' Reed said of the
thieves.
   ``It used to shimmy real bad. The only thing they didn't replace
is this rubber strip on the back bumper. Shouldn't be 10, 15
dollars.''
   The 25-year-old Reed, who sells rebuilt auto engines, said the
only item missing was a toolbox his mother-in-law had given him at
Christmas.
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said Sharon Reed, a 23-year-old
receptionist at a Dallas bank who added she thought the convertible
had been lost forever.
   Mark I. Barnes, owner of B&amp;D Motors in Corsicana, said he had no
idea the bug was hot when he bought it for $2,000. He said he
installed a $100 windshield but did not repair the bumpers or
fenders or repaint the car.
   He was asking for $3,200 for the car.
   Police are seeking the man who sold the car to Barnes.
</TEXT>
