<FIRST>r a PM-BeachFugitives     07-11 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beach Fugitives,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prison Fugitives Surrender After a Day at the Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day at the beach wasn't all sun and
sand castles for two Michigan Reformatory fugitives.
   After less than 24 hours on the lam, the pair called their
jailer, collect, and asked if they could return.
   Mark Allen Fox and Charles F. Rohn, both 19, were back behind
bars at the Ionia prison Monday, facing possible escape charges,
Warden Pamela Withrow said.
   ``They said they spent the day at the beach, they were a little
scared and hungry,'' said State Trooper Larry Medendorp. ``They
hadn't eaten at all that day.''
   The pair, along with a third inmate who remained at large,
escaped early Sunday from the prison's minimum-security dormitory,
officials said. How they escaped was under investigation.
   Prison Capt. Daniel Wilson accepted the collect call late Sunday
from Fox and Rohn, who said they were at a U.S. 131 rest stop near
Grand Rapids, about 40 miles away.
   ``They asked a bunch of questions, the kind you ask when you're
scared,'' Wilson said. ``They wanted to know what happens next, and
I said that could best be determined by what they did. ... They're
young, they had no place to go, no money.''
   Troopers picked up the two at the rest area and fed them
doughnuts and milk, Medendorp said.
   Fox was serving two to 10 years for burglary in Ogemaw County,
and Rohn was sentenced to three to 10 years in St. Clair County for
assault.
   The third inmate, Robert Parm, 19, was serving 1{ to 10 years for
larceny and burglary.
   Withrow said Monday it was unknown which beach they went to, but
police said they walked and hitchhiked most of the way in the
90-degree heat.
   Withrow also said she wasn't all that surprised the two
surrendered.
   ``At the time of orientation, they are told that if they escape
they have the responsibility to turn themselves in immediately if
they are going to claim that they were under duress,'' Withrow said.
``We like to think that portion of orientation had something to do
with it.''
</TEXT>
