<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MarcosSuits     07-11 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos Suits,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Torture Suits Reinstated in U.S. Courts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court reinstated damage
suits accusing former dictator Ferdinand Marcos of ordering the
imprisonment and torture of numerous Philippine citizens.
   The suits had been dismissed by federal judges in Hawaii and
California on the grounds that Marcos' actions were ``acts of
state,'' immune from lawsuit under a doctrine that courts in one
nation cannot judge the sovereign acts of another.
   But the 9th U.S. Court of Appeals ruled last year that the ``act
of state'' doctrine did not protect a deposed ruler like Marcos,
because the doctrine's main purpose is to avoid entangling the
courts in delicate foreign policy questions.
   That ruling revived a suit by the current Philippine government,
headed by President Corazon Aquino, which accuses Marcos of looting
the Philippines during his 20-year rule and hiding his wealth abroad.
   On Monday, the court cited the same ruling in ordering the
private damage suits reinstated.
   ``The issues raised, although extraordinarily complex, are within
the capacity of the courts to resolve,'' the three-judge panel said.
   Marcos, who fled a popular uprising in the Philippines in
February 1986, lives in Hawaii and has been hospitalized with a
grave illness since January.
   Monday's ruling involved five lawsuits, three in Honolulu and two
in San Francisco, that included accusations of illegal arrest,
torture and other abuse.
</TEXT>
