<FIRST>u i PM-China-Journalist 2ndLd-Writethru a0460 07-11 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Journalist, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0460,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwanese Reporter Deported, Says Top Dissident Arrested</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with journalist's details of capture, details
on possible arrest of dissident; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese journalist, freed and deported from
China today after being held eight days, said Chinese authorities
told him they arrested a key student leader from the crushed
pro-democracy movement.
   The whereabouts of the student leader, Wang Dan, have been
unknown since he met with the journalist, Huang Teh-pei, in Beijing
on July 2. There had been unconfirmed reports of his arrest.
   Huang, a reporter for Taiwan's Independence Evening Post, told
reporters in Hong Kong that officials of the Beijing Municipal State
Security Bureau informed him of Wang's arrest after Huang himself
was detained on July 3.
   ``They told me, `Tell the truth because everyone else has been
caught, your friend Wang Dan and your driver,''' Huang said.
   Huang said he had met Wang to discuss the dissident's options for
fleeing China, but the two split up when they realized they were
being followed by security agents.Huang's driver and Wang stayed
together and were chased by the agents, he said.
   Huang also said interrogators confronted him with information
only he and his driver would know, leading him to believe that Wang
had been arrested.
   ``It's very possible it's because of me'' that the student leader
was caught, he said.
   Huang was freed ``on account of his good attitude in admitting
his guilt,'' China's official Xinhua News Agency quoted a spokesman
for the Municipal State Security Bureau as saying.
   Xinhua said Chinese authorities also considered ``the overall
interest of the relations between the two sides of the Taiwan
Strait.''
   Huang was charged with violating martial law regulations that ban
foreign, Hong Kong and Taiwanese journalists from reporting on the
political turmoil in Beijing.
   Xinhua said he ``concocted rumors, filed news stories designed to
instigate turmoil and counterrevolutionary revolt, and drew maps of
the deployment of martial law enforcement troops.''
   Xinhua also said Huang, who arrived in Beijing in June with a
tourist visa, made secret contacts July 2 with a leader of the
illegal Autonomous Student Union of Beijing Universities and planned
to assist the student in fleeing the mainland. It did not name the
student, who was presumed to be Wang.
   Since the government crackdown began last month, some leaders of
the pro-democracy movement have escaped to the West to avoid arrest.
Others have been arrested and still others are in hiding.
   Huang said that throughout his captivity, interrogators demanded
that he confess to breaking the law. He said he acknowledged most
allegations, but refused to comply when authorities ``wanted me to
say I was a spy.''
   He said he was handcuffed and forced into a car, but added,
``There was no corporal punishment, they did not hit me.''
   Huang said he would remain in Hong Kong until another reporter
from his newspaper, Hsu Lu, left Beijing. Taiwan radio said Chinese
security informed Miss Hsu early today to leave the country within
48 hours.
   The rival Nationalist government on Taiwan bans all official
contacts with the mainland but in the past two years has relaxed
restrictions on travel and visits by sports delegations and other
non-governmental groups.
   Lee Ching-hua, secretary general of Taiwan's Olympic Committee,
said Monday he had received a cable from his counterpart in China
promising an early release for Huang because ``we cherish the easing
of tension across the (Taiwan) Straits and have fully considered the
wishes of Taiwan's leaders.''
   Hundreds of unarmed civilians were killed June 3-4 when troops
ran protesters out of central Beijing, crushing the student-led
pro-democracy movement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
