<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0513 07-11 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0513,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: FIXES previous eds note to CORRECT that only PMs separate was
a0476 on Blanc.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Mel Blanc</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mel Blanc, who entranced generations of
cartoon viewers with voices ranging from Bugs Bunny to Porky Pig,
died Monday from complication of heart disease. He was 81.
   Starting in 1937, he became part of Warner Bros.' cartoon studio,
which produced one short feature subject each week.
   Blanc was also a regular on radio's ``The Jack Benny Show.''
   His first Warner Bros. character was a drunken bull in the Looney
Tunes short ``Picador Porky.'' Blanc took over the role of Porky Pig
in ``Porky's Duck Hunt'' and created Daffy Duck.
   He introduced Bugs Bunny in the 1940 short ``A Wild Hare.''
   He invented the voices of such characters as Woody Woodpecker,
Speedy Gonzalez, Pepe Le Pew, Tasmanian Devil, Road Runner, Foghorn
Leghorn, Heathcliffe the cat, Speed Buggy, Yosemite Sam and that
Oscar-winning rabbit Bugs Bunny.
   He also did voices for Elmer Fudd, the Roadrunner and numerous
other characters he performed on 850 cartoons for Warner Bros.'
Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies.
   Blanc's last cartoon contribution came with 1988's popular
animation-live action film, ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' in which he
did the voices of Daffy, Tweety, Bugs and Sylvester. He wrote an
autobiography that year, ``That's Not All, Folks: My Life in the
Golden Age of Cartoons and Radio.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Tommy Trinder</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tommy Trinder, 80, a comedian whose nimble,
irreverent wit endeared him to generations of Britons, died Monday
after a long illness.
   Trinder became a favorite at London clubs, theaters and dance
halls, and in 1938 made the first of many appearances at the
Palladium. During World War II he entertained British soldiers all
over the world, and later toured the United States.
   Trinder appeared on the popular TV program ``In Town Tonight''
and the long-running British Broadcasting Corp. radio panel game
``Does The Team Think?'' He was also the host of Independent
Television's ``Sunday Night at the London Palladium.''
   His movie credits included ``The Foreman Went to France'' in 1942
and ``Fiddlers Three'' in 1944.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>J. Bruno Benziger</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN ELLEN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J. Bruno Benziger Sr., co-founder of
Glen Ellen Winery, which grew rapidly in the last eight years to
become one of California's biggest wine producers, died Monday of
heart failure, the company announced. He was 64.
   After marketing modestly price wines for family-owned
import-export outfit Park, Benziger &amp; Co., Benziger moved from New
York to Sonoma County in 1981 where he planned to become a
semi-retired farmer. His son Michael, who learned winemaking in
California, convinced his father to invest in a vineyard.
   They initially hoped to sell 50,000 cases by 1990 but achieved
that in the first 18 months. The winery expects to sell 3.2 million
cases this year, making Glen Ellen the second largest wine producer
in Sonoma County behind Sebastiani Vineyards.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Albert Lawrence</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Coast Guard Capt. Albert A.
Lawrence, a professor emeritus at the Coast Guard Academy and former
teacher at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, died Saturday.
   Born in 1905 at Cuba, N.Y., Lawrence taught for 23 years at the
U.S. Coast Guard Academy in New London, Conn., retiring in 1966 as
Dean of the Faculty there. He was credited with expanding the
Academy's curriculum and was inducted as professor emeritus in 1988,
the second person ever to be so honored.
   He also taught for eight years at M.I.T.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edgar Anderson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edgar Anderson, a San Jose State
University history professor who was named the Outstanding Educator
of America in 1972, died in an auto crash Wednesday. He was 69.
   Anderson was killed when the car he was driving was hit by a
truck near King City in central California. His passenger, Latvian
journalist Drosma Jurjeva, 33, also was killed.
   A Baltic and northern European scholar, Anderson came from Latvia
in 1944 and had been a member of the university's faculty since
1957. He wrote more than 14 books, was fluent in five languages and
was a regular broadcaster over the Voice of America.
</TEXT>
