<FIRST>u i PM-China 1stLd-Writethru   07-11 0969</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0475,0989</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Ousted Party Chief Still Under Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with party chief meeting Hong Kong
leaders, expelled reporters leaving; Picks up 4th pvs: `When the ...';
SUBS grafs 21-24, `China on ... crackdown began' with four grafs to conform;
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government spokesman today said ousted Communist
Party chief Zhao Ziyang is still under investigation for allegedly
supporting the pro-democracy movement, and refused to rule out that
he might be put on trial.
   Yuan Mu, the only high-ranking government official who has met
with reporters since the army crushed the movement June 3-4, told a
news conference that ``at this stage'' Zhao only was accused of
making mistakes that could be dealt with within the party.
   ``However, the problem is still under investigation,'' Yuan said.
``How the problem will finally be dealt with will be decided
according to the findings of the investigation.''
   In other developments, an American reporter and a Taiwanese
journalist left China after being ordered out, and authorities gave
a second Taiwanese reporter 48 hours to leave. All were accused of
violating restrictions on reporting.
   The new party chief, Jiang Zemin, met with a group of Hong Kong
leaders this afternoon but both sides refused comment on the
discussions.
   Jiang was expected to try to reassure Hong Kong residents
frightened by the mainland crackdown that China would preserve their
capitalist system for 50 years after Britain returns the colony in
1997. However, China also has called on Hong Kong to stop supporting
fugitive pro-democracy activists.
   When the party Central Committee ousted Zhao on June 24 from the
post he held for more than two years, it accused him of ``splitting
the party'' and supporting the student-led protests for a freer
society.
   However, Beijing Mayor Chen Xitong charged in a recently
disclosed major speech that Zhao ``connived at'' and facilitated the
gradual escalation of the protests from April to June, and that his
aides collaborated with the students in efforts to overthrow the
government.
   The report stopped just short of accusing Zhao of taking part in
the alleged coup conspiracy by those under him. Such a charge would
have to be followed by a trial, which might force party leaders to
reveal details of top-level decision-making and might arouse new
anti-party sentiment.
   Although Zhao did not enjoy wide personal popularity, he has
become a symbol of the crushed reformist camp.
   Only senior leader Deng Xiaoping, who once sponsored Zhao's rise
to power, could make the crucial decision of putting him on trial.
   The last time a top official was accused of plotting a coup in
China was in 1976, when moderates and generals arrested the radical
Gang of Four that led the Cultural Revolution. They were put on
public trial in 1980 and are serving life sentences.
   Recent official media reports also have accused Zhao of serious
ideological mistakes, including de-emphasizing the role of the
proletariat and neglecting party building.
   At his news conference, Yuan blamed Zhao for the endemic
corruption within party ranks, saying that under his leadership the
fight against corruption was relaxed.
   Yuan said martial law, imposed in central Beijing on May 20,
could not be lifted yet because ``the struggle has not ended. Some
guns still remain in society and that will be a cause of further
unrest.''
   He insisted, however, that foreign tourists and businessmen could
consider Beijing secure and said it would be unwise to make lifting
of martial law a condition for returning to the city.
   Thousands of Chinese-based foreign businessmen and their families
fled Beijing in the week after the army cleared central Beijing of
protesters, killing hundreds. Most have yet to return.
   Many joint venture companies, which provide capital and
technology China needs badly to modernize, remain virtually shut
down or operate at much reduced levels.
   ``Of course there will be a time limit for martial law, but even
I can't say exactly when that will be,'' Yuan said. He said it would
be lifted ``when things have completely returned to normal and when
we feel that all the problems of the rebellion that need to be
resolved have been.''
   He said sanctions imposed by some Western countries to protest
the crackdown ``will cause some temporary trouble'' for China's
ailing economy. Among the problems are inflation that Yuan said was
running at 25.5 percent in the first half of the year, and growing
budget and trade deficits.
   ``But the Chinese people will not yield to these pressures
because of these troubles,'' he said. ``On the contrary, it will
inspire a spirit of plain living and hard struggle and relying on
our own efforts. So in the long run it will do our country good.''
   Yuan refused to disclose figures for the number of people
arrested since the crackdown began. The Associated Press has counted
more than 2,000 arrests nationwide according to official media
reports, but Chinese sources said that many were believed to have
been arrested in the capital alone.
   China today expelled a Taiwanese reporter who was arrested a week
ago after he reported meeting with a key fugitive student leader.
   Huang Teh-pei of the Independence Evening Post said after
arriving in Hong Kong that authorities told him they had arrested
the student, Wang Dan.
   The Ministry of State Security ordered a second Independence
Evening Post reporter, Hsu Lu, to leave within 48 hours, the
People's Broadcasting Station said. It said she was accused of
violating martial law, conducting illegal interviews and filing
distorted reports.
   A reporter for the U.S.-run Voice of America, Mark Hopkins, also
flew to Hong Kong today after being accused of violating martial
law. He was the second VOA reporter and the seventh Western reporter
ordered out since the crackdown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
