<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0731EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NightStalker     07-11 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Rests in `Night Stalker' Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense rested its case in the ``Night
Stalker'' mass murder trial after presenting a photograph of
defendant Richard Ramirez that they say proves he couldn't have
committed two of the attacks.
   The string of slayings terrorized Southern California four years
ago.
   Ramirez's lawyers entered into evidence Monday a blown-up color
photograph of Ramirez they say is evidence he was in Texas at the
time of two of the attacks.
   The lawyers contend the photo of Ramirez with his parents and a
niece was taken on May 25, 1985, the day of his niece's first
communion in El Paso, Texas.
   The suspect's father, Julian Ramirez Tapia, testified earlier
that his son arrived two days before the event and stayed for eight
days, placing him out of town when the attacks occurred.
   Earlier prosecution testimony had linked Ramirez to the murder of
Mabel Bell and the attempted murder of her roommate between May 29
and June 1, 1985, and the rape of another woman on May 30, 1985.
   Ramirez's sister-in-law, Maria Torres, testified Monday that she
saw Ramirez in El Paso on May 25 and May 29, 1985. She said she
remembered because May 29 was ``the one-month anniversary after I
separated from my husband.''
   Raymundo Pantoja, a friend of Ramirez's father, also testified
that he saw Ramirez on May 25, 1985.
   The defense's contention that Ramirez was a victim of mistaken
identity was challenged during the trial by prosecution witnesses,
including a local dentist who said he treated Ramirez on May 30,
1985.
   Ramirez is charged with 13 murders and 30 other felonies in
connection with the noctural attacks.
   The 29-year-old drifter and self-described devil worshipper was
arrested Aug. 31, 1985, after a crowd of East Los Angeles residents
recognized him from news photographs and captured him as he
allegedly tried to steal a car.
   Closing arguments were scheduled for Wednesday.
</TEXT>
