<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Politics     07-11 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Politics,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir May Try to Rescue Government With New Peace Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir may try to keep
his governing coalition from collapsing by proposing a new Cabinet
vote on Israel's plan for seeking peace with the Palestinians, his
spokesman said today.
   The Labor Party, partner of Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc in the
coalition, has threatened to quit the Cabinet and force new national
elections.
   In a resolution passed Monday by its 120-member Leadership
Bureau, Labor accused Likud of torpedoing chances of starting peace
talks and added ``there is no room under these circumstances for the
continuation of the government.''
   Labor's decision came in response to the tough new conditions
adopted by Likud on the proposal for elections in the occupied
territories.
   A Labor pullout would require ratification by its decision-making
Central Committee, which was expected to meet within three weeks.
   Shamir's peace plan proposes that 1.7 million Palestinians in the
occupied territories elect representatives to talks with Israel
about an interim period of limited self-rule in these areas. The
final status of the territories would be decided in later talks.
   Likud hard-liners subsquently toughened the plan with more
conditions, including a demand that elections be delayed pending an
end to the 19-month Palestinian uprising in the disputed lands and
that Arabs in east Jerusalem be barred from voting.
   Likud also called for the continued construction of Jewish
settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strip and said it would never
agree to Palestinian statehood in these areas.
   Despite the tensions that Likud's program has generated, some
Israeli analysts have predicted the dispute could be resolved before
Labor convenes its Central Committee.
   ``The time lapse can give Shamir and his allies breathing space
to erase the results of Likud's meeting,'' Political commentator
Akiva Eldar wrote in the Haaretz daily.
   Shamir was making efforts to placate Labor, and was considering a
new vote on the peace plan which could remove the party's rationale
for leaving the government, Haaretz and four other newspapers said
in front-page stories.
   The news reports said the vote would likely be on a proposal put
forward by Industry Minister Ariel Sharon calling for adding to the
peace initiative the hard-line conditions that Likud adopted as
party policy.
   The Cabinet would likely defeat the proposals, reinforcing the
peace plan without condtions, the Israeli newspapers said. The
Cabinet first passed the plan by a 20-6 vote in May.
   Ahimeir, Shamir's spokesman, confirmed in a telephone interview
that Sharon's proposals for a Cabinet vote were on the premier's
desk.
   ``You could say that the prime minister's office should be
interested in holding such a vote,'' Ahimeir said.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III referred to the Likud
principles as ``not helpful'' last week and said Monday he wanted
assurances about Israel's intentions.
   Likud and Labor formed their governing coalition in December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
