<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-Singapore     07-11 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-Singapore,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tens of Thousands Line Up in Bid to Emigrate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 25,000 people, many fearful of life in
this British colony when it reverts to Chinese rule, flocked today
to take advantage of a new policy in Singapore relaxing immigration
requirements.
   Thousands more were turned away because of the huge crush of
people.
   Communist China's suppression of its student-led movement for
democracy has sparked fears among many of Hong Kong's 5.7 million
people of their fate when Britain returns the colony to Chinese rule
in 1997.
   More than 45,000 people emigrated from the colony last year, and
this year even more are expected to leave.
   A line of about 10,000 people, standing five abreast, stretched
for blocks in downtown Hong Kong when officials at Singapore
Management Corp. decided to stop handing out applications for
permanent residence in Singapore.
   The government-owned company, set up several years ago to entice
well-educated and rich Hong Kong residents to Singapore, said that
from now on it only would accept applications by mail.
   The crush at the company came one day after Singapore announced
it was relaxing requirements for Hong Kong residents to become
permanent residents in the republic.
   Britain has said repeatedly that it will not give Hong Kong's
people the right to live in Britain, causing many to look elsewhere
for a haven.
   Michael Lim, general manager of the Singapore company, said an
``overwelming demand for application forms'' forced the company to
close its offices.
   ``In the interest of public safety, we have decided to close the
booth ... and ask applicants to apply by post,'' Lim said.
   Another spokesman for the company said today that 15,000
application forms for permanent residency had been handed out before
the offices were shut down. Police said about 10,000 people were
turned away and that there were no incidents of violence.
   Singapore's new permanent residence plan lowers educational and
monetary prerequisites.
   The previous plan was limited to those with a university degree
or the professional equivalent and enterpreneurs willing to invest
$512,000 in Singapore.
   Now, any workers with at least five years of employment will be
allowed to apply as well businessmen who invest less than $500,000
provided their businesses are approved by the Economic Development
Board.
   Singapore has decided to liberalize its rules to compete with
developed countries in recruiting skilled workers, technicians and
professionals.
   ``Singapore's growing economy requires more such people than are
being produced domestically,'' said a statement from the Singapore
government. ``This liberalization applies to immigrants from all
sources, whatever their ethnic background, so long as they can be
integrated into Singapore society without upsetting the present
balance in its multiracial character.''
   Still, it is significant that most of the applicants were
expected to be ethnic Chinese.
   Of Singapore's 2.6 million people, 76 percent are Chinese, 15
percent Malays, 6 percent Indians and the rest Eurasians and
Europeans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
