<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--FlagNoise     07-11 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Flag Noise,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Drops Case Against Flag-Flapping Veteran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge threw out the criminal conviction
of a Navy veteran whose flapping American flag bothered a neighbor
after the man agreed to put up a quieter, cotton flag.
   ``The flag is not making any noise any more ever since he put up
a cotton flag,'' Assistant City Attorney Stephen Ryan told District
Judge Joe Galvan in asking that the case be dismissed.
   Galvan tossed out the conviction on Monday, wiping Lee Bach's
record clean. He had been convicted of violating the city's noise
law three weeks ago after a neighbor complained that Bach's nylon
flag was too noisy on windy days.
   ``It's unfortunate that something as important and sacred to all
of us as the American flag should create turmoil in the community,''
Galvan said.
   ``I'm satisfied,'' Bach said afterward, although he said he still
may fly his nylon flag on occasion. Most of the 100 people in court
applauded Galvan's ruling.
</TEXT>
