<FIRST>r a PM-CarrierCharged     07-11 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carrier Charged,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mailman Charged in Mail Hoarding Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter carrier has been charged with delaying
delivery of more than 2{ tons of mail and stashing it in his home
and yard for years.
   John Cade surrendered Monday and appeared for a preliminary
hearing on charges of delaying mail and theft of postal property
before U.S. Magistrate Richard Harvey, who set a $5,000 unsecured
bond.
   Some 6,550 pounds of mail was discovered at Cade's home in
Boulder after someone reported a carrier dumping mail into a trash
receptacle at the residence, said an affidavit by Postal Inspector
Lee Morris.
   Two postal supervisors found more than 200 pieces of mail in the
trash and observed piles in the yard. Cade admitted putting the mail
at his residence and agreed to allow officers to search the home and
recover the mail, the affidavit said.
   Most of the mail is bulk business mail and is undeliverable and
authorities are considering some way to reimburse the senders for
their loss, said John Freeman, chief postal inspector for Denver.
   Cade's cluttered house and yard contained thousands of pieces of
mail, including first-, second-, third- and fourth-class mail,
according to the court document.
   A preliminary hearing in the case was set for July 26.
</TEXT>
