<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     07-11 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Arrest 1,000 Suspected Sinhlaese Extremists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops have arrested 1,000 suspected
Sinhalese extremists during raids on insurgent hideouts in the
capital and three central districts, the government said today.
   The troops recovered land mines, guns, ammunition and military
uniforms during the raids on Sunday and Monday, an Information
Department statement said.
   A short-wave band radio transmitter also was confiscated in the
southern Hungama town, 85 miles south of Colombo, the statement said.
   Besides Colombo, the operations were carried out in the districts
of Badulla, Kandy and Moneragala, it said. The suspects were
detained for questioning, it said. No further details were given.
   The raids were part of a government crackdown on members of the
left-wing People's Liberation Front, who have been fighting to
topple President Ranasinghe Premadasa's government.
   The Sinhalese extremists began their anti-government campaign two
years ago to protest peace overtures made to Tamil rebels. The
Sinhalese militants said too many concessions to the minority Tamils
were made in an Indian-Sri Lankan peace accord that tried to end the
Tamil rebellion.
   The Sinhalese front is also believed to have sponsored a
crippling one-month transport workers' strike.
   Transport Minister Wijepala Mendis said Monday the strike by the
40,000 workers of the state-owned public transport company had been
broken. He said ``a fair percentage'' of workers reported for duty
after the government announced that strikers would be arrested.
   In an attempt to crush civil unrest, Premadasa imposed a
nationwide state of emergency June 20, giving security forces wide
powers to arrest and detain without legal obligations.
   On Thursday, the government said it ordered troops and police to
shoot saboteurs and those putting up anti-government posters. A
censorship campaign was also imposed the same day.
   The Sinhalese extremists also have protested the presence of
Indian troops, invited to maintain the Indian-Sri Lankan accord and
break the Tamil rebellion, saying it compromised the country's
independence.
   Premadasa's request to India to withdraw the troops has failed to
appease the Sinhalese radicals.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
allege discrimination in jobs and education by the Sinhalese, who
constitute 75 percent of the population and control the government
and the military.
</TEXT>
