<FIRST>r a PM-FamilySlayings     07-11 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Slayings,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent To Killing Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing his wife, mother
and three children 18 years ago pleaded innocent at his arraignment
and bail was set at $5 million.
   Hundreds of curiosity seekers, many with strong memories of the
macabre 1971 killings in a Westfield mansion, packed the Union
County courtroom for a look at the man arrested in Virginia on a tip
from a television viewer.
   The man authorities say is John E. List, 63, pleaded innocent
Monday to five counts of murder.
   The man, who says he is Robert P. Clark, did not speak during the
10-minute hearing. He was handcuffed and clad in prison-issue khaki
pants and shirt and wore brown plastic slippers.
   Superior Court Judge William Wertheimer set a trial date for Dec.
4.
   Clark's attorney, Elijah Miller, deputy chief of the county
Public Defender's Office, said prosecutors must prove his client is
List.
   ``Robert Clark is the name he was extradited under, is the name
he's listed under in jail,'' he said. ``The state is trying to prove
he is someone else.''
   Clark was arrested June 1 in Richmond, Va., on a tip from a
viewer of the national television program, ``America's Most
Wanted,'' which 11 days earlier had run a segment focusing on List.
   Officials say List, an accountant and devout Lutheran known for
his meticulousness and mild manners, killed his family because he
believed it was the only way to save them from leading a life of
sin. They say fingerprints and a scar prove List and Clark are the
same man.
   The bodies of List's wife, Helen, 45, and their children,
Patricia, 16, John Jr. 15, and Frederick, 13, were not found until a
month after the deaths, laid side-by-side in the ballroom of their
19-room mansion. The body of his 85-year-old mother, Alma, was
discovered in an upstairs bedroom.
</TEXT>
