<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     07-11 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Shot Dead in Gangland-Style Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men masked with Arab kaffiyeh scarves killed
a 28-year-old Palestinian in a shooting today on a downtown street
in the occupied Gaza Strip, witnesses said.
   Also today, an American woman injured in a bus crash blamed on a
Palestinian joined the Israeli government in calling for the United
States to declare it an act of terrorism.
   The army said the Gaza Strip slaying was carried out by
Palestinians and is under investigation. It comes amid increasing
attacks by Palestinians on fellow Arabs accused of collaborating
with Israeli authorities.
   In the West Bank, a general strike was called in Ramallah and
El-Bireh to protest the shooting deaths of three Palestinian youths
by Israeli army and security agents Monday, Arab reports said.
   ``Killing our people will not stop the intefadeh!'' slogans
painted on walls in the towns north of Jerusalem declared today,
using the Arabic term for the 19-month uprising against Israeli
occupation.
   A military spokesman confirmed two West Bank deaths and said the
army is checking the third report.
   The deaths around Ramallah would bring the toll to 558
Palestinians killed in the revolt. Thirty-five Israelis also have
been killed.
   In Gaza City, car painter Faqar Mohammed Hassan was gunned down
by two masked attackers who got out of a white car and, without
warning, pumped at least eight shots into the victim's face and
chest, witnesses said.
   The victim was not known to be involved in political activities,
but two of his brothers are in jail for being members of the
outlawed Moslem fundamentalist organization Islamic Jihad, Arab
reports said.
   The U.S. victim of the bus attack, Pella Fingersh of Kansas City,
Kan., made her appeal at a news conference arranged by the Foreign
Ministry, which has been pressing for Washington to make a stronger
statement on the bus attack.
   ``It pains me to think that America did not say this is a
terrorist attack,'' said Mrs. Fingersh, 47.
   Fourteen people were killed and 27 injured Thursday when police
said Abdel Hadi Ghanem grabbed the steering wheel and forced the bus
into a deep ravine.
   Police say they believe Ghanem, 23, acted on his own. He
reportedly told investigators he wanted to avenge a brother's
beating by Israeli soldiers.
   The U.S. State Department on Friday called the incident tragic
and senseless.
   Today, U.S. Embassy spokesman Donald Cofman said in Tel Aviv that
the State Department since has decided the incident fits its
definition of terror as ``premeditated, politically motivated
violence directed against civilians.''' An Israeli court meanwhile
convicted a teen-age Palestinian girl of manslaughter in the fatal
shooting of a teen-age Jewish seminary student in a Jerusalem park
on June 2, 1988, Israel radio reported today.
   It quoted the girl, unidentified because she is a minor, as
telling the court she attacked the Israeli to gain acceptance in
Arab society where she was rejected because she had Israeli friends.
Sentencing was delayed.
</TEXT>
