<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0492 07-11 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Israeli Soldiers Wounded in Guerrilla Ambush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Israel reinforcing security.
Picks up 2nd graf, `The patrol ....'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HASBAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas ambushed an Israeli army
patrol in south Lebanon early today and two soldiers were wounded in
a firefight that was followed by an Israeli artillery barrage, army
and security sources said.
   Israel later bolstered its forces in south Lebanon with about 150
soldiers in a mechanized force armed with tanks and armored cars,
howitzers and surface-to-air missiles, the sources said. Troops also
sealed all four gateways linking Israel's buffer zone in south
Lebanon to the rest of the nation, they said.
   The patrol came under fire in the Hasbaya region on the northern
edge of Israel's self-declared security zone, said one security
source on condition of anonymity.
   ``The two wounded soldiers were evacuted by an Israeli helicopter
under the cover of heavy artillery barrage,'' the source said.
   An army spokesman in Jerusalem said one soldier was wounded
slightly, the other moderately. No casualties were reported among
the guerrillas, whom the source would not identify.
   The army fired more than 400 rounds of artillery into areas north
of the zone, the heaviest barrage in years, security sources said.
The barrage was aimed at areas around the towns of Hasbaya and
Maidoun, they said.
   The army spokesman in Jerusalem said the fighting occurred north
of the security zone and came during the army's second thrust
outside of the zone in two days.
   Sources in south Lebanon said, however, that the fight apparently
broke out as the army withdrew from the first operation, a raid
against Hezbollah, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem militia backed by Iran.
   Israeli troops and their allies in the South Lebanon Army militia
had raided guerrilla hideouts around the village of Dellaya, three
miles north of the buffer zone, killing three guerrillas.
   The three-hour raid was triggered by an attack on the zone
earlier in the day by Palestinian and leftist Lebanese guerrillas.
   The Lebanese reports said the attacking guerrillas were from two
Palestinian factions, the Popular Struggle Front and the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, and the Syrian Socialist
Nationalist Party, a leftist Lebanese militia.
   Israel retained control over the 6-to-10-mile-deep buffer zone in
1985, as it withdrew from Lebanon, to protect its northern border
from guerrilla attacks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
