<FIRST>r w PM-Hecht-Bahamas 2ndLd-Writethru a0568 07-11 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hecht-Bahamas, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0568,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Senate Colleagues Oppose Hecht's Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts graf 2, But other, and grafs 6-10, Disagreeing, with
senators defending Hecht. Removes last four grafs pvs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Graham said today former colleague
Chic Hecht does not deserve to be U.S. ambassador to the Bahamas
because he lacks the qualities needed to work with the island nation
to combat drug trafficking.
   But other senators said Hecht's record has been distorted and
that he is fully qualified by his Senate service and a banking and
retail career to serve as a U.S. ambassador.
   ``It is difficult to speak in opposition to the confirmation of a
former colleague,'' Graham, D-Fla., said at the outset of debate on
confirmation of the former Nevada senator to the ambassadorial post.
   But Graham said members of the Senate ``stand in a unique
position to evaluate whether he has the requisite qualities'' for
the ambassadorship, which involves coordinating the U.S. anti-drug
effort with Bahamian leaders.
   ``I regretfully come to the conclusion that this individual does
not meet the standards that I believe our nation should set, that he
does not send to the world the statement of our commitment to
victory in the war on drugs,'' Graham said. ``...He does not
deserve, nor does our nation deserve to be represented by him, in
the Bahamas.''
   Disagreeing, Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., said his former homestate
colleague was jesting when he said he looked forward to service in
the Bahamas because of the pleasant lifestyle, golf, gambling and
fishing.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said Hecht had merely been attempting
to say that both the Bahamas and Las Vegas, Nev., have
multi-million-dollar tourist industries of great importance to their
economies.
   ``It is not something to be twisted and misrepresented and
hee-hawed by journalistic pygmies in the news media,'' Helms said,
declaring that Hecht has been attacked only because of his record as
a conservative.
   ``Chic is a remarkable man,'' Helms said. ``He is probably the
brightest man to serve in the Senate.''
   Reid, Helms and Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho, all said that Hecht's
experience as the owner of a Nevada bank will serve him well in
dealing with a situation in the Bahamas in which drug traffickers
are said to use local banks to launder their illicit profits.
   Graham is leading the fight against confirmation of Hecht, known
for his malapropisms while serving in Congress. Hecht is opposed by
some former colleagues who say they are worried that he would be
more interested in golf than in waging war on drugs.
   Opponents are defying a tradition that the Senate almost never
turns on a former colleague named to a post requiring confirmation.
That tradition was severely dented earlier this year when the Senate
rejected the nomination of former Sen. John Tower, R-Texas, to be
secretary of defense.
   But even the semblance of opposition is unusual. Graham contended
in advance of today's debate that Hecht _ whom he called a ``barrel
of gaffes'' _ deserved opposition because he is known more for
misstatements than diplomatic and law enforcement expertise.
   Graham has said that the next U.S. ambassador to the Bahamas must
play a ``vital, operational role'' in ending the island nation's
role as a transit point for narcotics destined for American streets.
   In his floor speech today, Graham said the American ambassador to
the Bahamas must spend considerable time in coordinating drug
enforcement activities.
   ``We need to have in that critical position ... not only someone
who has the requisite background in diplomatic and foreign policy,
but we also need someone who can give to the citizens of the Bahamas
... confidence in his or her ability to lead an effective effort in
the war against drugs,'' he said.
   At confirmation hearings before the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee earlier this year, Hecht drew criticism for his
lighthearted approach to his appointment.
   ``I am sure I will feel at home in the Bahamas,'' Hecht said.
``I've been involved in gambling in Nevada, and I've been involved
in banking for 25 years ...
   ``Also, I understand it is a nice lifestyle,'' he said. ``I love
golf and they have a lot of nice golf courses and good fishing.''
   Hecht, 60, who spent most of his working life in the women's
apparel industry, was defeated last year in his bid for a second
six-year Senate term.
   During the campaign he was quoted as saying he would oppose any
``nuclear suppository'' that could prove risky to his state.
</TEXT>
