<FIRST>r w PM-GunLiability 1stLd-Writethru a0426 07-11 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gun Liability, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>District Council Drops Plan to Vote on Proposed Anti-Gun Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: TOPS with 7 new grafs on bill withdrawal, picks up 6th graf
pvs., ``Richard Gardner...,'' edits to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia Council today dropped
plans to vote on a bill that would make gun manufacturers
financially liable for injuries and deaths caused in shootings, amid
concern that the legislation might interfere with existing laws.
   Wilhelmina Rolark, chairwoman of the council's judiciary
committee, withdrew the bill to allow for further study of any
potential conflict. Today's session was the last before the council
goes into summer recess, which means the matter cannot be
reconsidered until September.
   ``The intention of this legislation is to complement and not to
interfere with efforts in judicial forums,'' Mrs. Rolark said. ``In
order that the council staff can do some further work on existing
strict liability and tort laws, I am withdrawing the bill.''
   The bill, the first of its kind in the nation, faced an uncertain
reception in Congress, which reviews all laws passed by the council.
   Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., a frequent critic of the district
government, has likened the bill to an attempt ``to hold Black and
Decker responsible for `The Texas Chainsaw Massacre.'''
   Walter Fauntroy, the district's non-voting delegate to Congress,
warned the council in a letter Monday that the bill would stir up
too much trouble in Congress.
   The council gave the measure preliminary approval by an 8-4 vote
two weeks ago. The measure was created in an attempt to slow the
city's drug-driven record murder rate.
   Richard Gardner, state and local affairs director of the National
Rifle Association, said, ``The bill is unconstitutional because it
places an extreme limitation on interstate commerce, and the federal
government is the only body that can regulate interstate commerce.''
   City Corporation Counsel Frederick D. Cooke also raised concerns
about the interstate commerce restrictions during city council
hearings last month on the measure.
   Council Chairman David A. Clarke, one of the bill's sponsors,
said the district's handgun liability bill resembles restrictions on
other products in other states.
   ``Historically, other states have regulated things like alcohol,
and the closest thing is that some have restricted dynamite,''
Clarke said. ``The only thing different about this bill is that it
is handguns.''
   The liability bill is just one of several proposals made as
drug-related crime has increased in the nation's capital.
   City officials hope to hire 1,200 new police officers by 1991,
more than half of them funded by the federal government.
   Through Monday, 228 persons had been killed in Washington in
1989, compared with 159 by the same time last year. In 1988, a
record 372 persons were killed.
   Police blame more than 60 percent of the slayings on drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     07-11 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Admonishes Two Cabinet Ministers for Remarks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno today scolded two Cabinet
ministers for harming public trust in politics after one called
women ``useless'' in politics, and the other kindled fears of higher
taxes, officials said.
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Masajuro Shiokawa told reporters that Uno
admonished Hisao Horinouchi, minister of agriculture, forestry and
fisheries, and Shigenobu Sakano, the home affairs minister.
   Shiokawa told the 21-member Cabinet at a meeting today: ``Some
Cabinet members lacked discretion in remarks they made recently that
were contrary to Cabinet policy. Any remark that may be taken to
impair trust in national politics should be strictly avoided.''
   Uno asked each Cabinet member to behave ``always with a sense of
caution,'' Defense Agency chief Taku Yamasaki told reporters at a
briefing after the meeting.
   In a campaign speech on Friday for fellow Liberal Democratic
Party members running in upper house elections July 23, Horinouchi
said women are ``useless in the world of politics.''
   Horinouchi retracted the remark and apologized in a nationally
televised news conference the next day, but on Monday the Communist
Party demanded his dismissal and six women from the main opposition
Socialist Party called the prime minister's office to lodge their
protest.
   Sakano was quoted in news reports as saying Sunday that the new 3
percent sales tax, which took effect April 1, required handling a
lot of small change, and ``there will be fewer coins if the
percentage is an even number of 4.''
   But the reports said he added later he was not advocating an
increase in the unpopular tax. He apologized for causing
misunderstanding.
   Kyodo News Service said both Horinouchi and Sakano offered to
resign but Shiokawa persuaded them to stay. Uno and his Cabinet have
been in office only a month, following the resignation of former
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita to take responsibility for a
widespread influence-peddling scandal.
   The admonitions came as the governing Liberal Democratic Party
was trying to woo voters in the face of predictions that it will
lose its majority in the upper house in the July 23 elections.
   It suffered losses in the July 2 Tokyo Metropolitan Assembly
elections that political analysts attributed to the sales tax, the
influence-peddling scandal and allegations that Uno had kept paid
mistresses.
   Under fire from women's groups, Uno denied doing anything
immoral. But Horinouchi's remark brought even more denunciations
from women's organizations.
   The Liberal Democrats now have 139 seats in the 252-seat upper
house. Half of the upper house seats are at stake in the upcoming
election and analysts are predicting the governing party's holdings
will be reduced to fewer than 126.
  
</TEXT>
