<FIRST>u a PM-NursesStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0518 07-11 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nurses Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0518,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sick Children Moved From Oakland Hospital as Nurses Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with nurses on strike, add quote,
picking up at the 4th graf, ``We're in ...'; Adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nurses went on strike today against
California's largest pediatrics hospital and ambulances lined up to
take dozens of critically ill children to other hospitals.
   Officials of Children's Hospital were forced to search as far
away as Los Angeles for beds for children with special medical needs
after the strike vote Monday night. The transfer of patients was
expected to continue until tonight.
   ``Nurses haven't been getting anything in the way of raises over
the last couple of years,'' said Mary Lesander, 21, who arrived to
pick up her nurse mother and stayed to walk the line. ``My mom's got
to support a family. She can't work for next to nothing.''
   ``We're in the third year of an escalating nursing shortage
that's preventing us from giving good care,'' said Karen Cooper, a
pediatrics nurse in the intensive care unit and a union spokeswoman.
``We're taking a painful step today to avert an even worse crisis in
the 1990s.''
   More than 80 percent of the 700 Childrens Hospital nurses
belonging to the California Nurses Association turned out for the
vote, Cooper said.
   Although the exact tally hadn't been completed, Cooper said a
``large majority'' voted to reject an 18 percent pay raise over two
years offered by the hospital.
   The nurses, who earn from $32,000 to $39,000 per year, are
seeking a 26 percent increase over two years.
   Hospital officials planned to transfer about half of the 139
patients in the 194-bed facility to other hospitals, hospital
spokesman Steve Tiger said.
   ``We're sad that it's come to this, and we feel that the wage
demands of the nursing union are unrealistic,'' Tiger said. ``There
aren't any real staffing shortages at this hospital.''
   At 6 percent, Childrens has the lowest vacancy rate among nurses
in California, Tiger said.
   Many of the striking nurses planned to sign up with nursing
registries in the area, hoping to get placed temporarily at the
hospitals where their patients are transferred, Cooper said.
   ``We are worried about our patients, especially since the
hospital has been so irresponsible,'' Cooper said. ``But we're more
worried about what will happen to the patients in a couple of years
if we don't reverse the nursing shortage.''
   Children's closed its pediatrics trauma center at midnight, Tiger
said.
   ``By transferring these kids there's going to be a ripple effect
because we've just about filled up all the pediatric beds in the Bay
area,'' he said. ``We normally have 30 to 40 admissions a day. It's
anybody's guess where any of those kids will go.''
   The hospital also began postponing elective surgery and planned
to stop admitting patients from the emergency room. Walk-in
emergency care would still be offered, and general admissions would
be done on a case-by-case basis, Tiger said.
   The hospital plans to continue running its pediatric intensive
care unit despite the strike and will keep as many patients as it
can handle with non-staff registry nurses and nurses who cross
picket lines.
</TEXT>
