<FIRST>r i PM-Mecca 2ndLd-Writethru a0562 07-11 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mecca, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0562,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITS a0589 to fix slugline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bombs Kill One, Hurts 16, During Holy Pilgrimage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Iran blaming Saudi Arabia,
U.S. for blasts. Pickup 4th graf, `Security sources...' Minor editing to
TRIM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded in Mecca as thousands
of people took part in the annual pilgrimage to Islam's most sacred
city, killing one person and injuring 16, the official Saudi press
said today.
   Two of the injured are in critical condition, the Saudi news
agency said, quoting an unnamed Saudi Interior Ministry security
official.
   No one claimed responsibility for the blasts, which occurred at
10 p.m. Monday while hundreds of thousands of pilgrims were praying
and walking around the Kaaba, Islam's holiest shrine, inside the
Grand Mosque.
   Iran, which has boycotted the pilgrimage this year in a feud with
Saudi Arabia, accused the Saudis of planting the bombs to discredit
Tehran.
   Iran's prime minister, Hussein Musavi, said the two bomb blasts
late Monday were an effort ``by the Saudi regime to create a climate
of suppression and repression,'' the official Islamic Republic News
Agency reported Tuesday.
   A Iranian Foreign Ministry statement urged pilgrims in Mecca to
protest the bombings, which it said were carried out by ``the United
States and its agents in the region,'' a reference to pro-Western
Saudi Arabia.
   Security sources in Riyadh said a number of suspects have been
arrested and are being interrogated.
   They said the injured include Pakistanis, Indians, Egyptians and
two Saudis. The identity of the dead person has not been released.
   The explosions occurred on the main road leading to the Grand
Mosque and a nearby overpass.
   One of the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
explosives were bombs of ``the type that makes a loud bang, has
quick impact, but causes little damage.''
   Diplomatic sources said investigators believe they were crude,
timed devices, or they would have injured more people.
   An estimated 1.8 million Moslems from more than 80 countries are
in Mecca on the annual pilgrimage to the city, birthplace of the
prophet Mohammed. During the pilgrimage, known as hajj, Moslems also
travel to Medina to visit the tomb of the 7th century founder of
Islam.
   A pilgrimage is one of the five basic duties of all Moslems.
   Iran is boycotting the hajj because of limits on the number of
pilgrims who can take part and has called on Moslems to disrupt the
ceremonies. Last year, Saudi Arabia began limiting the number of
pilgrims to Mecca and Medina based on a country's population.
   Security sources refused to link Monday's explosions to the
Iranians, saying the investigations were incomplete.
   ``Only a small number of Iranians came on their own and these
were mainly from Europe,'' said one security source.
   The pilgrimage season has been marred by disturbances since
Iran's Islamic revolution in 1979. In that year, religious
extremists seized the Grand Mosque in Mecca and held it for two
weeks before Saudi forces stormed it.
   More than 250 people were killed. Saudi authorities later
beheaded 63 more.
   The Saudis arrested scores of Iranian Revolutionary guards posing
as pilgrims in 1986 when they tried to smuggle in weapons and
explosives.
   The next year, 402 pilgrims, mostly Iranians, were killed in
riots in Mecca that the Saudis say were instigated by
fundamentalists.
   Saudi Arabia cut ties with Iran in April 1988. Tehran since has
campaigned to strip King Fahd of his title as ``custodian of the two
holy shrines'' and place Mecca and Medina under international
supervision.
</TEXT>
