<HEAD>Former Cabinet Minister Sentenced for Embezzlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SKIEN, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Cabinet minister pleaded guilty
Tuesday to embezzling trade union funds and was given a six-month
suspended jail sentence and two years' probation, state radio
reported.
   Einfrid Halvorsen resigned as minister of consumer affairs April
28 following published allegations that she stole about $21,500 from
a Skien union local in her 10-year term as treasurer until 1987.
   Mrs. Halvorsen, 51, repaid the entire amount, and said she had
taken union funds due to family problems, according to the NTB news
agency.
   The court said the embezzlement violated the trust placed in Mrs.
Halvorsen as public servant, union official and Cabinet minister,
the state NRK radio said.
   Mrs. Halvorsen had taken a leave of absence as mayor of this
eastern Norway city, 60 miles southwest of Oslo, to serve in Prime
Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland's cabinet.
