<FIRST>r w AM-DrivingTest     07-11 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Driving Test,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Televised Test to Check Americans' Driving Skills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When driving in fog at night, should your car's
headlights be set on high beam or low beam?
   The answer is low beam, which will direct light onto the road
ahead, while light from high beams will hit the fog and be reflected.
   That question and answer were part of a practice test released
Tuesday to prepare motorists for the National Driving Test on Aug.
29 on CBS, just before the long Labor Day weekend.
   More people lose their lives in accidents during the Labor Day
holiday than any other holiday period.
   ``It's been a long time since most of us took a driving test,''
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said at a Capitol Hill news
conference. ``Fifty million Americans will be able to renew
themselves and examine themselves.''
   Skinner, several members of Congress, the National Safety Council
and other highway safety organizations cooperated with Valvoline Oil
Co. and CBS in preparing the show, the first National Driving Test
in about 20 years.
   The 25-question test will cover defensive driving techniqus,
rules of the road, basic mechanical know-how and how to deal with
unexpected events.
   Carl F. Frey, Valvoline senior vice president, declined to say
how much the Kentucky-based company is spending for the hour-long
show and distribution of the test preparation booklets through
retail outlets. The booklet also will be published in TV Guide and
USA Today, Frey said.
   More than 48,000 people are killed and 1.8 million injured in the
nearly 21 million accidents on the nation's highways each year.
   Actor Christopher Reeve will be the host of the program, which
will include appearances by actors Perry King, Lorenzo Lamas, Betty
White and Susan Sullivan, Olympic gold medalist Bruce Jenner and
country singer Randy Travis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
