<FIRST>u a PM-FiresRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0584 07-11 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires Rdp, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0584,0963</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Firefighters Killed; Families Evacuated in Colorado</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs the 25th graf, ``We are cautiously,'' to CORRECT that airport
is east of Chadron, not west.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XCRF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Forest fires ravaged thousands of acres in Colorado canyons
today, destroying 65 homes and threatening 18 others, while
California authorities blamed a cigarette for a blaze that forced
hundreds of evacuations.
   Two firefighters have been killed, the first fatalities of this
summer's blazes in several Western states.
   A rapidly expanding brush fire in Utah has moved near two
transmission lines that relay power to much of the West, but
officials say no outages have occurred despite the temporary
shutdown Monday of one 345,000-volt line.
   The fire, which has scorched more than 1,000 acres in the Little
Sage Valley 15 miles southwest of Nephi, swept near the
Intermountain Power Plant's Intermountain-Mona transmission lines,
both major east to west carriers.
   In California, officials said today a smoldering cigarette may
have ignited a fire that has burned more than 4,000 acres on Mount
Laguna and forced the evacuation of hundreds of mountain residents
and visitors.
   ``A team of investigators were up there Monday, and they managed
to narrow it down to a cigarette butt as the most likely cause,''
said Dolores Fremter, a spokeswoman with the California Department
of Forestry.
   Firefighters battled a half-dozen blazes in the Colorado
mountains including a 2,200-acre fire that destroyed 65 homes and
threatens 18 others near Boulder and another burning near the
ancient Indian cliff dwellings of Mesa Verde National Park.
   ``It's like a war scene,'' said Jonathan Trent, whose mountain
cabin was destroyed by fire. ``It's like someone took a bomb and
dropped it on the cabin.''
   ``Today, they are going to be patrolling for spot fires on the
lines that have been built and stationed at threatened structures,''
said Mary Ann Chambers, a fire information officer with the U.S.
Forest Service at Boulder. Chambers confirmed that 65 homes had
burned.
   ``Low temperatures really helped Monday. In the afternoon it got
down into the 60s and there was a little moistures on the fire, but
after the rain came the winds and dried it out.''
   People are being allowed back into their homes, but they are not
allowed to stay there overnight, Chambers said.
   Sheriff Brad Leach said the fire was started Sunday by a resident.
   ``We know for sure where the fire started and that it was from
somebody's trailer,'' Leach said. ``We're questioning that
individual to try and determine whether he knew he did it or whether
it was an accident.''
   At Mesa Verde, site of the ancient Anasazi cliff dwellings,
archaeologists flagged ruins so work crews digging fire lines would
not damage them.
   ``We're not going to compromise the archaeology of the area to
put a bulldozer line in,'' said Paul Hefner, a firefighter from the
Bureau of Land Management. ``We've got to stop this fire, but not at
that cost.''
   The blaze, which had grown to 2,600 acres, was 50 percent
contained Monday.
   In California's scenic Big Sur wilderness, 120 miles south of San
Francisco, a falling tree killed a prison inmate Sunday night and
six members of his crew were injured, including two with broken
bones, said state forestry department spokeswoman Karen Terrill.
   Authorities decided after the death to stop night firefighting.
Fire lines were being staffed, but crews were not allowed to attack
the blaze, which is burning brush on slopes rising from the ocean.
   ``It's steep and rocky and slick,'' said forestry department
spokesman Bill Jones.
   The fire had blackened 2,655 acres and was 50 percent contained
Monday night, Jones said. No buildings were threatened.
   In Nebraska, firefighters used aerial attacks against fires that
burned dry pine trees and grassland over an area 22-by-8 miles in
the state's northwest corner.
   Up to six planes at a time each dumped 300 gallons of water on
the flames.
   Kurt Budd, sporting a blue ``I fought at Yellowstone'' T-shirt,
landed his crop-duster on a section of U.S. 20 that had been blocked
by state troopers to facilitate loading water from firetrucks.
   The blaze, which officials estimated had charred about 50,000
acres since Saturday, was partially contained and no longer
threatened historic Fort Robinson, built in 1874.
   ``We are cautiously optimistic that the worst part of the fire is
over,'' Gov. Kay Orr said at the Chadron Airport, about 22 miles
east of Crawford.
   ``It is better contained, but not fully contained,'' said Jerry
Larson, deputy state fire marshal.
   In Arizona, lightning struck and killed Ernie Cachini, a
firefighter from New Mexico who was battling a fire in the Tonto
National Forest.
   ``He was a member of the famous Zuni Firefighters team from Zuni
Pueblo,'' said forest spokeswoman Joyce Hassell. ``He was on the
steep slope ... when he was struck.''
   Two fires that consumed nearly 2,000 acres near Fremont National
Forest in south-central Oregon were largely controlled early today,
the U.S. Forest Service said.
   Dan Sholly, chief ranger at Yellowstone National Park, which last
year suffered its most destructive fire season on record, said the
park was drying out more each week.
   ``We can anticipate signficant fire activity in Yellowstone,''
Sholly said at a news conference he attended with James Ridenour,
new director the National Park Service.
   Crews were expected to pull out of the Bridger-Teton Forest fire
in Wyoming today, after containing the blaze that burned 3,447 acres
about 150 miles southeast of Yellowstone.
   Crews in Utah were close to containing a 15,500-acre fire in
rough, remote terrain about 20 miles west of the Colorado line.
</TEXT>
