<FIRST>r a PM-DroughtInsuranceTrial 1stLd-Writethru   07-11 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drought Insurance Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0500,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Jury Picked for Agent That Sold Drought Insurance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE that trial will start Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers have selected a federal court jury of
eight people to hear a trial on behalf of 8,000 farmers in 10 states
who sued a company that allegedly oversold 1988 drought insurance
policies.
   The trial was scheduled to begin Wednesday before U.S. District
Judge Carl B. Rubin.
   U.S. Magistrate Robert Steinberg presided over Monday's jury
selection. Rubin was to decide later which of the eight jury members
will be alternates, since a civil jury usually has six members. The
trial could last two weeks, lawyers said.
   In the lawsuit, the farmers are asking for damages of at least
$20 million in addition to unspecified punitive damages against Good
Weather International Corp. of Syosset, N.Y., said Stanley M.
Chesley, a Cincinnati lawyer representing the farmers.
   His clients allege that Good Weather sold them drought insurance
policies backed by Chubb Corp. of Warren, N.J.
   Chubb later canceled the farmers' drought insurance coverage
after learning Good Weather had sold more than the available number
of such policies.
   Chubb has joined the farmers from Ohio, Illinois, Iowa, Kentucky,
Indiana, Tennessee, Minnesota, Michigan, Missouri, and Wisconsin as
plaintiffs in the suit.
   Chesley said the farmers and Chubb have an agreement in which the
farmers would receive two-thirds of any winnings from the lawsuit
and Chubb would get one-third.
   Chubb and its insurance subsidiaries agreed last November to a
settlement in which they set aside a fund of $48.1 million to settle
the farmers' claims. Lawrence Kane Jr., a Cincinnati lawyer named by
Rubin to distribute the money to the farmers, began doing so in
March.
   Chubb said Good Weather violated its contract with the company by
selling too many crop insurance policies. Chubb said Good Weather
owes it at least $75 million because of the overselling, and also
wants Good Weather to pay the fees of lawyers Chubb hired.
   The farmers said they suffered emotional distress because they
were denied drought insurance, in addition to losses stemming from
interest payments they would have received had they been issued
policies.
   Good Weather denies all of the claims by the farmers and Chubb,
said its attorney, James Moore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
