<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-HungarianEnterprise     07-11 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Hungarian Enterprise,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Enterprise Greets Bush Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's visit to Hungary is
providing an opportunity for several private enterprise ventures of
the kind Hungarian and U.S. officials are encouraging.
   Radio Bridge, a new, private, English-language radio station, on
Tuesday began a trial broadcast to coincide with the two-day visit,
the official MTI news agency said.
   The station, which will broadcast on a trial basis for the
duration of the Bush visit, until noon Thursday, plans to go on the
air regularly at the end of the year, MTI said.
   Radio Bridge, which will broadcast exclusively in English, is
aimed at foreign businessmen in Hungary with broadcasts of political
and economic news as well as cultural and tourist information.
   A Swedish-U.S.-Canadian partnership and Hungarian private
individuals have set up a limited company to finance the station,
MTI said.
   MTI said it was the first private radio station to broadcast in
Hungary. Commercial radio stations began broadcasting in Hungary in
1986 primarily as a service to tourists but also became popular with
Hungarians.
   During the Bush visit, Radio Bridge is broadcasting out of a
studio in the Hungarian Academy of Scieces using transmitting
equipment lent by the Hungarian post office, MTI said.
   Since it pioneered Soviet bloc economic reform in the late 1960s,
Hungary has allowed a fair degree of latitude to small-scale
economic entrepreneurs. Many have proved more than adept.
   Two young Hungarians took the opportunity of the presidential
visit to offer Hungarians a snapshot with Bush, using a Polaroid
camera and a lifesize, stand-up portrait of the smiling president.
   Laszlo Halnai and Peter Lakos on Tuesday offered Hungarians their
``snapshot with the president'' for 200 forints ($3.30) a shot.
   Sixty or 70 takers came forward in the first hour, said Laszlo
Halnai, who advertised the deal with large billboards slung over his
shoulders as he wandered near Budapest's main Vaci Utca shopping
mall area.
   Asked whether permission was required from city authorities to
embark on the project, Halnai grinned. ''Yes, but we didn't get
around to applying for it yet.'''
</TEXT>
