<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev     07-11 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev on Troubleshooting Trip to Leningrad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev left Tuesday on a
troubleshooting mission to Leningrad, where the Communist Party
leadership failed to win parliamentary elections in March, Tass said.
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov said problems have been accumulating
in Leningrad, according to the official news agency.
   Leningrad party officials, including the city's party boss, Yuri
F. Solovyev, failed to win a seat in the Congress of People's
Deputies in the March 26 elections.
   ``Gorbachev has gone there to help sort out a whole gamut of
problems on the spot,'' Ryzhkov said at a session of the Supreme
Soviet legislature.
   Tass said, ``The program for the Soviet leader's stay in
Leningrad includes meetings with Communists, public activists,
economic executives and managers of the city.''
   Gorbachev visited the Izohorsky power engineering site and was to
tour a Soviet-West German shoe-making enterprise, Tass said.
   The factories of Leningrad, with a population of 5 million,
account for more than 3 percent of the country's industrial output,
the news agency said.
   Tass did not say how long Gorbachev would remain in Leningrad,
the Soviet Union's second largest city. He returned from an official
visit to Bucharest, Romania, on Sunday.
