<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bush-Hungary'sHopes Bjt   07-11 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Hungary's Hopes, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Looks to Bush for Lift from Economic Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's leaders are hoping the first
visit by an American president will cast a favorable light on their
moves toward democracy and help attract more Western investment.
   Unlike their Polish counterparts, the Hungarians were not
expecting any direct aid from President Bush to alleviate their
stiff foreign debt.
   But like the Poles, the Hungarians have a heavy load to carry.
Hungary's nearly $18 billion foreign debt is the highest per capita
in Eastern Europe.
   Hungary has been at the forefront of economic reforms in the
communist bloc since the 1960s, encouraging private entrepreneurs
and even a small but energetic stock market.
   It is also the land where Soviet tanks and troops crushed a
revolt against communist rulers in 1956.
   Today, government officials and ordinary folk alike share the
hope that the Bush visit will help mend Hungary's economic woes and
further democratic reforms.
   It's ``a great honor for a small country such as ours for the No.
1 political leader of a huge country to visit it,'' Premier Miklos
Nemeth told the government daily Magyar Hirlap.
   ``The most important thing as far as I am concerned is to
eliminate the doubts which still exist in the United States, and in
other Western countries, about a roll-back in Hungary, and the
security of capital investments,'' Nemeth said.
   Ferenc Pityo, who sells flowers on Budapest's lively main
shopping mall, Vaci Utca, said the Bush visit ``might do some good
for the country as a whole.''
   ``But what would do me a lot of good is if they gave me a
permanent and not a temporary permit to sell my flowers,'' added the
woman, who said she has four children.
   Hungary's English-language daily and other state-run media ran
supplements to mark the historic visit.
   ``I'm happy that the relationship is unfolding the way it is,''
said Zoltan Benedikt, a university student. ``But I'm afraid that if
Bush is bringing any capital, it's going to be given to the company
managers who have already shown their incompetence in handling these
funds.''
   Any retreat from current efforts to build a market-oriented
economy and a multi-party democracy in Hungary would be ``a national
tragedy for our people,'' Nemeth said.
   The premier, 41, an economist who once spent a semester at
Harvard University, is one of four men currently running Hungary at
the head of its Communist Party until a party congress selects new
leaders this fall.
   The four-man leadership took control June 24 in what was widely
seen as a compromise between the strengthening reformist wing and
more orthodox communists who oppose what they regard as a return to
capitalism and the bourgeois democracy that ruled before the
communist takeover in 1948.
   Party general secretary Karoly Grosz, who previously headed the
party alone, was forced to share power with Nemeth, radical reformer
Imre Pozsgay and Rezso Nyers, who pioneered the economic reforms of
the 1960s. Nyers fell from grace in 1973 but now has been made party
chairman.
   Bush meets each of the four Wednesday. Later, he sees leaders of
emerging democratic opposition groups negotiating with the
communists on the framework and timetable for multi-party elections
next year.
   Nemeth stressed that political and economic reforms must move
together to avoid ``a political explosion'' that would wreck any
changes.
   Western assistance is needed to transform the largely state-run
economy, he said, providing new jobs for Hungarians, whose outmoded
factories are threatened with closure under government austerity
policies.
   U.S. and Hungarian officials will sign four agreements Wednesday.
   Senior Foreign Ministry official Jenoe Alfoeldi told The
Associated Press that one of them involves a trade and development
program for Bozsod county in Hungary's northeast, a heavily
industrialized area where large steel mills and other industries are
running at a heavy loss.
   The other agreements concern tourism, air traffic and
agriculture, Alfoeldi said.
   While Bush's visit signals Western recognition of Hungary's
reforms, officials emphasize Budapest is not pulling too far away
from Moscow or other communist allies.
   Withdrawal from the Warsaw Pact ``would be quite inappropriate
right now,'' Nemeth told Magyar Hirlap.
   ``It is very important for us to preserve and develop the
relationship with the Soviet Union,'' Foreign Minister Gyula Horn
told reporters Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
