<FIRST>u w PM-Pentagon-Overhaul 3rdLd-Writethru a0604 07-11 0960</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon-Overhaul, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0604,910</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Announces Pentagon Reform Blueprint</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Cheney quotes; picks up at pvs 4th graf,
President Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, acknowledging he
has no ``quick fix'' for streamlining the Pentagon, today put
forward a complex plan to overhaul the military bureaucracy and
tighten controls over weapons purchases.
   He predicted that some $30 billion in total savings could be
achieved by the 1993 fiscal year if his ``simplified and more
efficient'' weapons acquisition system is put in place.
   Procurement accounts for more than $60 billion of this year's
$305 billion defense budget and involves more than a half-million
civilian and uniformed employees of the Defense Department.
   At a news conference, Cheney said the ever-tightening defense
budget, as well as the amount of distrust in Congress and among the
public about the way the Pentagon does business, requires that
something be done.
   ``There's no silver bullet here. ... We have a blueprint that we
plan to pursue ... to try to significantly improve the way we do
business,'' he said.
   But Cheney, a former member of the Republican leadership in the
House, acknowledged that he won't be able to achieve changes on his
own. ``If we're going to be successful, it will be because we got
Congress to cooperate,'' he said.
   President Bush requested the management report five months ago as
part of a major review spurred on by a series of weapons procurement
scandals. Defense industry employees and consultants and Pentagon
workers have been accused of improperly using confidential
information to funnel lucrative contracts to certain manufacturers.
   The elements of the package have been circulating in Washington
for some time. The report already has stirred some opposition on
Capitol Hill, where it has been snubbed as not going far enough to
outline details for revising the Pentagon's procurement practices.
   The report seeks some relief from congressional oversight
requests, complaining about the ``staggering'' number of reports
Congress requires from the Defense Department each day.
   Some sections of the plan require congressional approval. For
instance, the study asks that Congress implement fully a biennial,
rather than annual, defense budget and establish select committees
in both houses to review and rewrite ``the maze of federal
procurement laws.''
   Many of the ideas included in the reform package were first
proposed in the 1986 Blue Ribbon Commission on Defense Management,
also known as the Packard Commission.
   In a summary released with the report, Cheney said that because
of competing national priorities, ``the real resources available for
defense in the early 1990s are likely to decline.''
   ``If we are to protect our global interests, met our
responsibilities and minimize the risks to our security, we must
preserve essential military capabilities through ever more skillful
use of the resources at our disposal,'' he said.
   Cheney called for ``better teamwork'' to put his initiatives into
reality.
   ``None represents a quick fix. Only an unreserved and sustained
commitment on the part of the administration, Congress and industry
will bring about real change,'' he said.
   The secretary's goal is ``to make clear the lines of authority in
the (procurement) process, not only to make it more responsive, but
also more responsible,'' said one Pentagon official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The proposals include:
   _The establishment of an executive panel to make all the major
decisions at the Defense Department.
   The board would be composed of the secretary, the deputy
secretary, undersecretary, the deputies for procurement and
acquisitions, the heads of the various services and chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff. The panel would be smaller than the current
Defense Resources Board, which advises Cheney on major weapons and
budgetary decisions.
   _Allowing the deputy secretary of defense to oversee the
Pentagon's system for planning, programming and devising its budget.
   The deputy secretary would oversee the Defense Planning and
Resources Board, which also will be asked to come up with a coherent
national defense strategy, as well as a 20-year ``road map'' on the
long-term needs and investment plans for the department.
   _Enhancing the powers of the undersecretary of defense for
acquisition _ dubbed the ``acquisition czar.'' The undersecretary
would have ``full authority for major acquisition programs,'' which
would trim some of the services' powers.
   _Paring down and consolidate overlapping structures in the
acquisition system, the proposal under which Cheney predicts will
``eliminate layers and functions that have no value,'' and primarily
through payroll cuts achieve the $30 billion in savings over the
next four budget years.
   The report notes that some 580,000 civilian and military
personnel around the world are involved in the procurement process.
The report suggests trimming the organizations on a phased basis
``by at least 15 percent'' by 1993.
   _The establishment of a Defense Contract Managment Agency to
consolidate its contract administration activities and ride herd on
the contracts after they have been awarded.
   _Streamlining the Defense Acquisitions Board, which would study
the cost and performance of weapons programs at each stage of
development.
   _Establishing a ``dedicated corps'' of military procurement
specialists in each service, who would be career acquisition
specialists. Congress will also be asked to approve legislation to
upgrade the salaries and training of civilian acquisition officials.
   _Setting up an ethics council composed of the acquisitions chief
and the various service secretaries.
   Bush, who was in Warsaw on Monday, issued a statement supporting
Cheney's program. The president's letter accompanied the report to
congressional leaders.
   ``This report provides a basis for significant additional
improvements in the management of the Department of Defense and in
the defense acquisition process,'' Bush wrote. He added the
proposals would eliminate ``unnecessary management layers and
activities, a reform that will yield significant savings, which can
be applied to essential defense programs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     07-11 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Cheer Junta; Military Ruler Vows No Return to Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Sudanese demonstrated support
for the nation's new military ruler Tuesday, cheering wildly as he
pledged no return to the multiparty democracy he overthrew last
month.
   ``Exterminate! Exterminate government by masters!'' the crowd
chanted, referring to the multiparty system under which ousted
civilian Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi had ruled since he won 1986
elections.
   ``Yes, yes. Government by masters will be exterminated,'' the
coup leader, Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan Ahmed el-Bashir, responded in a
15-minute speech.
   Earlier Tuesday, el-Bashir set up four military tribunals, one a
court of appeals, to try el-Mahdi and about 45 other ousted
officials and politicians charged with corruption or mismanagement,
state radio reported.
   Heading a 15-member junta, el-Bashir, 45, toppled el-Mahdi in an
apparently bloodless coup June 30.
   He immediately dissolved parliament, disbanded political parties
and unions and declared a nationwide state of emergency. On Monday,
he declared himself prime minister and defense minister.
   Despite temperatures well into the 100s, Tuesday's demonstration
brought 20,000 to 30,000 people, mostly workers, to the presidential
palace along the Nile.
   ``One army! One nation!'' they shouted, frequently cheering and
applauding el-Bashir. ``We shall protect the revolution by hard
work.''
   The crowd burned an effigy marked ``sectarianism,'' in the shape
of a bearded man wearing the kind of robe used by followers of
el-Mahdi's Ansar sect. Ansar and Khatmiya are the principal Moslem
sects in Sudan.
   Khatmiya leader Mohammed Osman el-Mirghany, patron of the
Democratic Unionist Party, is among those under arrest. The
Unionists and el-Mahdi's Umma were the main partners in the ousted
coalition Cabinet.
   Tuesday's demonstration was sanctioned by el-Bashir's ruling
council, but el-Bashir told supporters there will be no more street
demonstrations. ``This is the first and the last,'' he said.
   El-Mahdi's government was rocked by street protests this year as
citizens wearied of a $1 million-a-day southern civil war that has
fueled food shortages, displaced hundreds of thousands and induced
famine that killed perhaps a quarter million people last year.
   El-Bashir has cited el-Mahdi's inability to end the war as one
reason for the coup.
   On Tuesday, a Sudanese delegation arrived in Addis Ababa and
asked the Ethiopian government to help settle the southern rebellion.
   Ethiopian state radio quoted delegation chief Lt. Col. Mohammed
el-Amin Khalifa as saying Sudan's new military government wants
Ethiopia to mediate with the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army,
which the Addis Ababa government supports.
   Khalifa's five-man delegation was to meet President Mengistu
Haile Mariam and other Ethiopian leaders, the radio said.
   It also quoted Khalifa as saying he would meet with Sudanese
rebels ``if the situation is favorable.''
   El-Bashir says he is committed to peace, but he scrapped a
tentative accord approved by el-Mahdi's government, which included
meeting rebel preconditions for talks by suspending Sudan's harsh
Islamic laws and abrogating defense pacts with Libya and Egypt.
   The new leader says he seeks an eventual union with Egypt and
Libya.
   Northern Sudan is largely Moslem and leans toward the Arab world.
The rebels have been fighting for greater autonomy for the minority
Christians and animists of the south, who look to black, sub-Saharan
Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
