<FIRST>r i AM-GdanskShipyard     07-11 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gdansk Shipyard,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Heiress May Help Save Historic Shipyard</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lenin shipyard has become a symbol of
Poland's difficult fortunes in the postwar era.
   Rebuilt after World War II as a model of socialist Poland's
possibilities, it became famous in 1980 as the birthplace of
Solidarity but was declared inefficient last fall in the nation's
drive for economic reform.
   The sprawling yard, which President Bush visited Tuesday, has
been in decline since the late 1970s, when it produced a high of 27
ships yearly and had 15,000 employees.
   Hazardous work and poor living conditions have long made the
shipyard a hotbed of political and union activity. In 1970, security
police opened fire on workers protesting food price rises, killing
45, according to the official death toll.
   Ten years later, during a strike sparked by the firing of a
popular crane operator, Lech Walesa scaled a shipyard fence to lead
what became the first independent trade union in the Soviet bloc.
   Last Oct. 31, the government said the yard would be closed Dec.
1, 1989, because it was unprofitable. The shipyard employed about
10,000 when the closing was announced.
   The shipyard was the first major enterprise to be singled out for
dismantling by the then month-old government of Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, who had said he would move swiftly to close
inefficient factories that drain off huge state subsidies.
   Walesa called the move a ``personal provocation ... against the
birthplace of Solidarity.''
   In the intervening months, the communist government, increasingly
aware that it could not control the economy or social unrest without
Solidarity, held reform talks with the union and agreed to restore
its legal status.
   On June 4, as Poles voted in their freest elections under
communist rule, a Polish-American businesswoman from New Jersey
joined with Walesa to announce a plan to save the shipyard.
   Barbara Piasecka Johnson, heir to the Johnson &amp; Johnson
pharmaceutical fortune, pledged up to $100 million to save the
shipyard.
   Under the plan, not yet finalized, Mrs. Johnson and her advisers
would own 55 percent of the prospective joint venture and the
management of the state-run enterprise would own 45 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
