<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dave Winfield's first court-ordered child support
payment is due Saturday, but lawyers for the New York Yankees
outfielder say they will appeal.
   A jury ruled last month that Sandra Renfro, a Houston flight
attendant and mother of Winfield's 6-year-old daughter, was his
common-law wife from 1982 to 1985.
   District Judge Allen J. Daggett on Monday ordered Winfield to pay
Sandra Renfro $13,500 a month in temporary support and child
support, her $210,000 in legal fees and half of the expenses and
taxes on her car and condominium.
   Support payments for Ms. Renfro begin Aug. 5.
   Dennis Kelly, a lawyer for Winfield, said he will appeal.
   ``I've always taken care of my child, but I contend I was never
married to the lady,'' Winfield said Monday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harrison Ford says he understands why his fans
are interested in his every move.
   ``People think celebrities have gotten away with something,''
Ford says in the August issue of Redbook. ``We've escaped from the
pack, from the daily grind. The public appoints us to be symbols of
success.''
   ``I'm very uncomfortable when people stare at me, but I think
I've learned how to deal with that. I try to think of those people
as satisfied customers and that's why they're approaching me,'' he
said.
   Ford knows about the flip side of fame. After bit parts in such
TV series as ``Gunsmoke,'' ``Ironside'' and ``The Virginian'' and a
role in the 1970 flop ``Zabriskie Point,'' he became a carpenter.
   ``I became somebody other than an out-of-work actor,'' he said.
``I was now a carpenter, so whenever I went to an audition or met an
agent, I wasn't worried about getting the acting job.''
   George Lucas cast Ford in ``American Graffiti'' in 1972. But Ford
didn't hang up his carpenter's tools until the 1976 blockbuster,
``Star Wars.''
   ``I always knew that if I was going to make it, it was going to
take a long time,'' said Ford, 47. ``I knew there was no such thing
as an `overnight success.' So I hung in there.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lauren Chapin has been a 4-year-old sex-abuse
victim, a 16-year-old bride, a 17-year-old alcoholic, a heroin
addict, a call girl, a check forger and an unmarried mother.
   She also was a star as a teen-ager in ``Father Knows Best,''
playing ``Kitten'' on the 1950s series. It is that role that gives
her inspiration in her current role as a happily married mother and
minister at the age of 44.
   ``I have nothing but admiration for the message of `Father Knows
Best.' I'm trying to raise my family like the Andersons _ I believe
the father should be the head of the household, the mom should be
home nurturing the kids and the whole family should attend church,''
she said in the August issue of Redbook.
   Her upbringing is detailed in her autobiography, ``Father Does
Know Best: The Lauren Chapin Story,'' to be published in August.
   In it, she says that her father sexually abused her for two years
and that she was insulted and ignored by her alcoholic mother to the
point where she tried to commit suicide at age 11. The book recounts
Ms. Chapin's slide into crime and addiction, the birth of her two
children and her religious rebirth.
   She lives in Texas with her children and her husband, a
firefighter.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after playing their first concert
together in 20 years, the Monkees received a star on the Hollywood
Walk of Fame.
   More than 700 noisy fans greeted Monkees Peter Tork, Davy Jones,
Mickey Dolenz and Mike Nesmith as the quartet accepted the honor
Monday.
   ``We have seen such a sense of support and love over the years,''
Nesmith said. ``This has meant more than we can ever possibly say.''
   The Monkees, who had a TV show in the 1960s, have toured as a
threesome in recent years. On Sunday night for the first time in two
decades, Nesmith joined the other band members at a Monkees
convention in Universal City.
   The group's hits included ``Last Train to Clarksville'' and ``I'm
a Believer.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Danny Glover thinks his character in this
summer's action-smash ``Lethal Weapon II'' should have been sexier.
   In the film, Glover's wife is played by Darlene Love, but the two
are never shown in romantic situations.
   ``You know, he could at least be seen kissing her. Or holding
her,'' Glover said. ``I think that in real life I probably bore my
own daughter, the way I'm always hugging and kissing her mama.''
   Glover, 40, and his wife, Asake, live in San Francisco with their
daughter, Mandisa.
   In ``Lethal Weapon II,'' Glover plays Roger Murtaugh, a cop with
a reckless partner played by Mel Gibson. If there is a sequel,
Glover sees his character leaving his wife, having an affair, then
coming to his senses and returning home.
   ``What do you think?'' Glover asked. ``Doesn't that make Murtaugh
sound just a little more interesting, a little more human?''
