<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1425EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-11 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Asks U.N. Troops Block Returning Radical Student</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government asked U.N. forces to
block a radical South Korean student who plans to cross the border
from North Korea as a symbol of national unification, news reports
said Tuesday.
   The head of South Korea's governing party said there will be
trouble if North Korea permits Im Su-kyong to walk through the truce
village of Panmunjom in the Demilitarized Zone.
   Park Jyun-kyu, chairman of the governing Democratic Justice
Party, said the action ``will raise havoc on the present military
status quo at the (military) demarcation line'' that separates the
two Koreas,'' but he did not elaborate.
   Miss Im, who in defiance of her government traveled to North
Korea via Europe to attend a youth festival, said she would enter
Panmunjom on July 27, anniversary of the cease-fire that ended the
Korean War.
   The government has said it will arrest Miss Im, 20, on charges of
national security violations for an illegal trip to North Korea, but
newspapers said officials believed the arrest should not take place
at the border because it could increase political tension.
   Seoul says dialogue with the communist government in Pyongyang
must be conducted only through government or authorized channels.
   The semi-official South Korean news agency Yonhap said the
government has asked the United Nations Command guarding the border
to stop Miss Im at Panmunjom, where some of the 43,000 U.S. troops
in South Korea are garrisoned.
   The command, highly sensitive to any issue involving politics
between the nations, refused comment on the reports.
   Under the armistice, no one can cross the DMZ without prior
agreement from both sides, but if allowed access to the area, it
would be simple to walk from one nation to the other at Panmunjom
because there are few barriers. It was not clear how the command was
expected to stop Miss Im.
   The peninsula was divided into North Korea and South Korea in
1945, and the nations fought the 1950-53 Korean War and have
remained archrivals despite their talks in the past 18 years for
reconciliation.
   Park, in Tokyo on his way back to Seoul from a visit to Canada,
said he believes the student will return home ``via other routes,''
adding it is North Korea ``who is afraid of breaking the demarcation
line.''
   Some South Korean dissidents and radical students claim Seoul is
insincere in its attempt to seek unification. They also demand the
overthrow of the government of President Roh Tae-woo and withdrawal
of U.S. troops from South Korea, saying they hinder unification
talks.
   The only mutually acceptable crossings in the last 36 years have
been delegates to talks by the two nations and about 150 people from
each side who took part in a 1985 home visitation program allowing
Koreans on either side to visit relatives.
</TEXT>
