<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseIndustry     07-11 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Industry,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carlucci Says US Can't Go It Alone in Defense Procurement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
cautioned Tuesday against strict protectionist legislation to help
the declining U.S. defense industry, saying the country can't ``go
it alone'' technologically.
   ``If we protect U.S. industries from foreign competition, we
reduce the incentive to invest in modern facilities and advanced
technologies, and we deprive ourselves of access to advances in
technology being achieved in foreign countries,'' Carlucci told the
Senate Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs Committee.
   Congress is weighing renewal of the Defense Production Act, which
expires Sept. 30. The 39-year-old act gives the federal government
authority to subsidize industries, including those that produce
goods for the Pentagon. It also gives the president the power to
limit or prohibit the acquisition of foreign products.
   In the House, Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, D-Ohio, has introduced an
amendment that would limit participation of foreign comapanies in
defense manufacturing and provide financial assistance to
medium-size and small defense companies.
   Recent studies have shown a decline in domestic sources of
defense production. Specifically, the Center for Strategic and
International Studies found that from 1987 to 1982 the number of
companies suppling goods to the Defense Department dropped from
118,000 to 38,000.
   Adm. Bobby Inman, former deputy director of the CIA, told the
Senate panel that immediate action is necessary because of the
erosion of the defense industrial base.
   ``I should have put my money into T-bills instead of defense
production activities,'' Inman said.
   But the former CIA official said the House legislation is an
``unwise approach,'' and suggested limiting the use of domestic-only
suppliers on specific items.
   Robert B. Costello, former undersecretary for defense
acquisition, told the Senate committee that since the U.S. defense
industry uses foreign parts and technology, the Pentagon cannot
arbitrarily ban the use of any foreign supplied material.
   Carlucci said a move toward protectionism ``invites retaliation.
It could be disastrous to our national security, if we assume we can
`go it alone' technologically.''
   Asked by Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., if an presidential advisory
committee was needed, Carlucci said such a panel would not solve the
problem.
   ``The government should take a more active role in encouraging
adoption of improved manufacturing processess throughout our
industrial base, not just among defense contractors,'' Carlucci said.
   He also suggested favorable tax policies and long-term investment
in defense programs.
</TEXT>
