<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     07-11 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emigres: Passports Confiscated of Former Foreign Minister, Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovak authorities confiscated the
passports of more than 20 activists, including a former foreign
minister who said on a Scandinavian visit that reform in his country
was too slow, emigre sources said Tuesday.
   The sources in the Austrian capital, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Czechoslovak officials on July 4 revoked the
passport of Jiri Hajek, who served as foreign minister during the
1968 ``Prague Spring'' reform period that was crushed by Soviet
troops.
   More than 20 independent activists had their passports
confiscated last month, the sources said.
   The Norwegian newspaper Aftenposten quoted Hajek, who is also a
member of the Charter 77 human rights group, as saying he was told
the passport was revoked ``because it wasn't in the interest of the
state for me to have travel documents and be able to travel abroad
now.''
   The emigre sources said Hajek appealed the decision.
   Hajek was told the measure was taken due to interviews granted to
Western media while he was abroad and his attendance at a meeting of
the Socialist International in Stockholm June 20-22, the sources
said.
   Hajek gave a series of interviews to Swedish media and held a
news conference at the airport when he arrived in Norway May 11 at
which he criticized the Czechoslovak regime for being slow to
implement reforms.
   He also visited his son who is studying in Oslo and is not
permitted to travel to Czechoslovakia.
   Rut Sormova, a signatory of the Charter 77 human rights manifesto
and a member of the Independent Peace Association, also had her
passport revoked before a planned visit to Spain to attend a
congress of European Peace movements. She was then to travel on to
Budapest, Hungary, for an East-West dialogue, the sources said.
   Two weeks ago, authorities seized the passport of the wife of
dissident playwright Vaclav Havel. She had been planning to visit
friends in Vienna.
</TEXT>
