<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Bush-Hungary     07-11 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Hungary,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crowd Defies Rain to Greet Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs. Retransmiting a0648 to add headline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush arrived in Hungary today
to a rainstorm that led him to tear up his opening remarks and tell
well-wishers ``I feel the warmth of this welcome and the rain
doesn't make a darn bit of difference.''
   Bush, the first U.S. president ever to visit Hungary, told the
crowd in Kossuth Square, ``we have in our country a special
affection and feeling for the people of Hungary.''
   In his meetings with Hungarian leaders, Bush said, ``I will be
bringing them the warm greetings from the American people and the
convictions of the people of the United States that we must work
with Hungary, we want to work with Hungary to continue the changes
and the reforms going forward in your great country.''
   Bush said he scrapped his opening speech and decided to speak
``from the heart'' because the crowd had been out in the rain too
long.
   ``You'll have to listen to me tomorrow, I'm sure, at some drier
time and some drier place,'' he said, adding:
   ``Long after this rain is gone, I am going to remember the warmth
of the welcome from the people of Hungary.''
   On Kossuth Square, workers had to hastily repair wind damage
caused by a fierce thunderstorm that turned the sky pitch black 75
minutes before Air Force One landed at Ferihegy Airport.
   One bannr hoisted in the square by an anti-government group said,
``Don't give money to communists.''
   As President Bruno F. Straub greeted Bush at some length, the
U.S. president drew warm applause for helping wife Barbara into a
raincoat.
   Straub told Bush Hungary is convinced that his visit means his
country's current reforms have ``the sympathy and support of the
American people'' and noted that international relations had
improved since Bush's visit as vice president in 1983.
   Then, Straub said, East-West relations were characterized by ``an
almost total lack of East-West dialogue.''
   Now, he noted, Hungary is ``getting similar words of
encouragement from East and West alike and we do need these very
much.''
   The welcoming ceremony took place on a large square near the
Danube River named after Lajos Kossuth, the hero of Hungary's failed
1848 revolt against its then Austrian rulers.
   Kossuth is a symbol both of the nation's long fight for freedom
and its affection for the United States, where Kossuth was hailed as
a hero during an 1851-52 visit. Kossuth was an orator of reknown,
and Abraham Lincoln reportedly borrowed some of his words for the
Gettysburg Address.
   Bush journeyed here from Poland. His next stop on Thursday is
Paris for the economic summit, followed by a visit to the
Netherlands Monday and Tuesday before returning to Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
