<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1457EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-HUDProbe 3rdLd-Writethru a0615 07-11 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0615,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Pledge `Zero Tolerance' for Abuses at HUD</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 2 new grafs to UPDATE with Kemp testifying.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp today pledged
``zero tolerance'' for thievery and influence peddling at the
scandal-ridden Department of Housing and Urban Development that he
inherited this year.
   ``What I could not anticipate three months ago was the extent to
which I had inherited a legacy of abuse and mismanagement, fraud and
favoritism in certain HUD programs,'' Kemp said in testimony before
a congressional panel.
   Kemp was warmly received by his former colleagues in the House.
Unlike all the other witnesses who have appeared before the panel in
its HUD investigation, he was not asked to testify under oath.
   Kemp denounced the practice that prevailed during the Reagan
administration, when developers hired well-known Republicans to act
as ``consultants'' to help secure HUD funds to fix up housing for
the poor. He said that practice helped inflate the cost of the
projects.
   ``That extra money goes for excess profits for the developer and,
clearly, to cover consultant fees,'' he said.
   Developers and consultants testifying before Congress all have
denied that taxpayers' money was used to pay their fees, sometimes
in six figures.
   ``The Department of Housing and Urban Development will maintain a
policy of zero tolerance for violations of our standards of
conduct,'' Kemp told the House Government Operations subcommittee on
housing and employment.
   In addition to influence peddling, federal investigators are
looking into the possible theft of as much as $20 million by a dozen
private closing agents around the country who failed to hand over
money to the government they collected for the sale of foreclosed
properties.
   One such agent, Marilyn Harrell of Maryland, has publicly
confessed taking more than $5 million, but said she gave some of it
to the poor, earning her the nickname ``Robin HUD.''
   ``People who steal from this program are not Robin Hood type
heroes, as some have protrayed them, and they aren't `robbing the
rich','' Kemp said. ``They are stealing from the taxpayer and
depriving low and moderate income people of the opportunity to
realize the American dream of home ownership.''
   HUD, meanwhile, has reassigned four employees of its Washington
field office pending investigations of their role in apparent
mismanagement that officials believe cost the government about $10
million.
   That investigation is part of a Kemp-ordered review of virtually
all major HUD programs.
   Kemp has suspended three HUD programs and said last week there
may be more suspensions as he examines the agency's operations.
   He has promised he will not use HUD's problems to curtail the
federal government's role in housing.
   ``I think Kemp is going to do the right thing, by and large,''
said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass. ``The big thing is that we have
somebody in there who cares about the programs instead of waging an
all-out war on the programs.''
   The congressional investigation of HUD may expand to the Senate,
where the Banking Committee plans a Thursday vote on whether to
launch its own inquiry.
   The four Washington field office workers who were reassigned,
including the office's former director, will be placed for up to 90
days in non-management positions at four separate offices at HUD
headquarters, agency spokesman Robert Nipp said Monday.
   The four were placed on 30-day administrative leave at the start
of the investigation last month. That period expired Monday and HUD
officials decided to give the four 90-day temporary assignments as
the investigation continues.
   An audit of the Washington field office uncovered lax financial
and management controls that allowed private closing agents hired by
HUD to handle single-family property to delay payments to the
government and in some cases not make them at all.
   The four workers are I. Margaret White, who had headed the
district field office for five years; Robert B. Warner, its director
of housing management; Charles W. Womble, a loan specialist in the
single-family home divisions; and Everett Rothschild, who headed the
field office's property disposition division.
   The field office oversees HUD properties in the District of
Columbia and parts of Maryland and Virginia.
</TEXT>
