<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-ExxonValdez 1stLd-Writethru a0494 07-11 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0494,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to UPDATE with Coast Guard identifying Valdez
as likely source of oil slick. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil inside the hull of the crippled tanker Exxon
Valdez, washed away by the sea, was the likely source of a 10-mile
oil sheen off the Southern California coast, a Coast Guard official
said today.
   Concern about the offshore oil slick and the discovery of five
flaps of steel hanging from the bottom of the tanker will delay the
disabled tanker's entry into San Diego Bay at least several days.
   Preliminary results of test samples taken from the oil slick have
not yet confirmed that the oil came from the tanker, said U.S. Coast
Guard Cmdr. Jack Scarborough, captain of the Port of San Diego.
   However, Scarborough said, Exxon officials agreed that the Exxon
Valdez was the likely source.
   Although Exxon officials had maintained the inside of the tanker
was thoroughly cleaned before it began the journey from Valdez,
Scarborough said: ``They were wrong. The ship is not squeaky clean.
That's a discrepancy I can't explain.''
   The oil slick today was about 10 miles long and 25 yards wide,
Scarborough said, smaller than the 18-mile-long sheen visible from
the air Monday.
   Because oil floats, officials planned to flood the tanker's cargo
tanks with seawater, pushing the residual oil up inside the vessel,
Scarborough said.
   Once the leaking oil problem has been resolved, the tanker can be
brought in to calm waters so divers can repair the flaps of steel
hanging as much as 40 feet beneath the tanker.
   The ship that spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil off Alaska
was about 50 miles southwest of Point Loma today, Scarborough said.
   The tanker moved slowly under its own power while Coast Guard
officials reviewed test results of samples taken from the oil in the
ocean, Coast Guard Lt. Larry Solberg said.
   ``She's not going anywhere,'' Solberg said of the tanker. ``We've
told them they can't come any closer.''
   Exxon Shipping Co. spokeswoman Carrie Chassin said she was not
sure when the Valdez would be cleared to dock.
   The 987-foot ship, damaged March 24 when it smashed into a reef
in Alaska's Prince William Sound, is to be repaired at National
Steel and Shipbuilding Co., where it was built in 1986.
   The tanker, under tow since leaving Alaska on June 23, had an
uneventful trip until the final leg of its 2,500-mile journey.
During the Coast Guard's inspection, an underwater camera showed
that five metal plates had peeled away from the hull and were
hanging from the frame.
   The loose steel increased the vessel's draft to as much as 65
feet, making it impossible for it to travel through a San Diego Bay
channel averaging 40 feet in depth, Solberg said.
   ``This all happened in transit,'' he said. ``It wasn't this way
when they left. There are pieces of the steel shell plating, the
hull itself, that have basically been torn away due to the wave
action.''
   Also Monday, officials downgraded the amount of oil spilled when
a Greek tanker ran aground June 23 off Newport, R.I., to one-fifth
the original estimate of 1.6 million gallons.
   In Boston, Gary Ott, of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, said less than 300,000 gallons of No. 2 heating oil
spilled from the World Prodigy off Rhode Island.
   Officials said the initial estimates were wrong because the
remaining oil from the tanker was mixed with water when it was
removed.
   In Philadelphia, the captain and eight crew members of a
Uruguayan tanker that spilled more than 300,000 of heavy heating oil
into the Delaware River on June 24 tested negative for drugs, their
lawyer, Raymond Letulle said Monday. The urine tests were taken the
day after the spill, he said.
   The Coast Guard boarded the Presidente Rivera right after the
accident and ``saw no evidence that there was any problem with
alcohol,'' Letulle said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
