<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     07-11 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Says Nicaragua Harassing, Reporters, Political Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department accused the Nicaraguan
government of harassing reporters, opposition figures and observers
and called for a halt so elections set for next year can be
credible, a department spokesman said Tuesday.
   Spokesman Richard Boucher said the United States is ``very
concerned about the way things are going in Nicaragua,'' where
elections are scheduled for February.
   ``Sandinista harassment of the press, the opposition and
observers, whether done through brute force or through the use of
transparent legalisms, must cease if the elections scheduled for
February 1990 are to command respect both within Nicaragua and
internationally,'' Boucher said at a regular briefing.
   ``We urge the Sandinistas to reconsider their current course of
action,'' he said.
   Nicaragua and other Central American nations signed a peace
accord calling for the elections last February. Under the agreement,
the U.S.-backed Contra rebels opposed to the Sandinistas are to be
abolished.
   Boucher cited three recent instances in Nicaragua that he said
were inconsistent with the Sandinista's ``professed commitment'' to
a pluralistic society.
   First, he said a Sandinista mob attacked two correspondents from
La Prensa with rocks and rotten eggs on June 20 in the city of Leon.
   On July 7, the Sandinistas expelled Nicaraguan-born Antonio
Ibarra Rojas, a sociology professor at Dubuque University in Iowa
who had come to Managua as an electoral observer on behalf of
Freedom House, a human rights group.
   Finally, Boucher said, the Sandinistas denied permission to the
United Nicaraguan Opposition to hold a march in the city of Ocotal
on the grounds that UNO is not a political party.
   ``The United Nicaraguan Opposition, of course, is the umbrella
organization of democratic parties from right to left which oppose
Sandinista repression,'' Boucher said.
   He refused to say whether the Sandinistas' recent actions could
jeopardize an agreement on aid to the Contras forged this spring
between Congress and the White House. The issue is likely to surface
this fall in Congress, he said.
   The Bush admninistration, in a break with the previous
administration, worked out a compromise with Congress to give the
Contras $49.8 million in non-military aid.
   While forgoing military assistance to the rebels, President Bush
put the ball in the Sandinistas' court, saying that regime must
honestly comply with promises to encourage democracy and freedom.
   Last month, Nicaragua's foreign minister, Miguel D'Escoto,
accused the United States of spreading ``systematic lies'' to
discredit Nicaragua and its preparations for free elections in 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
