<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-11 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed as Ethnic Violence Flares Anew in Nagorno-Karabakh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Azerbaijanis were ambushed Tuesday,
apparently by Armenians, and two were shot and killed as ethnic
rioting flared anew in the troubled southern region of
Nagorno-Karabakh, Tass said.
   In a separate incident, soldiers trying to clear roads around
Stepanakert, the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh, were pelted by
stones and shot at with hunting rifles, and 19 suffered injuries,
Tass said.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is predominantly Armenian and Christian,
although it is located within the predominantly Moslem republic of
Azerbaijan.
   In the ambush near the village of Kirkidzhan, on the outskirts of
Stepanakert, two Azerbaijanis wer shot to death and a third was
seriously wounded, Tass said. Although Tass did not identify the
attackers, the ambush apparently was the work of Armenians.
   The report said tension was continuing to rise in the Caucasian
Mountain enclave, which for nearly two years has been the scene of
sharp conflict between the Armenian majority and Azerbaijanis.
   Interior Ministry troops and police were on alert in the region,
with troops patrolling in cars and helicopters, Tass said.
   On Monday, unidentified people had tried to block roads in the
region, and that ``clashes of large groups of population with the
use of firearms ... and bottles filled with incendiary liquid became
more frequent,'' Tass said.
   On Tuesday in Stepanakert, Armenians blockaded streets with iron
plates and telegraph poles, and in the village of Khodzhali,
Azerbaijanis built barricades of cars, it said.
   Interior Ministry soldiers trying to clear roads in the area
around Stepanakert were ``pelted by stones from the crowd and fired
upon with hunting rifles,'' and 19 were injured.
   Azerbaijanis near the regional administrative center of Askeran
stopped a police car and tried to seize the officers' weapons, the
news agency said. One of the officers was injured in the struggle
before another police detail restored order, it said.
   The strife in Nagorno-Karabakh began when the Armenian population
there and in neighboring republic of Armenia began protesting
because the largely Moslem republic of Azerbaijan administered the
enclave.
   Officials in Moscow sought to defuse the tension by creating a
commission to exercise administative control of Nagorno-Karabakh in
January, but the troubles have continued.
   A commission on Nagorno-Karabakh established by the new Congress
of People's Deputies will review seven proposed solutions for the
ethnic conflict, government officials have said.
   On May 9, authorities took further steps to curb the unrest by
lengthening the curfew there.
</TEXT>
