<FIRST>r i AM-SovietJews     07-11 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Jews,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>World Jewish Congress Office Slated for Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Jewish Congress, which opened
its first office in a communist country this week, could open one in
the Soviet Union within two years, said the group's president said
Tuesday.
   Edgar M. Bronfman also said his talks with Hungarian leaders
convinced him they are committed to transforming the country into a
democracy.
   The new office opened Monday in the Hungarian capital, with a
staff of five, is designed to work with Hungary's 80,000 Jews and
with the small Jewish populations in other East European countries
outside the Soviet Union.
   ``My guess is that the WJC will have an office in the Soviet
Union within the next two years,'' Bronfman told reporters. ``We
would like to open up an office in the Soviet Union because there
are so many Jews there.''
   Bronfman said the Soviet Jews, estimated to number anywhere from
1.8 million to 3 million, would first have to become more organized
and join the World Jewish Congress to clear the way for the office
in Moscow.
   He also said that while an office had been ``agreed upon in
principle'' with the Kremlin, the timing still was not certain.
   ``The situation in the Soviet Union has improved enormously as
far as the Jewish population is concerned, both in terms of cultural
and religious freedom, and in terms of emigration,'' Bronfman said.
   After years of thwarting such emigration, the Soviet Union has
begun allowing thousands of Jews to leave each year.
   Bronfman met with various Hungarian leaders, including Premier
Miklos Nemeth and Minister of State Imre Pozsgay, during his
three-day visit to Budapest.
   ``It's clear that they want this country to become a democracy,''
Bronfman said, speaking just hours before the scheduled arrival of
President Bush.
   Bronfman continued: ``They are very anxious to have a lot of
capital investment. They don't expect any debt forgiveness.''
   Hungary, with a population of 10.5 million people, has a nearly
crushing foreign debt of $17 billion.
   Earlier Tuesday, Bronfman received a government award in
recognition of his efforts to promote Hungarian-American relations.
   The congress, based in New York, represents Jews in 70 countries
around the world.
</TEXT>
