<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Terrorist     07-11 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Terrorist,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interim Government Will Not Act on U.S. Request for Suspected Terrorist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected Palestinian terrorist won't be
extradited to the United States during the three-month duration of a
new conservative-communist coalition government, the justice
minister said Tuesday.
   Minister Fotis Kouvelis said the decision will be made by the
government emerging from elections in October.
   Mohammed Rashid, 39, is accused of planting a bomb on a Pan Am
jumbo jet in 1982. A Japanese teen-ager was killed and 15 other
people were wounded in the blast over Hawaii.
   Greece's Supreme Court on May 12 upheld an extradition order
sought by the United States. But the justice minister has final say
on all extraditions.
   U.S. officials have described the case as a test of Greece's
willingness to fight international terrorism.
   The former socialist administration had postponed the decision on
Rashid until after June 18 general elections.
   But after no party won a majority in the vote, the conservative
New Democracy party and communist-led Coalition of the Left and
Progress decided to govern together for three months.
   Kouvelis is one of two ministers appointed by the communists. The
other is Interior Minister Nikos Kostandopoulos, a lawyer who fought
Rashid's extradition case.
   Rashid, held since his arrest at Athens airport in May 1988, was
sentenced to eight months' jail on March 28 on charges of attempting
to escape after makeshift knives were found in his cell.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization claims Rashid is an officer
in its military branch called Mohammed Hamdan, 34. PLO officials
deny charges he is a terrorist and describe the extradition request
as a plot to discredit them.
</TEXT>
