<HEAD>Soviet Television Shows Bush-Walesa Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television on Tuesday broadcast a brief
report on the meeting between President Bush and Polish labor leader
Lech Walesa in the port of Gdansk, birthplace of Solidarity.
   Soviet media, which until recently had branded Walesa and his
independent Solidarity trade union as anti-socialist, now carry
neutral and in some cases positive reports about the moderate Polish
opposition.
   Reports have critized radical Solidarity groups that refused to
take part in parliamentary elections.
   The main Soviet evening television news program ``Vremya''
reported that Bush, ``on an official visit to Poland, arrived in
Gdansk and met with Lech Walesa, chairman of the Solidarity trade
union.''
   It also said Bush met with Polish leader Wojciech Jaruzelski and
showed footage of that meeting.
   Bush later flew to Hungary for a visit before attending an
international economic summit in Paris.
