<DOCNO> AP890711-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1619EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ForeignAid     07-11 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foreign Aid,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Aid Bill Bogged Down in Partisan Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee drafting a foreign aid
bill broke up in bitter partisan dispute Tuesday after its
Democratic chairman complained Republicans were not going along with
a compromise worked out with the Bush administration.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., had proposed a compromise to the $14.3
billion money bill for the fiscal year that begins this Oct. 1,
shifting $166 million into categories the administration wants _
primarily military aid to friendly countries.
   But as the meeting of the Appropriations Committee's Foreign
Operations panel began, Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., asked to be
allowed to offer an amendment that would cut development aid to
China through the International Development Association.
   Obey, seeing the move as an effort to score political points at
the expense of Democrats, reacted angrily: ``Unless we have
bipartisan agreement, we don't have any intention of supporting the
agreement worked out with the administration. It's just that
simple.''
   Ranking GOP subcommittee member Mickey Edwards of Oklahoma, his
voice rising, said Obey was asking for too much. There would be no
``gag rule,'' he declared. ``You can play games all you want.''
   Responded Obey: ``If I buy this amendment, I want to know what it
gets us.'' Obey later adjourned the meeting indefinitely and told
reporters he was tired of taking the heat for pushing an unpopular
bill which the White House wants far more than does Congress.
   The bill in dispute appropriates money for the full range of U.S.
foreign aid programs for the coming year, from subsidies for
military equipment purchases to aid for health and development in
the Third World.
   At the same time, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee failed
for the fifth time to muster a quorum needed to take action on its
own foreign aid bill, which would set the policies under which the
aid money would be spent.
   Committee Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., said he would try
again Wednesday to get enough senators together so the measure could
be sent to the full Senate.
</TEXT>
