<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Draft     07-11 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Draft,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Freed from Soviet Military Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislature voted Tuesday to allow students
drafted into the Red Army to be discharged before they complete
their two-year service, Tass reported.
   The move was seen as another step to scale back the Soviet
military.
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov proposed the measure, and it was met
by ``a storm of applause, unprecedented in the new Soviet
parliament,'' the official news agency said.
   The Supreme Soviet decreed that 175,000 students will be relieved
of military service in the next two months.
   The step had been suggested by legislators speaking to the
Supreme Soviet's parent body, the Congress of People's Deputies,
which met May 25 to June 9.
   It was an expansion on plans Tass announced April 11 for students
to serve only one year in the military instead of 18 months in the
army and air force or two years in the navy.
   The Defense Ministry had announced in March that students could
defer military service until after graduation.
   Previously, all Soviet men between the ages of 18 and 25 were
eligible for the draft and there were no exemptions for students.
   Tass did not give a vote for the Supreme Soviet's approval of the
discharge. It was the first lawmaking action the new body has taken
since it went into session June 10. The Supreme Soviet had been
focusing on reviewing the candidates Ryzhkov nominated for his
Cabinet.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has taken several steps since
coming to power in 1985 to decrease military spending and reduce the
Soviet arsenal. In December, he announced that Soviet troops would
be cut by 500,000 and military spending would be reduced by 14
percent.
   Gorbachev's reductions would cut the Soviet armed forces to
3,760,000. The United States has about 2.13 million men and women in
active duty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
