<DOCNO> AP890711-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1648EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-House-Mexico     07-11 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House-Mexico,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Urges Bush to Pressure Banks on Mexico Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday urged President Bush to
pressure private U.S. and foreign banks to negotiate larger debt
forgiveness agreements with Mexico.
   The action, on a 331-77 vote, was a reaffirmation of a plan
introduced earlier this year by Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady.
   The reduction should be big enough to allow Mexico ``to achieve a
sufficiently positive rate of economic growth to ensure the
maintenance of social and economic stability,'' according to the
non-binding resolution.
   The House action also urged U.S. banking regulators _ the Federal
Reserve Board and the Comptroller of the Currency _ to make banks
set aside more reserves for covering impaired foreign debt.
   Mexico and its 15 main creditor private banks said over the
weekend that they are close to reaching an agreement in principle on
a package that could reduce Mexico's debt service costs by $3
billion a year.
   Mexico asked for a 55 percent reduction in the $54 billion it
owes private lenders, about $15 billion of it to U.S. banks, after
Brady unveiled his Third World debt relief plan in March.
   The banks, led by Citicorp, Manufacturers Hanover and Chemical
Bank in New York and Bank of America in San Francisco, have offered
a 35 percent reduction if the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund guarantee interest payments on the remaining balance.
   Brady's plan offers private banks government-backed guarantees
they will be paid interest on the remaining balance if they
voluntarily reduce the debt Third World countries owe them.
   ``The Mexican deal is going to be the model for implementation of
the Brady plan,'' said Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y.
   However, opponents complained that the guarantees will perpetuate
a taxpayer bailout of poor lending decisions made by the private
banks.
   ``In the end, the U.S. taxpayer is going to be left holding the
bag,'' said Rep. Toby Roth, R-Wis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
