<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Bush     07-11 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Bush,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Poles America Stands With Them</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50,000 people gave President Bush
a hero's welcome Tuesday at the worker's monument where Solidarity
was born in a wave of labor upheaval. ``America stands with you,''
Bush said.
   They chanted ``Stay with us'' and ``Long live Bush!'' during an
emotional rally just outside the Lenin Shipyard, after Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa asked Bush to amplify a $115 million U.S. aid
plan with his support for a $10 billion private-investment rescue
package.
   About 25,000 people were packed in around the monument while at
least an equal number lined the 2.5 miles of streets as Bush's
motorcade drove from a lunch at the home of Walesa to the yard.
   An interpreter for Mrs. Bush quoted Walesa as telling the crowd:
``There have been many demonstrations in this place, and I have
never in my whole life seen anything like this.''
   Bush paid homage to Polish workers who have struggled since 1970
for freedom and a better life, contributing to the dramatic
democratic reforms now taking place in the country.
   Walesa hosted a homestyle private lunch for the president and
raised the possibility of even more aid to Poland by Western nations
than the $115 million announced by Bush on Monday.
   Solidarity argues that the help is needed to ensure that public
unrest does not upset the delicate progress toward democracy. But it
agrees any aid should have tight controls on it, so it is not wasted
as it was in the past.
   After Bush's departure for Budapest, Walesa's spokesman issued a
statement quoting Walesa as saying the six points the president
presented in parliament were ``an important idea,'' but adding:
   ``We hope that these will not be the only sums and projects. We
especially count on this after the Paris summit,'' referring to the
economic summit of seven industrial nations that begins Friday.
   In his speech at the workers monument outside the shipyard _
three soaring steel-plated crosses topped by anchors _ Bush invoked
the spirit of President John F. Kennedy's 1963 speech at the Berlin
Wall.
   ``To those who think that freedom can be forever denied, I say:
let them look at Poland,'' Bush said.
   ``To those who think that dreams can be forever repressed, I say:
let them look at Poland. ...
   ``Today the brave workers of Gdansk stand beside this monument as
a beacon of hope, a symbol of that dream. And the brave workers of
Gdansk know Poland is not alone. America stands with you.''
   The phrase brought a roar of applause and renewed chants of
``Long live Bush.''
   The president repeated throughout the visit that the United
States was willing to help Poland but that Poles themselves must
accept further sacrifice.
   Bush sought to inspire his listeners, telling them that Poles who
came to American built a better life in one generation and they
could do the same too, this time at home in Poland.
   If he was a young Pole, he added, he would remain at home and not
emigrate.
   ``Stay with us, stay with us,'' the crowd chanted back to Bush
amid laughter.
   Before taking leave of the workers, Bush and Walesa together
faced the monument and raised their arms in a ``v'' for victory, a
sign used by Solidarity.
   The president rounded out his visit to Poland with one last
meeting and farewell from Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   ``We have sown new seeds,'' Jaruzelski told Bush. ``I am
convinced ... this visit will contribute to the development of
comprehensive bilateral cooperation.''
   An official commentary issued by the PAP news agency declared the
visit ``a success of both sides'' sealing the return of normal
U.S.-Polish relations after the breakdown of the martial-law years
in the early 1980s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1713EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Evangelicals     07-11 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Evangelicals,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Evangelicals Open Conference in Manila</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 4,000 evangelical Christians
opened a conference Tuesday to forge new strategies for spreading
the faith in a rapidly changing world.
   The goal is to preach to everyone in the world by the end of this
century and try to take advantage of political changes such as
liberalization in the Soviet Union and the growth of the faith in
developing countries.
   Delegates to the 10-day convention, dubbed ``Lausanne II'' after
a similar gathering in Lausanne, Switzerland, in 1974, represented
191 countries, making it one of the largest gatherings of its kind,
organizers said.
   In a keynote address, the Rev. Leighton Ford, chairman of the
Lausanne committee that is sponsoring the conference, said the
evangelical movement was facing new opportunities.
   ``Now, we wait expectantly to see what the new openness and
longing for freedom in our world _ as shown in the spirit of
`glasnost' and the events in China _ will mean for the future of the
gospel,'' said Ford, a Canadian.
   Ford said he welcomed delegates from the Soviet Union, Poland,
Czechoslovakia, Hungary, East Germany, Romania, Cuba, Mozambique and
other communist countries to the convention.
   But another official said the Soviet delegation had not arrived
and that the list of those who are in Manila has not been finalized.
   Ford also noted an increase in interest in evangelism among major
Christian denominations.
   ``Now, we do not hear the word `moratorium' and many of these
same historic churches are re-thinking the need for agressive
missionary outreach and some have called for the '90s to be a decade
of evangelism,'' said Ford, a brother-in-law of the American
evangelist, the Rev. Billy Graham.
   Graham was set to speak at the Manila conference but commitments
in London prevented him from coming, organizers said.
   Ford said that by the year 2000, world evangelicals should be
able to reach 2.5 billion people who have not heard the gospel.
   He also cited the increase in the number of missionaries from
developing countries and the need to face economic and social issues
in spreading the faith.
   ``Then, our world was not quite so clearly aware of the
`troubles' in Northern Ireland or of apartheid in South Africa,
where the gospel has been wrapped in the sectarian robes of race and
power,'' Ford said. ``Now, we are aware and we stand with our
brothers and sisters in those areas where they seek to faithfully
live and speak for Chirst.''
   He told the delegates they must find ways to make the faith
attractive to people in widely differing parts of the world.
   ``Indians see Christ's peace in a way that Englishmen don't.
Brazilians see it in a way that Nigerians don't. Pacific Islanders
see it in a way that Germans don't,'' Ford said. ``But as we focus
on these next 10 days on Christ, we may learn to procalim his peace
as He did.''
   Earlier, Thomas Wang, Lausanne II international director, said
continued suffering has helped in the steady growth of Christian
churches in China since the world's most populous country fell under
Communist rule in 1949.
   ``Suffering is one of the important reasons for churches to
grow,'' said Wang, and American. ``I believe that has been the main
reason for the Chinese churches to grow from 800,000 members in 1949
to 50 million today.''
   China forced a halt to religious activity during the 1966-76
Cultural Revolution, but since has allowed churches to reopen.
   Wang said some 300 Chinese church representatives had been
expected to attend the Manila conference, but China's crackdown on
the democracy movement has made it virtually impossible for Chinese
to obtain exit visas.
   Wang said he expected seven Chinese church leaders who already
were outside China when the crackdown began to attend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
