<FIRST>u i AM-Where'sBush?     07-11 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Where's Bush?,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm Brings Change in Plans, Confusion, Disappointment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The thunderstorm that soaked crowds
waiting to see President Bush left some Hungarians with no glimpse
of him at all _ including a military honor guard that had stood at
attention through a driving rain but was bypassed by the
presidential entourage.
   ``Nobody told us a damned thing,'' fumed a militarty officer, who
asked not to be named.
   For at least 10 minutes of driving rain, the guard had waited in
front of a red-carpeted reviewing stand for Bush to review the
troops after speaking in Lajos Kossuth Square.
   But Bush discarded his planned speech, spoke briefly to thank the
thousands of Hungarians for braving the hurricane-like winds that
preceded his arrival and then was whisked to his limousine for a
ride of a few hundred yards to a side entrance of the nearby
parliament building for a state dinner.
   Others who had braved the rains shared the honor guard's
frustration as Bush abandoned the second half of the planned
welcoming ceremonies.
   Indeed, thousands of wellwishers had positioned themselves for
the military review, the playing of the U.S. and Hungarian anthems
and the formal presentation of flowers.
   After Bush's limousine whisked by, many in the crowd rushed to
the front entrance of parliament in a futile effort to catch a
glimpse of the president, who was already inside.
   Hungarian military officials scurried around trying to find out
whether the program had been changed and, finally, one agitated
officer ordered the honor guard to march away.
   Despite the abrupt change in plans, Hungarians were still
delighted that Bush had come.
   ``It was well worth waiting in the rain,'' said Agnes Varnai, a
young Budapest advertising worker. ``This was a good thing, it will
take a few days for it to sink in.''
</TEXT>
