<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FAA-Busey     07-11 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FAA-Busey,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>New FAA Administrator Plants Flag, Takes Oath</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Adm. James B. Busey IV planted a bright
orange flag on a Federal Aviation Administration stage Tuesday and
took the oath as administrator of the 50,000-employee agency.
   ``You've got to plant your own flag now. In the Navy, you used to
have people do it for you,'' Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner
told Busey before swearing him in on a stage decorated with the
bright FAA banner.
   Skinner said Busey was taking on a harder job than his own. The
former commander of U.S. Navy forces in Europe succeeds Allan
McArtor, who resigned as FAA administrator in February.
   The FAA oversees nonmilitary aviation and includes air traffic
control operations that monitor and guide aircraft through U.S.
skies. It also is responsible for the safety of all types of
aircraft.
   Among challenges Busey faces are the need to modernize and expand
the air traffic control system, protect the safety of the nation's
aging airliner fleet and meet what he said is the threat of
``state-sponsored terrorism.''
   Skinner, who has kept a high profile on aviation issues during
the four months the agency was without a permanent head, said he did
not know Busey before beginning the process of searching for a new
administrator. But he said he was convinced Busey is the
most-qualified man for the job.
   Congress had to pass special legislation to allow Busey to serve
at the top of the civilian agency while retaining his Navy
retirement status. The law creating the FAA says its administrator
must be a civilian, although similar legislated exceptions have been
made in the past.
   The admiral received no opposition during confirmation hearings.
   Busey, who rose from an enlisted man to four-star admiral during
37 years of Navy service, has no civilian aviation experience. He is
a pilot, however, and had been commander of the naval air systems
command.
   Busey, in brief remarks, gave no indication of policies he would
pursue but said he would work to keep the skies safe and planned to
travel extensively to FAA facilities ``where the rubber meets the
road.''
   The swearing-in ceremonies, broadcast by satellite to 33 FAA
facilities, featured an original song by an FAA choral group, a
prayer by a minister and the singing of an expanded version of The
Star Spangled Banner by a soprano. Both the minister, Harold Pratt,
and the singer, Sandra Buchanan, are also FAA employees.
</TEXT>
