<FIRST>r w AM-GunLiability     07-11 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gun Liability,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>DC Council Cancels Vote on Gunmakers Liability Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia Council on Tuesday
canceled a vote on legislation aimed at holding handgun
manufacturers financially liable for injuries and deaths caused in
shootings.
   The bill, apparently the first of its kind in the nation, had
faced an unfriendly reception in Congress, which has the power to
review and reject any law passed by the council.
   Councilmember Wilhelmina Rolark said she was withdrawing the bill
because court cases in which plaintiffs are suing handgun
manufacturers have not yet been resolved.
   Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., a frequent critic of the district
government, had threatened to block the legislation. He likened the
bill to an attempt ``to hold Black and Decker responsible for `The
Texas Chainsaw Massacre.'''
   Del. Walter Fauntroy, D-D.C., told the council in a letter
delivered on Monday that the bill was likely to be rejected by the
House.
   ``There were simply not the votes to support the bill,'' said
councilmember Charlene Drew-Jarvis. ``It could cause problems ... on
the Hill.''
   ``The council's action shows enlightened foresight,'' Parris said
in a statement released after the bill was pulled back.
   Richard Gardner, state and local affairs director of the National
Rifle Association, had contended the bill was unconstitutional. He
said it would limit interstate commerce, a regulatory right reserved
for the federal government.
   The bill, given preliminary approval by an 8-4 vote two weeks
ago, was created in an attempt to stem a drug-related wave of
murders and other violent crime.
   Through Tuesday, 229 persons had been killed in Washington in
1989, compared with 159 by the same time last year. In 1988, a
record 372 persons were killed.
</TEXT>
