<FIRST>u a AM-NursingContract     07-11 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Contract,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>RNs At NorCal's Largest Pediatric Hospital Walk Off Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of nurses demanding higher pay to
ease a nursing shortage went on strike at northern California's
biggest pediatric hospital Tuesday, forcing the transfer of nearly
100 critically ill youngsters.
   ``We're special people with special skills and we need special
pay,'' said a 34-year-old registered nurse, who identified herself
only as Jean.
   She joined the line outside Children's Hospital when the night
shift ended and the strike began at 7 a.m. Some 200 nurses picketed.
   A line of ambulances began moving the young patients, some of
northern California and northern Nevada's most critically ill
children, shortly after midnight, an operation officials didn't
expect to end until Wednesday.
   Doctors and management took up some nursing duties, said hospital
spokesman Steve Tiger.
   Patients were sent mostly to other San Francisco Bay area
hospitals, but Tiger said many might go to hospitals as far away as
Los Angeles and Seattle.
   The strike came after the California Nurses Association,
representing 700 nurses at Children's, rejected a wage offer of 18
percent over two years by a 4-1 margin Monday night. The nurses'
previous contract expired June 30.
   The nurses are demanding a two-year, 26 percent raise.
   ``If we don't do enough to attract people, we won't have the best
and the brightest nurses around for these children,'' said intensive
care nurse Karen Cooper.
   She called the strike ``a painful step'' to avert an even worse
labor crunch in the 1990s. A nursing shortage has hobbled hospital
throughout the country.
   No new talks were scheduled. Hospital administrator Tony Paap
said the hospital will not improve its offer, and he predicted a
long strike.
   ``We feel like the nursing union is disrupting the children's
care in the misguided hope of ending a nationwide nursing
shortage,'' said Tiger.
   Tiger denied there were ``real staffing shortages at this
hospital.'' At 6 percent, Children's has the lowest vacancy rate
among nurses in California, he said.
   Approximately 90 of about 140 patients were to be transferred and
about 10 others were to be discharged, leaving only some of the most
severely ill.
   Many of the youngsters at the hospital, which is one of only 14
in the nation with a pediatric trauma center, are premature, have
lung or heart ailments or are burn patients, said nursing supervisor
Dorothy Holmes.
   The hospital postponed elective surgery and stopped admitting
patients from the emergency room. Walk-in emergency care will be
offered, and general admissions will be done on a case-by-case
basis, Tiger said.
   Children's nurses now make between $32,000 and $39,000, which has
made them among the highest paid in the nation. But because of
recent wage increases at other facilities, CNA officials fear nurses
will leave Children's.
   The union is seeking salaries that would range between $39,400
and $49,100.
</TEXT>
