<FIRST>r w AM-US-PuertoRico     07-11 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Puerto Rico,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Says Senate Plan Would Give Puerto Rico Greater Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Justice Department official said Tuesday that
a Senate proposal to ``enhance'' Puerto Rico's commonwealth status
``would render the island virtually independent of U.S. authority in
many areas.''
   ``The governor of Puerto Rico would be granted an unprecedented
and truly extraordinary power to certify that a federal law or a
federal regulation is inapplicable to Puerto Rico,'' Edward S.G.
Dennis told a hearing of the Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee.
   Dennis, acting deputy attorney general, said the proposal for the
enhancement of commonwealth ``also would grant Puerto Rico much
greater advantages than any other area under U.S. sovereignty that
is not a state.''
   ``So long as Puerto Rico remains under the sovereignty of the
United States, it is essential that this fact be made clear. ...,''
Dennis told the committee.
   He advised the committee to make clear that any ``autonomy''
provided the commonwealth be ``limited to internal affairs.''
   ``Congress retains the authority to legislate with respect to
Puerto Rico,'' he added. ``Federal law may not be pre-empted or
nullified by the local government.''
   Dennis told the committee the proposal for statehood is ``the
least problematic'' and said most people understand what statehood
means. But he advised the committee to make sure that any vote for
independence would be a vote for ``full independence.''
   Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., chairman of the committee, told
the administration spokesman he believes the commonwealth should
have as much autonomy as is possible, and also urged full
citizenship be allowed for the first generation should the voters of
Puerto Rico choose independence in a plebiscite scheduled for 1991.
   Johnston said he said he would favor the right of those Puerto
Ricans wishing to retain U.S. citizenship to do so but does not
believe it should extend to their children.
   During the morning session in a three-day round of hearings on
Puerto Rico's status, the chairman needled Bush for declaring his
personal preference for statehood and expressed hopes the
administration would be ``evenhanded'' in its treatment of the
upcoming plebiscite.
</TEXT>
