<FIRST>r w AM-GratefulDead-Malaysia     07-11 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grateful Dead-Malaysia,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grateful Dead Give Congress an Earful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Grateful Dead, trading guitars for
briefcases, came to Congress Tuesday to draw attention to the
Malaysian rain forests, an issue they say is new to most of their
``Dead Head'' fans.
   Jerry Garcia, Bob Weir and Mickey Hart, members of the band that
has attracted devotion from fans for about two decades, said they
hoped to focus public awareness on the drive to stop destruction of
the rain forests.
   While the three said they were eager to promote the cause among
their fans, Garcia seemed to enjoy sparring with Rep. Claudine
Schneider, R-R.I., who suggested the band encourage ``Dead Heads.''
   ``I would guess that about 90 percent of the Dead Heads don't
vote,'' Schneider said at the hearing sponsored by the Congressional
Human Rights Caucus.
   ``That's about right,'' responded Garcia, who said many people
need a specific, positive reason to vote.
   When Schneider told Garcia she entered politics because she
``wanted to change the world,'' the guitarist said she need not
worry. ``We're on the team,'' he said.
   Then Garcia asked the congressional panel, ``Where are the rest
of the people on the human rights caucus?''
   Only six members of the 185-member caucus attended the hearing.
   Garcia, wearing his gray hair in a ponytail and smoking
cigarettes in a no-smoking room, said he'd never been to Malaysia
but was captivated by the rain forest issue because ``I'm an
earthling on this planet.''
   Deforestation has become a top priority of environmentalists
around the world who say that denuding the land destroys species of
plants and animals, creates water pollution, encourages the
spreading of the desert and leads frequently to flooding and
mudslides.
   Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., co-chairman of the caucus,
discussed how the tropical forests in Malaysia, specifically in the
Sarawak region of Borneo, are being destroyed at a rapid rate. At
the same time the inhabitants of the rain forests are being
resettled and some have been jailed for attempting a blockade to
stop logging on their ancestral lands.
   Gilman has introduced legislation to protect such peoples
throughout the world.
   Other legislation pending in Congress authorizes suspension of
duty-free treatment to wood products unless the affected countries
implement reforestation programs.
   Weir, a guitarist with the Grateful Dead, said that some
estimates are that tropical rain forests around the world might be
destroyed in 50 years unless efforts are made to stop logging.
   In Malaysia, much of the logging is done by Japanese cartels that
use the wood for disposable chopsticks.
   Several representatives of the Malaysian Embassy attended the
hearing but were not impressed with the testimony or a film that
showed the plight of the people on Sarawak.
   An embassy official called the film sensationalist and said many
people were not informed about the Malaysian reforestation efforts.
   As for the Grateful Dead, the counselor said, ``I don't know of
this band.''
</TEXT>
