<FIRST>r a AM-FaithfulHusband     07-11 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Faithful Husband,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Man to Be Faithful to His Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered a man who fathered six
illegitimate children to refrain from having more kids with anyone
except his wife.
   Derone Suber, in court to plead guilty to stealing a city
sanitation truck, got a lecture from Judge Frank Eppes on the need
to own up to responsibility.
   Suber, 26, has six children from several women. He fathered his
first child when he was 13.
   ``The state's got to pay for him and his children,'' said Eppes.
``This is one of the most tragic things I've seen in court in a long
time.''
   At first, Eppes wanted to make Suber visit schools or churches.
But Suber, who uses a walker because of injuries suffered when he
crashed the struck in 1986, would have difficulty meeting that
sentence, said his lawyer, W. Barry Bland.
   Eppes then placed Suber on five years' probation with the
condition that Suber not have children with anyone but his wife.
   Civil libertarians questioned the appropriateness of the sentence
but a criminal law scholar said it probably did not violate Suber's
rights.
   Bill McAninch, a professor at the University of South Carolina
Law School, said cited state laws prohibiting fornication and
adultery and said that defendants on probation are required to obey
all state laws.
   ``I guess what he's doing is just singling out one part of the
law,'' said McAninch, who specializes in criminal and constitutional
law.
   The matter probably would not become an issue unless Suber
violated the terms of his sentence and Eppes decided to enforce it,
said Steven Bates, executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union of South Carolina.
   Bland said he may appeal the sentence.
   In April, the 66-year-old judge came under fire for springing
soul music legend James Brown from prison for a day to sign
autographs.
</TEXT>
