<FIRST>r a AM-Exercise-Punishment     07-11 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exercise-Punishment,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Says Push-Ups Are Corporal Punishment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gym teachers and coaches may not use
push-ups and extra laps as punishment, says the state Department of
Education.
   The agency issued an advisory _ which doesn't have the force of
law but guides districts _ warning that any forced exercise that
causes pain or discomfort is banned under a 1987 state law against
corporal punishment.
   The advisory was not issued in response to any specific
complaint, officials said.
   Singling out an individual for wind sprints, push-ups or laps
because of lateness, dropping a ball or missing a tackle is illegal,
said Milton P. Wilson, pupil personnel specialist for the state
Department of Education.
   Instead, a student who is late for team practice could, for
example, be benched while others play, the advisory said.
   Some coaches said they didn't believe laps or push-ups were
effective motivators anyway. Others ridiculed the advisory.
   ``It's another attempt by the government to mandate everything,''
said Elk Grove High School football coach Ed Lombardi. ``Pretty
soon, you won't even be able to blow your nose.''
</TEXT>
