<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-11 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Killed in Guerrilla Rocket Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas bombarded the capital
with rockets Tuesday, killing four people shortly after the
Soviet-backed government announced a unilateral cease-fire to mark a
Moslem holiday.
   After the attack, Afghan Foreign Ministry spokesman, Mohammad
Nabi Amani warned of growing public anger against Pakistan for its
support of the guerrillas and warned that Afghanistan would strike
back.
   Meanwhile, hundreds of Afghans marched through Kabul urging the
government to take military action against Pakistan, where most of
the insurgents are based.
   The Moslem guerrillas, supported by the United States, have
fought an 11-year war against the Soviet-backed government.
   On Tuesday, at least six rockets slammed into Kabul after a week
of intensified guerrilla attacks on the capital.
   On Monday, at least 55 rockets hit the city of 2.25 million
people, killing 18 civilians and two soldiers and wounding 51
people, the government said. Hospital sources said that at least 165
people, including 22 children, were hurt in the bombing, which also
destroyed a weapons depot near the airport.
   But in a statement issued by the government-in-exile in
Islamabad, the guerrillas denied firing rockets at civilian targets.
   ``Mujahedeen commanders around Kabul and other cities have strict
instructions to aim only at the enemy's military installations and
to be careful not to miss their targets,'' the statement said.
   The guerrilla-controlled Afghan News Agency charged that
government troops fire rockets at civilian targets to discredit the
mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors.
   The rocket attacks came despite the cease-fire announced by
President Najib to celebrate the three-day Eid al-Azha, or Feast of
Sacrifice, which begins Thursday.
   Najib's spokesman, Sarwar Yourish, told reporters that government
troops would lay down their weapons from midnight Tuesday until
midnight Saturday to observe the festival. Eid al-Adha is the
three-day holiday marking the end of the annual Moslem hajj, or
pilgrimage, to the holy cities of Mecca and Medina.
   Hundreds of people marched in at least three rallies staged by
the governing People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, calling for
military action against Pakistan.
   Najib's government has frequently accused Pakistan of direct
involvement in rocket attacks on Kabul, a charge that the government
in Islamabad denies.
   ``There is a growing resentment and anger among the Afghan people
against Pakistan which is directly involved in the war against us,''
Amanis said. ``The people of Afghanistan want the government to take
serious measures against Pakistan.''
   He did not specify what measures might be taken. But diplomatic
sources said the government was seeking the backing of public
opinion for a possible strike on rebel bases inside Pakistan.
   Afghanistan and the Soviet Union have alleged that the
guerrillas, along with Pakistani military advisers, are planning an
offensive on Kabul. Up until last week, guerrrilla efforts were
concentrated on the city of Jalalabad.
   The Soviet Union withdrew the last of its 115,000 troops on Feb.
15 under a U.N.-mediated accord ending nine years of military
involvement in Afghanistan. Moscow, however, has continued to supply
arms to the Kabul government.
   In Moscow, the official Soviet news agency, Tass, said that
``decisive retaliatory measures will be taken by Afghanistan'' in
response to Pakistani support for the guerrillas.
   ``In this case, responsibility for the consequences will rest on
the Pakistan military,'' Tass said.
</TEXT>
