<FIRST>u i AM-Bush&amp;Walesa     07-11 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush &amp; Walesa,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Lavish Dinner in a Very Comfortable Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush sat down for lunch with
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa at his home Tuesday to a menu of
turkey, roast beef, pork and plenty of politics.
   Commenting on the huge banquet, Bush said, ``My mother taught me
to eat what's before you. In this house, I would weigh 300 pounds.''
   Accompanied by his wife, Barbara, Bush went to Walesa's home in
this seaport city in a gesture of respect for the trade union leader
who helped spark a political revolution in Poland.
   Walesa, the father of eight children, told Bush, ``I'm trying to
keep my kids out of politics.''
   Bush replied, ``It's hard to do. How about your wife? Can you
keep her out of politics?''
   ``It's different with wives,'' Walesa replied, sitting alongside
his wife, Danuta, in their small dining room. Walesa, who is toying
with the idea of running for the new but powerful post of president
of Poland, did not elaborate about wives.
   Later, Walesa said that ``my primary appeal and request'' to Bush
was for a $10 billion package of assistance for Poland. Bush called
the proposal interesting and emphasized that Walesa was not asking
for outright cash but for investment assistance.
   Walesa's two-story brick and stucco home at 54 Polanki Street is
not a typical Polish residence, which frequently is nothing more
than a cramped apartment.
   Walesa's home is located on a big plot of land, surrounded by a
chain-link fence topped with barbed wire, and boasts a small pond,
an orchard of pear and apple trees and a carefully tended flower
garden.
   The two-car garage behind the house is topped by a large
satellite dish for receiving television programs.
   A huge pile of sand and lumber in the rear gave a hint of
Walesa's plans for home improvements.
   ``The house is fairly old and it needs to be remodeled almost as
much as Poland does,'' Walesa said. ``I really am trying to get to
work on fixing it up. And I hope I'll be just as successful with
Poland.''
   Bush replied, ``You must have very cold winters up here, right?''
   Walesa acknowledged that he lives a privileged lify
   ``If I were an ordinary Pole,'' Walesa said, ``I wouldn't be able
to afford it.''
   Explaining his ability to afford such a comfortable home, Walesa
said, ``I used to live in an ordinary apartment. But it's because I
make some money out of Solidarity.''
   He did not explain, but previously has said that he purchased the
home a year ago with earnings from his autobiography, ``A Way of
Hope.''
   The Walesas' dining room was adorned with a woven wall hanging of
the Polish Black Madonna and Child, a common religious symbol in
this country. Walesa offered Bush beer but he declined. The two men
and their wives each lifted a glass of vodka to salute each other at
the remarkable occasion.
   The menu, prepared by family friends, was this: smoked eel and
salmon with lemon slices; a traditional cold vegetable soup called
choldnik; roast beef, turkey, schnitzel and pork loin with mushrooms
garnished with pineapple, grapes, peaches, orange slices, radishes
and new potatotes.
   Desert was mixed Jello with nut topping.
</TEXT>
