<SECOND>AM-Stones Tour, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0645,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Back Together Again: Stones to Hit the Road</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to RECAST lead; CLARIFY chronology of 1986
album; and ADD concert dates; picks up 9th graf, `Tickets for ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rolling Stones announced Tuesday they have
patched things up and will play a 29-city North American tour this
fall _ their first tour since 1981.
   ``This tour is not historical,'' Mick Jagger said. ``I don't see
it as a retrospective tour, I don't see it as a farewell tour. It's
the Rolling Stones in 1989.''
   Jagger was joined by bandmates Keith Richards, Ron Wood, Bill
Wyman and Charlie Watts in the news conference at Grand Central
Terminal. The tour, which will begin Sept. 1, will coincide with the
release of their album ``Steel Wheels.''
   The band's most recent album was 1986's ``Dirty Work,'' which was
followed by three years of internal conflict and a rumored break-up
of the band.
   Jagger and Richards, the focus of the controversy, hugged and
mugged before a roomful of reporters when asked if they had patched
up their differences.
   ``The answer to that is we both gave up masochism,'' said
Richards, who last year released his first solo album, ``Talk Is
Cheap.'' The band will play only Stones material on this tour.
   The Stones, whose hits include ``(I Can't Get No) Satisfaction,''
``Jumpin' Jack Flash'' and ``Honky Tonk Women,'' become the latest
veteran rock act to take to the road this summer.
   The Who is in the middle of a 25th anniversary tour, while the
Allman Broters Band, the Doobie Brothers and the Jefferson Airplane
are also taking to the road.
   The first leg of the tour includes these dates:
   Buffalo, Rich Stadium, Sept. 1; Toronto, Exhibition Stadium,
Sept. 3; Pittsburgh, Three Rivers Stadium, Sept. 6; East Troy, Wis.,
Alpine Valley, Sept. 9 and 11; Cincinnati, Riverfront Stadium, Sept.
14; Raleigh, N.C., Carter-Finley Stadium, Sept. 16; St. Louis, Busch
Stadium, Sept. 17; Philadelphia, John F. Kennedy Stadium, Sept. 21;
Washington, Robert F. Kennedy Stadium, Sept. 25, and Cleveland,
Municipal Stadium, Sept. 27.
   Additional dates will be announced later for shows in New York;
Los Angeles; Vancouver, British Columbia; Atlanta; Tampa, Fla.;
Foxoboro, Mass.; Detroit; Montreal; Indianapolis; Minneapolis;
Jacksonville, Fla.; Houston; Birmingham, Ala.; Dallas; Denver;
Kansas City, Mo.; Ames, Iowa; New Orleans, and Miami.
   Tickets for most Rolling Stones shows, priced at $28.50, will go
on sale Saturday.
   No financial details were announced, but Rolling Stone magazine
reported the band had signed a $65 million tour deal.
   But the band said money isn't their motivation for reuniting and
going back on tour.
   ``That's The Who!'' Wood joked.
</TEXT>
