<HEAD>Bush Gives Raincoat to Elderly Woman In Budapest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush doffed his raincoat
during a downpour Tuesday and presented it to an elderly woman who
wildly applauded his speech in Kossuth Square.
   The impromptu move startled Secret Service agents, but Bush
seemed pleased with what he had done.
   Asked hours later after a dinner in the parliament with Communist
Party Chairman Rezso Nyers what he would use in its place, Bush
said: ``It's not going to rain anymore. It's not going to rain on my
parade.''
   The elderly woman had waited for about an hour to hear Bush's
speech. She stood behind a rope, without shelter from the rain, but
seemed not to mind. Most of the people around her were older and
shielded from the downpour, so evidently she caught the President's
eye.
   The tumult that followed the president's gesture prevented
reporters from getting close.
