<FIRST>r w AM-Cambodian-Newspapers     07-11 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodian-Newspapers,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Sued Over Visa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization of newspaper editors and a
congressmen have sued the government, alleging that a Cambodian
journalist and politician was illegally denied a visa to come to the
United States.
   The State Department twice rejected Khieu Kanharith's request for
a visa after he was invited to the United States to speak, according
to the lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court.
   Kanharith, a journalist, is a member of the National Assembly in
Cambodia.
   The communist government was installed during the 1978 Vietnamese
occupation of Cambodia and is engaged in negotiations with a
political faction led by U.S.-supported Prince Norodon Sihanouk.
   The State Department said Kanharith was ineligible for a visa
because there is reason to believe he would engage in activities
prejudicial to the public interest or would endanger U.S. security.
   U.S. Rep. Chester Atkins, D-Mass., and the American Society of
Newspaper Editors filed the suit against Secretary of State James
Baker III and Attorney General Dick Thornburgh.
   The refusal to grant a visa based on political associations or
anticipated political speech violates federal law and violates the
First Amendment rights of the plaintiffs to exchange ideas on
matters of vital national interest, said the suit.
   The Foreign Relations Authorization Act says no alien may be
denied a visa because of beliefs that, if engaged in by a U.S.
citizen, would be protected by the Constitution.
   The suit seeks a court order that Kanharith be issued a visa.
   Atkins wants Kanharith's views on the current political situation
in Cambodia and U.S. policy options there. ASNE wants Kanharith to
meet with its members to discuss events in Cambodia.
   The American Civil Liberties Union is representing the
plaintiffs, who include the American Friends Service Committee and
John McAuliff of the U.S.-Indochina Reconciliation Project, who
issued the invitation.
</TEXT>
