<FIRST>r w AM-NorthwestSale     07-11 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest Sale,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Requests More Information on Northwest Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department asked Tuesday for
more details about a Los Angeles investor's plan to buy NWA Inc.,
parent company of Northwest Airlines.
   Alfred Checchi announced the nearly $4 billion deal June 19, but
department approval is required for the sale to proceed. The
department is examining impact of the proposed sale on the airline's
financial health.
   Government aviation analyst John V. Coleman asked in a letter to
Checchi's Wings Holdings Inc. about the extent of foreign
involvement in the sale. Investors include KLM Royal Dutch Airlines
and several U.S. financial interests, including Bankers Trust New
York Corp.
   Coleman wants the identity and citizenship of each partner and
the percentage share of each person in the partnership, as well as
whether any of Bankers Trust's shares would be held for other
owners, who they are and their citizenship.
   He also wants a detailed statement of the sources and uses of
acquisition financing, the investors' appraisal of NWA assets, any
plans for sale or aquisition of airline assets and details of debt
financing to be used in the purchase.
   Transportation Samuel Skinner told NWA Chairman Steven Rothmeier
in May that the department was concerned the acquisition might have
a ``substantial adverse impact'' on Northwest's financial structure.
   But after Skinner met with Checchi two weeks ago, a department
spokesman said the secretary was keeping ``an open mind'' on the
sale proposal.
   The sale would raise NWA's debt to $3.7 billion from $945
million, according to Standard and Poor's Corp. The credit-rating
agency said interest on the debt would cut the airline's operating
cash flow nearly in half.
</TEXT>
