<FIRST>u w AM-Hastings 1stLd-Writethru a0695 07-11 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: New throughout with Dredge testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed associate of Florida underworld
figures told senators at a closed-door hearing Tuesday how he helped
federal investigators stalk federal Judge Alcee L. Hastings in a
bribery conspiracy case.
   ``We think his testimony went well in terms of presentation of
how the investigation got under way,'' Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas,
told reporters after William Dredge finished testifying at Hastings'
impeachment trial.
   Hastings, a U.S. District judge from Miami, is accused of
plotting to get a $150,000 payoff, of lying about it to a jury that
acquitted him in 1983 and of improperly disclosing information
obtained through a federal wiretap.
   Hastings, the first black federal judge in Florida history, was
impeached by the House a year ago and is now on trial in the Senate,
which could remove him from the bench and take away his $89,500
annual salary.
   A committee of senators is hearing the impeachment charges voted
by the House. Eventually, the full Senate will have to vote on the
charges.
   Hastings lost a bid Tuesday in the U.S. Supreme Court to halt the
impeachment trial.
   Justice Byron R. White, without comment, denied Hastings' request
to block the proceedings on grounds that the Constitution ``will
suffer irreparable harm'' if the impeachment trial is allowed to
proceed.
   Hastings had sought a temporary order pending a decision from the
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia on his
efforts to block the Senate proceedings.
   Senators cleared the hearing room and put in effect a television
blackout as Dredge was brought in through a rear entrance. Lawmakers
said he apparently is in fear of mob retaliation because of his
testimony for the government in a racketeering trial involving the
late Florida mob boss Santo Trafficante.
   Bryant said that Dredge was not part of the government's witness
protection prorgram but that he ``is an elusive figure who can only
be located through the FBI.''
   ``On cross examination, I think I showed up the slippery little
worm,'' Hastings' attorney Terence Anderson told reporters after
Dredge had been escorted out a rear exit and the hearing reopened to
the public.
   Anderson that both he and a number of senators hearing the
evidence struck at Dredge's credibility by dwelling on his criminal
associations.
   ``Everyone involved in this knew that Dredge had a lengthy
criminal record spanning his entire adult life,'' Bryant told
reporters. He said efforts to remove Hastings from the bench do not
hinge on the credibility of Dredge's testimony and that all of the
key points are corroborated by other witnesses.
   The purpose of the testimony was to show the senators that there
was nothing out of the ordinary about the genesis of the Hastings
investigation.
   Prosecutors say Dredge was used as a go-between by Washington
attorney William Borders to solicit a $150,000 payoff in exchange
for Hastings' keeping two brothers, Frank and Thomas Romano, out of
prison. They had been sentenced by Hastings to three years each
following a racketeering conviction involving a loan from a
Teamsters Union pension fund.
   The Romano brothers expressed no interest in the alleged scheme.
Dredge, at the time under indictment on charges of conspiracy to
distribute quaalude tablets, became an informant against Borders,
who eventually went to prison.
   Attorneys and lawmakers said that in his five hours of Senate
testimony Dredge essentially retold the story in detail.
   Hastings emerged from the hearing room for the noon recess and
told reporters that Dredge was ``an incredible liar.''
   ``Quite frankly, I don't like him,'' Hastings said. ``Never did,
never will.''
   He said Dredge's testimony ``has been carefully rehearsed and
gone over repeatedly.''
   In other action, House members acting as prosecutors failed in
efforts to ask Miami criminal lawyer Neal Sonnett about a telephone
call between the Romano brothers and an associate, Phillip Moscato.
Prosecutors say he met with Dredge in a garage to discuss the legal
problems of the Romanos.
   Sonnett told reporters Frank Romano said that Moscato met with
Dredge and reported back that ``a Washington big shot'' could
intervene in the case. But the Romanos said they had no interest in
such a deal, Sonnett said.
   He said he informed the government of the conversation when the
chief of the Justice Department's strike force telephoned him hours
after Borders' arrest to warn him that reporters might be calling
him to task about the case.
   The Senate panel's chairman, Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., ruled
out Sonnett's testimony concerning the telephone conversation after
Anderson objected that it was hearsay evidence passed through
individuals who are either dead or too disabled to testify and
``every one of whom except Mr. Sonnett is a member of one organized
crime family or another.''
   Justice Byron R. White, without comment, denied Hastings' request
to block the proceedings on grounds that the Constitution ``will
suffer irreparable harm'' if the impeachment trial is allowed to
proceed.
   Hastings had sought a temporary order pending a decision from the
U.S. Court of Appeals here on his efforts to block the Senate
proceedings.
</TEXT>
