<FIRST>u w AM-PlagarismCharge     07-11 0951</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plagarism Charge,940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biologist To Appeal Plagarism Charge By National Institutes of Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A biologist charged with plagiarism said
through an attorney Tuesday that he will fight his exclusion from
government research grants and will defend himself before a
university committee investigating the charges.
   C. David Bridges, a former eye researcher at the Baylor College
of Medicine in Houston and now on the faculty of Purdue University,
is charged in an investigation by the National Institutes of Health
with using research data from a team of Harvard scientists to
prepare a research report that he published under his own name.
   A report on the NIH investigation, obtained Tuesday by The
Associated Press through a Freedom of Information request, charges
that Bridges made unauthortized and uncredited use of information
from a Harvard University manuscript that had been sent to him for
peer review.
   The report recommends that Bridges be blocked from receiving
federal grants and excluded from peer review programs for 10 years.
   Bridges' attorney, George Bishop of Houston, denied the charges
and said the researcher will appeal the NIH action to the the
Department of Health and Human Services. Bridges also plans to fight
an investigation now underway at Purdue.
   The NIH report said Bridges used Harvard experiment data, which
he saw in the manuscript, to conduct his own experiments and then
published an article in the journal Science without acknowledging
the Harvard source, the NIH said.
   ``Plagiarism _ the unauthorized use of another person's
experimental protocol, in this case _ is a serious misconduct of
science in that it undermines the entire peer-review process upon
which the scientific enterprise is dependent,'' the NIH
investigation report said.
   An NIH committee that reviewed the investigation said it was
``clearly dismayed'' by Bridges' behavior, and said that using
information obtained from unpublished manuscripts sent for peer
review ``is reprehensible and cannot be tolerated by scientists or
the public.''
   In addition to barring Bridges from federal grants and from peer
review programs, the NIH report also recommended that all current
NIH grants to Bridges be terminated and that the journal Science be
notified of the investigation report.
   In what it called a ``Notification to Readers,'' the journal
Science will announce the result of the NIH investigation in an
issue to be released Friday.
   Carol Rogers, a spokeswoman for the American Association for
Advancement of Science, publisher of Science, said the association
also will notify science libraries so that the notificiation will be
cross-referenced in computer files of scientific research.
   Bishop, the Houston attorney representing Bridges, said the NIH
ruling was unfair because Bridges was never given a chance to
confront his accusers or to know precisely the charges.
   ``The charges were reviewed in secret,'' said Bishop. ``We think
if the facts are heard, Bridges will be vindicated.''
   Bishop said the NIH action keeps Bridges from making a living and
could threaten his position at Purdue.
   ``Those grants are important to keep his livelihood going,'' said
Bishop, and loss of the grants ``probably will have some effect'' on
Bridges' tenured position at Purdue.
   ``These colleges and universities, particularly in biological
sciences, depend a great deal on grants to keep going,'' said Bishop.
   The lawyer said that an NIH grant given to Bridges already has
been cancelled and that two research assistants have been laid off.
   A woman who would identify herself only as an administrative
assistant at Bridges' Purdue office in West Layfayette, Ind., said
the researcher was not accepting telephone calls and was referring
all calls to Bishop.
   Joe Bennett, a spokesman for Purdue, said that a committee of
faculty members has been named to investigate the charges against
Bridges. He said the committee may review the entire case before
taking any action.
   ``The matter is not really a Purdue issue,'' said Bennett, since
the alleged plagarism took place before Bridges joined the Purdue
faculty in May, 1987. But Bennett said Purdue could take action if
it appears the university would be affected.
   According to the NIH report, Bridges, a professor in the
department of ophthalmology at Baylor College in Medicine at the
time researching the biochemistry of vision, was sent a Harvard
University manuscript to review for a National Academy of Sciences
publication in the summer of 1986.
   Science research manuscripts are usually reviewed by experts
before they are published in learned journals. The NIH investigation
said Bridges declined to review the manuscript and returned it to
the academy in September 1986.
   The Harvard research described in the manuscript had to do with a
identifying an enzyme called isomerase which plays a role in vision.
   In November 1986, Bridges submitted a manuscript on isomerase to
the British journal Nature, but the article was turned down in
January 1987. Bridges revised the article and then submitted it to
Science which published it in June, 1987.
   Prior to the publication, Harvard researcher Robert R. Rando
learned of Bridges' reports and discovered that Bridges had received
an advance copy of the Harvard study. Rando also noticed the
similarities of the two studies.
   Another researcher arranged a meeting between Bridges and Rando
and Bridges agreed to credit the Harvard research in his Science
article. This was not done, however.
   Bridges resigned from Baylor in August 1987, and went to Purdue
in October. The month before he left, a Baylor committee, prompted
by Rando, began investigating the Science article. The committee
concluded that Bridges did misuse the Harvard information.
   Since a federal grant was involved, Baylor notified the NIH which
started an investigation last October. The report, including
recommendations for debarring Bridges, was completed last month and
approved by Dr. James B. Wyngaarden, the director of the NIH.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
