<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-11 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0646,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir May Urge New Peace Vote to Save `Unity Government'</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS graf after 8th, `The army...' to UPDATE with three wounded.
Pick up 9th pvs, `On the...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir may call a new
Cabinet vote on his proposal for Palestinian elections in a bid to
save his coalition government from collapse, his spokesman said
Tuesday.
   Spokesman Yossi Ahimeir confirmed newspaper reports Shamir is
considering a vote to head off moves by the center-left Labor Party
to quit Shamir's coalition Cabinet and force national elections.
   ``You could say that the prime minister's office should be
interested in holding such a vote,'' said Ahimeir.
   A vote could be called within the next three weeks, before
Labor's Central Committee meets to make a final decision on Monday's
recommendation by its 120-member Leadership Bureau that the party
quit the government. Labor is the junior partner in the coalition
dominated by Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc.
   Renewed Cabinet backing for Shamir's peace initiative would aim
at assuaging Labor and Washington, which both object to hard-line
conditions the Likud bloc has set for the proposal, Israeli dailies
reported.
   The peace plan has split Shamir's bloc, with Likud hawks forcing
the condition that the government first crush the 19-month uprising
against Israeli occupation of the occupied Gaza Strip and West Bank.
   In the Gaza Strip on Tuesday, two men masked with Arab kaffiyeh
scarves shot and killed 28-year-old Palestinian Faqar Mohammad
Hassan on a downtown Gaza City street.
   The army said it believes the slaying was carried out by fellow
Palestinians. Hassan's death comes as attacks are increasing on
fellow Arabs accused of collaborating with Israel.
   Also in Gaza, three Palestinians were shot and wounded in clashes
with Israeli troops, Arab reports said. The army said it was
investigating.
   On the West Bank, leaders of the revolt called a general strike
in Ramallah and El-Bireh to protest Monday's shootings of three Arab
youths by Israeli soldiers and security agents, Arab reports said.
The army confirmed two of the deaths and said it is investigating
the third.
   ``Killing our people will not stop the intefadeh!'' slogans
painted on walls in the towns north of Jerusalem declared, using the
Arabic term for the rebellion.
   The deaths around Ramallah would bring to 558 the number of
Palestinians killed in the uprising. Thirty-three Israelis also have
been killed.
   In the West Bank town of Nablus, the fundamentalist Islamic Jihad
movement praised a Palestinian's attack last week on an Israeli bus,
and urged the ``use of bullets and grenades'' in their fight against
Israel.
   ``We praise the mujahed (holy warrior) who destroyed the Zionist
bus,'' said a Jihad leaflet, the first issued in the occupied
territories by the organization. Fourteen civilians died, including
two Canadians, when the Palestinian refugee wrenched the wheel and
forced the bus down a ravine.
   If Shamir calls a vote, he would urge Cabinet ministers to reject
amendments to the election plan such as those he accepted as Likud
policy to quell a revolt in his right-wing bloc, the daily Haaretz
reported.
   The Cabinet, which first approved the plan by a vote of 20-6 in
May, probably would defeat the amendments, Israeli papers said.
   Shamir's original proposal calls for Palestinians in the occupied
territories to elect representatives to negotiate with Israel for
autonomy. The final status of the territories would be decided later.
   The proposal is vaguely worded to try to win Palestinian approval.
   But Likud hard-liners, led by Industry Minister Ariel Sharon,
voted for tough conditions including demanding more Jewish
settlements in the occupied lands and that Israel refuse to give up
land seized in the 1967 Middle East War.
   U.S. Middle East policy calls for Israel trading land for peace
and an end to Jewish settlements.
   Shamir insists the Likud conditions do not affect the formal
government peace proposal.
   On Monday, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said he is
sending envoys to Jerusalem to determine if Israel is serious about
its peace initiative, which U.S. diplomats are trying to sell to the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
