<SECOND>AM-Bush-Appointments,174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Nominates Judges for D.C., Maryland, Virginia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is nominating Clarence Thomas,
chairman of the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, to
succeed Robert B. Bork on the U.S. Circuit Court for the District of
Columbia.
   Thomas, who is black, is a former assistant secretary for civil
rights in the Education Department.
   Bork quit the bench after he failed to gain Senate confirmation
for a seat on the Supreme Court.
   The traveling White House also announced on Tuesday three other
judicial nominations as well as a new assistant secretary of the Air
Force for space policy.
   He is Martin C. Faga, and he would succeed Tidal W. McCoy if
confirmed by the Senate.
   The other judicial nominations were:
   Marvin J. Garbis to be U.S. District Judge for the District of
Maryland. He suceeds Joseph B. Young.
   Rebecca Beach Smith to the U.S. District Court for the eastern
district of Virginia. She would succeed D. Dortch Warriner.
   S. Jay Flager to be U.S. Circuit Judge for the Federal Circuit.
He would succeed Shiro Kashiwa.
