<DOCNO> AP890711-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 2029EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     07-11 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Jet Fighter Flies Low Over West Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian jet fighter roared over Moslem
west Beirut Tuesday just one day after army commander Gen. Michel
Aoun reportedly threatened air strikes against Syrian gunboats
blockading Christian ports.
   Later, heavy artillery duels broke out between Syrian and
Christian gunners and shells fell on residential districts on boths
sides of the dividing green line, wounding two civilians in a
western district. There were no immediate reports of casualties in
Christian districts.
   Police said a British-made Hawker Hunter flew low over west
Beirut's waterfront, from where Syrian howitzer batteries have
shelled the Christian coastline for the past four months.
   An eyewitness said on condition of anonymity the aging warplane
``came very low over the sea from the north, flew low over the
boulevard and then turned west and north again.''
   A police spokesman said Syrian gunners, manning dozens of
multi-barrelled anti-aircraft launchers did not fire at the jet
fighter, which flew at 800 feet.
   ``It seems their radars did not detect the Hawker Hunter because
it flew very low,'' the spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   A source with Aoun's air force, also speaking on condition of
anonymity, described the overflight as an exercise. He refused to
elaborate.
   It was the first overflight of west Beirut by one of Aoun's three
operational Hawker Hunters since the confrontation with the Syrians
and their militia allies broke on March 8 when Aoun blockaded
illegal militia-run ports. The Syrian-Druse alliance responded by
blockading the 310-square-mile Christian enclave.
   In addition to the Hawker Hunters, Aoun has eight French-designed
Gazelle helicopter gunships.
   Aides to Aoun said Monday the 54-year-old Maronite Catholic
general was planning air strikes against six Syrian gunboats
blockading the 28-mile coastline of the enclave north of Beirut.
   The aides declined to comment when asked how the Christian
warplanes could confront the Syrian air force's superior Soviet-made
jet fighters.
   The Syrian gunboats this week intercepted at least three cargo
ships carrying food supplies and a fuel tanker headed for the
Christian enclave.
   A 25-foot Lebanese motor yacht, the Sea Tiger, with six men on
board was released from a Syrian naval base at Tartus north of
Lebanon and sailed to Larnaca, Cyprus, Tuesday. The boat was
intercepted by Syrian gunboats Sunday as it sailed out before dawn
from Kaslik harbor north of Beirut.
   By police count, the present round of violence in Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war has killed 405 people and wounded 1,583.
   The Syrians have an estimated 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a
1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
