<HEAD>Thunderstorms And High Temperatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell over broad sections of
the eastern two-thirds of the nation Tuesday, and uncomfortably hot
weather spread from the Plains to the East Coast.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended over the Texas Gulf Coast and
southern Louisiana, from northern Alabama to central Tennessee, and
from north-central Oklahoma to east-central Kansas.
   More showers and thunderstorms developed over southeastern
Nebraska, southwestern Iowa, south-central South Dakota, eastern
North Dakota, Minnesota, Wisconsin, northern Illinois, western
Indiana, northern Vermont and northeastern New York state
   Heavier rain during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 1.94
inches in Huntsville, Ala., and 1.13 inches in Rochester, Minn.
   Hail three-quarters of an inch in diameter fell at South Bend,
Ind., and wind gusted to 60 mph at Eau Claire, Wis.
   In the West, southern Nevada had showers
   A combination of high temperatures, high humidity and little wind
produced high heat indices during the afternoon. Advisories were
posted for sections of Missouri, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky and
North Carolina.
   Cape Hatteras, N.C., hit a record high temperature for the date
of 93 degrees. The previous record of 91 had stood since 1926.
Wilmington, N.C., tied its record of 97.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at San Simeon, Calif., to 99 at Yuma, Ariz. Tuesday's low
for the Lower 48 states was 33 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Wednesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from much
of Missouri to Illinois, southern Wisconsin, the Ohio Valley, and
north-central Texas.
   Highs in the upper 60s were predicted near San Francisco; in the
70s and 80s from New England to much of Virginia, West Virginia, the
Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the northern Plains, the
Rockies, northern Montana, and Washington state, and scattered along
the California coast; near 110 degrees over the desert Southwest;
and generally in the 90s in the rest of the nation.
