<FIRST>u a AM-CrackSentences     07-11 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack Sentences,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbors' Input Helps Judge Set Sentences In Crack Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges here have begun basing sentences for
people convicted of dealing crack cocaine on the suggestions of
neighbors and other community members.
   ``We're getting longer and more creative sentences. ... And the
letters are strengthening our resolve in these cases, also,'' said
Hennepin County Attorney Tom Johnson.
   Johnson cited the sentence of a 20-year-old drug defendant to
nearly two years in prison, rather than the probation called for by
state sentencing guidelines, after the judge received three letters
from concerned citizens.
   In another case, in addition to 90 days in jail on a drug charge,
Minneapolis resident Eli Acevedo was ordered to have no more than
six visitors per day at his home and none at night for five years.
   Judge Ann Montgomery devised that sentence after receiving a
letter from a neighborhood group which described all-day and
all-night disruption caused by a stream of visitors to Acevedo's
house.
   The county policy mirrors a year-old state law that requires that
before sentencing, probation officers assess the community impact of
narcotics in drug-dealing cases.
   Montgomery said she does not always follow victims'
recommendations, but she likes to know what the community is
thinking before issuing a sentence.
   In another sentence based on a letter to a judge, Jerome Gregory
got 90 days in a workhouse, and was ordered not to return to the
neighborhood where he was caught with crack for three years.
   Dave Murrin, a senior attorney in the county public defender's
office, said he does not believe public opinion should be used to
sway a sentence.
   ``It is like `The People's Court' for minor crimes in Russia,''
Murrin said. ``Our system of justice is not designed for individual
retribution. We are supposed to establish uniformity.''
</TEXT>
