<SECOND>AM-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0894</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Leaders Refuse to Rule Out Trial For Zhao</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with China saying the suppression
of disent should not hurt relations with Taiwan. Pickup 4th pvs, `One Major...';
INSERTS 1 graf after 8th pvs, `A trial...' to ADD comment from Wu'er Kaixi.
Pickup 9th, ``Also Tuesday...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Tuesday refused to rule out a trial and
further punishment for Zhao Ziyang, who was ousted as Communist
Party chief for opposing the military crackdown that crushed
pro-democracy demonstrators.
   ``His problem is still being investigated,'' government spokesman
Yuan Mu said at the first news conference by a high-ranking official
since troops on June 3-4 marched on Tiananmen Square and attacked
unarmed demonstrators.
   On Wednesday, China urged the rival government on Taiwan not to
let China's harsh suppression of dissent stand in the way of
improving ties between the two nations. The appeal, in a front-page
commentary in the Communist Party People's Daily, came one day after
the government expelled a Taiwanese reporter.
   When the party Central Committee ousted Zhao as secretary-general
on June 24, it accused him of supporting the protesters and
splitting the party, and said his case would be dealt with
internally. Since then, however, official criticism has escalated,
fueling speculation Zhao may stand trial.
   One major government report last week accused Zhao's aides of
collaborating with protest leaders accused of trying to overthrow
the government. It stopped short of also accusing Zhao of plotting a
coup.
   Yuan stressed the party charges and decision to treat Zhao's case
as an internal disciplinary matter are not final.
   ``How the problem will finally be dealt with will be decided
according to the findings of the investigation,'' he told more than
100 Chinese and foreign reporters.
   Premier Li Peng, a key force behind the crackdown, was quoted
last week as saying Zhao remained at his home. Putting him on trial
would be an extreme measure taken only if Zhao and his supporters
are considered a continuing threat.
   A trial may force the disclosure of details about the power
struggle that preceded the army attack and could turn Zhao into a
popular hero. The government says hundreds of people were killed,
mostly soldiers. Chinese students and Western diplomats say
thousands of unarmed civilians were slain.
   In an interview with CBS television Tuesday, student leader Wu'er
Kaixi said ``optimistically'' it would be two to three years before
there was another chance to push for democratic reform in China.
``Conservatively,'' it would be seven to eight years, he said from
hiding in Paris.
   Also Tuesday, authorities deported two reporters _ one American
and one Taiwanese _ and gave a second Taiwanese reporter 48 hours to
leave. All are accused of violating martial law bans on reporting
activity.
   They bring to nine the number of reporters ordered to leave China
since June 4. All but two were in China on tourist visas.
   The two Taiwanese, Huang Teh-pei and Hsu Lu of the Independence
Evening Post, also are accused of trying to help a student protest
leader escape China. Authorities put Huang on a plane to Hong Kong
Tuesday morning, eight days after arresting him. Ms. Hsu said she
would leave Wednesday.
   Huang reported meeting with the student, Wang Dan, on July 2. He
said in Hong Kong that security officials told him they had arrested
Wang. However, authorities refused to comment on Wang's status.
   Mark Hopkins, a reporter for the U.S. government-run Voice of
America, also flew to Hong Kong. He is the second VOA reporter
expelled since the crackdown.
   Zhao's successor as party chief, Jiang Zemin, tried Tuesday to
reassure Hong Kong residents frightened by what the use of harsh
military tactics may portend for the British colony that reverts to
Chinese rule in 1997. Many are trying to emigrate.
   ``We practice our socialism and you may practice your
capitalism,'' the official Xinhua News Agency quoted Jiang as
telling three members of committees drafting Hong Kong's post-1997
constitution.
   But he warned, ``You should not transplant capitalism onto the
country's mainland.'' Hundreds of thousands of Hong Kong residents
have marched and signed petitions to protest the military attack.
Many donated funds to the students and helped fugitives escape.
   At his news conference, Yuan said martial law imposed May 20 in
central Beijing cannot be lifted yet because ``the struggle has not
ended.'' He said some people stole guns from army trucks during the
June 3-4 attack and may cause ``further unrest.''
   There have been unconfirmed reports of attacks on troops since
army guns silenced protesters. One Westerner recently reported
seeing a naked body, possibly of a soldier, floating in a canal near
his home.
   But Yuan said foreigners should feel secure in Beijing and said
it would be unwise to wait until martial law is lifted to return.
Thousands of China-based foreign businessmen and their families fled
Beijing in the week after the army attack. Most tourists have stayed
away.
   ``Of course there will be a time limit for martial law, but even
I can't say exactly when that will be,'' Yuan said. The government
still has not lifted martial law in Tibet's capital, Lhasa, imposed
after anti-Chinese protests there March 5.
</TEXT>
