<FIRST>u w AM-IncomeLimitations     07-11 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Income Limitations,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Bill Seen as Anti-Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council passed legislation Tuesday
limiting outside income for top city officials, but not before some
council members slammed the bill as a thinly veiled attempt to
discourage Jesse Jackson from running for mayor.
   The bill, proposed by mayoral hopeful John Ray, a member of the
council, limits the outside income for the mayor and council members
to $10,000 per year.
   Another candidate for mayor, council Chairman David Clarke,
succeeded in attaching an amendment that sets a $10,000 annual limit
for royalty earnings by the mayor and council chairman.
   Jackson, whose advisors have said he is ``strongly considering''
running for mayor in 1990, was traveling in Egypt and could not be
reached for comment.
   The mayor's job pays $82,500 a year.
   One council member called the bill a ``cheap shot'' at Jackson,
who earns most of his $200,000 annual income from giving speeches.
   ``I think it looks like a cheap shot, and we always look foolish
when it looks like we're trying to keep someone from running,'' said
Frank Smith. ``It usually turns out to be a short-sighted mistake.''
   Ray said the bill is intended to prevent conflicts of interest.
He has said he began work on the bill last year after residents
residents criticized the council for voting itself a pay raise, but
he did not introduce it until Jackson began to be mentioned as a
possible candidate.
   The bill passed on Tuesday by voice vote without debate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
