<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 2121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;Ls     07-11 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Committee Members Increase S&amp;L Penalties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators trying to
reconcile differences in a $157 billion taxpayer bailout of savings
and loan losses agreed Tuesday to provide civil fines of up to $1
million a day for bank and S&amp;L fraud.
   The negotiators, aiming at having a bill ready for President
Bush's signature before Congress recesses in early August, also
eliminated a $2,500 per day cap on civil fines for minor violations
that was in the Senate version of the legislation as approved in
April.
   Under the current law, the maximum civil fine for bank or S&amp;L
fraud is generally $1,000.
   As approved Tuesday by the House-Senate conferees, maximum fines
for minor violations of federal banking and S&amp;L laws would be raised
to $5,000 with provisions for penalties up to $25,000 a day if the
violations resulted in substantial losses.
   The bill also raises maximum criminal penalties from one year in
jail and a $5,000 fine to five years and fines of up to $1 million
for each violation.
   Fraud in making loans with federally insured deposits has been
cited by the General Accounting Office as the single biggest
contributor to the S&amp;L crisis and the failure of more than 500
thrift institutions in recent years.
   Over the objections of Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, the
negotiators also agreed to mandate that the Justice Department
maintain a special fraud task force in Texas, where most of the past
abuses occurred.
   A call by the House for a second task force in Los Angeles was
deleted while Senate members of the conference committee accepted a
House provision increasing to $75 million Bush's initial proposal of
$50 million in new appropriations to prosecute S&amp;L fraud.
   The negotiators put off the two most controversial issues until
Thursday: How to finance the bailout and how much of their own money
S&amp;L owners should have to at risk to continue qualifying for federal
insurance of their depositors funds.
   Sen. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., the chairman of both the conference
and the Senate Banking Committee, tried Tuesday to tackle a third
major dispute, so-called special interest provisions inserted into
the two versions of the bill by various lawmakers over the past four
months.
   ``It's decision time, time to get some of these tough issues out
in the open and see where we are,'' he said.
   However, decisions on them also were postponed when it became
clear there were major differences in interpretations of what
constituted a special interest.
   ``One man's special interest is another man's scam,'' said Rep.
Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House Banking Committee.
   But Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said many of the provisions
labeled special interest are actually in the public's interest
because they would allow some institutions to remain open and avoid
further depletion of federal deposit insurance funds.
   Just before passing its version of the bill last month, the House
struck from the bill more than half a dozen provisions aimed
specifically at helping companies such as Sears, Citicorp, Chemical
Bank, First Interstate Bank of Los Angeles.
   However, the instigator of that move, Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa,
said Wednesday he saw ``some mischief'' in separate lists of 17 to
20 special interest provisions prepared by Senate and House staffs.
   Included on the lists were exemptions still in the House bill for
S&amp;Ls acquired by Ford Motor Co. and savings banks in New York and
New England.
   There also is a host of the provisions in the Senate bill aimed
at helping American Express, Sears, the John Hancock Insurance Co.,
Ford, Citicorp, First Interstate, Merrill Lynch, Paine Webber and
individual S&amp;Ls in Florida, Tennessee, California and Texas.
</TEXT>
