<FIRST>r w AM-GunLiability     07-11 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gun Liability,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>D.C. Council Postpones Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia City Council on
Tuesday canceled a vote on landmark legislation that would have held
handgun manufacturers financially liable for injuries and deaths
caused in shootings.
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Wilhelmina Rolark said she withdrew
the bill because court cases in which plaintiffs are suing handgun
manufacturers have not yet been resolved.
   But the bill, the first of its kind in the nation, faced an
unfriendly reception in Congress, which has the power to review and
reject any law passed by the council.
   The vote postponement came in the council's last legislative
session before the summer recess, which means the matter cannot be
reconsidered until the council reconvenes in September.
   The liability bill, given preliminary approval by an 8-4 vote two
weeks ago, grew out of frustration over the drug-related crime wave
that has surged through the nation's capital.
   Through Tuesday, 229 people had been killed in Washington this
year compared with 159 by the same time last year. In 1988, a record
372 persons were killed.
   Police blame more than 60 percent of the slayings on drugs.
</TEXT>
