<FIRST>r a AM-HeatRdp     07-11 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heat Rdp,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stifling Heats Grips South and Southeast; One Heat-Related Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Army recruits at Fort Bragg, N.C., got a break from training
Tuesday, and Nashville, Tenn., residents collected fans for the
elderly as high temperatures and humidity created sauna-like
conditions in the South and the Midwest.
   In St. Louis, the second heat-related death of the city's hot
spell was reported after the body of a 69-year-old man was found in
his home.
   In Virginia, temperatures that soared into the 90s apparently
pushed electricity demand to a record level, a utility spokesman
said.
   The mercury hit 98 degrees at Fort Bragg, prompting base
officials to issue an alert. Starting at noon, all Army units were
instructed to stop all strenuous activities and training, said a
statement by the base.
   It was 93 degrees in Cape Hatteras, N.C., breaking by 2 degrees a
record for the date that had stood for 63 years.
   In Nashville, residents collected fans for the elderly, and
business picked up at some shelters for the homeless.
   The Rev. Carl Resener, director of the Nashville Union Rescue
Mission, said he was seeing signs of heat stress among the homeless
and that bigger crowds were gathering in the air-conditioned chapel
during the day.
   In St. Louis, the body of Edward Pounds, 69, was found in his
home Monday evening, and his death was confirmed as heat-related
Tuesday, said City Health Commissioner Dian Sharma. An 81-year-old
woman was found dead in her home Saturday.
   At least seven people were treated for heat-related illnesses in
the past 24 hours, including four who were hospitalized, Sharma said.
   A heat warning was upgraded to a heat alert in the city Monday as
temperatures and humidity combined to push the heat index to
dangerous levels. Calling a heat alert triggered the opening of 32
``cooling centers'' where residents can go to beat the heat.
   ``We're expecting quite a bit of an increase in business,'' said
Vincent Wright, a spokesman at the Salvation Army, which is
operating an air-conditioned shelter.
   Virginia Power experienced power demands of 11,800 to 11,900
megawatts in the state, utility spokesman Carl F. Baab said in
Richmond.
   ``We think we set an all-time record,'' he said, but said it
would be Wednesday before the utility determined the official peak
demand.
   The previous record peak demand was set Aug. 15, 1988: 11,756
megawatts.
   Electrical consumption in Virginia hit 11,200 megawatts on
Monday, the high point for the year.
</TEXT>
