<SECOND>AM-Nielsens, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fox's `Totally Hidden Video' Makes Splash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Fox had ...,' to CORRECT to two segments, sted
three; SUBS 13th graf, `Here is ...,' to CLARIFY that ``Unsolved Mysteries''
tied with ``Night Court'' for 10th in Top 10.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fox Broadcasting's ``Totally Hidden Video''
gave the fledgling network its highest-rated premiere, following
allegations it was a ``Candid Camera'' ripoff that used actors
instead of unsuspecting victims.
   NBC easily extended its winning streak to 55 consecutive weeks.
   ``Totally Hidden Video'' tied with NBC's ``Seinfeld Chronicles''
for 21st place in the Nielsen ratings for the week ended July 9.
``Seinfeld Chronicles,'' broadcast on Wednesday, starred stand-up
comic Jerry Seinfeld.
   Fox had to substitute a part of ``Totally Hidden Video'' on
Sunday after it was learned that actors were used in three segments.
The show is billed as using a hidden camera to record the reactions
of unsuspecting people.
   Allen Funt, creator of ``Candid Camera,'' has sued Quantum Media
Inc. on grounds the show uses many of the same stunts from his 43
years of ``Candid Camera.''
   The Fox Sunday schedule also got a boost when ``Married ... With
Children,'' normally Fox's highest-rated show, got its highest
rating in a tie for 29th place.
   ``Totally Hidden Video'' got a 10.5 rating and ``Married ... With
Children'' got 10.0. In past weeks, ``Married ... With Children''
has been in the mid 40s in the rankings and had ratings of 8.6 or
lower.
   NBC's ``Cheers'' took undisputed possession of first place in the
ratings. ABC's ``Roseanne,'' tied with ``Cheers'' for first last
week, fell to 13th place thanks to Fourth of July fireworks.
   All of the network Tuesday night shows suffered because of the
holiday last week. The average ratings for all three networks fell
to 50 percent, from 63 percent the week before. ABC won the night
with a ratings average of only 8.9. ``Roseanne,'' with 12.2, was the
only show to get into double-digit ratings.
   NBC won the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings with an average of 10.1. ABC
was second with 8.8 and CBS third with 8.4.
   For the season to date from Sept. 19, NBC leads with 15.1, ABC is
second with 12.1 and CBS third with 12.0.
   The ratings is the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes
in the United States that have televisions. The share is a
percentage of sets in use.
   Here is the Top 10: NBC's ``Cheers,'' ``Dear John,'' ``The Cosby
Show,'' ``A Different World,'' CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,'' ``60
Minutes,'' NBC's ``L.A. Law,'' ABC's ``20-20,'' NBC's ``The Golden
Girls,'' and ``Unsolved Mysteries'' tied with ``Night Court.''
   The NBC summer series ``Knight and Daye'' made its debut in 16th
place.
   CBS had the highest-rated evening news show with a rating of 8.5.
ABC, which tied for first with CBS last week, was second with 8.1
and NBC was third with 7.9.
   The lowest-rated show was the ``CBS Summer Playhouse.'' The
bottom five on the networks: CBS' ``Paradise,'' CBS' ``Tour of
Duty,'' ABC's ``Have Faith'' NBC's ``The Jim Henson Hour'' and the
``CBS Summer Playhouse.''
</TEXT>
