<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearDump 1stLd-Writethru a0735 07-11 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Dump, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Regulators Raise Objections to Dump Site Planning</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs to include Glenn bill on weapons plant cleanup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators said Tuesday that the Energy
Department may be giving too little attention to issues that could
disqualify Nevada's Yucca Mountain as the site for the nation's
first high-level nuclear waste dump.
   Nuclear Regulatory Commission staff members said they were
generally pleased with the department's plan for determining the
suitability of the site as a permanent graveyard for radioactive
waste from commercial and defense nuclear reactors.
   But they raised two crucial objections to the plan and cited
several less urgent concerns.
   Commissioner Kenneth Rogers said he was especially worried that
the Energy Department was not ensuring that the most critical issues
get settled early.
   Among what Rogers described as ``killer issues'' is whether there
are active geologic faults or potentially destabilizing volcanic
activity in the area that would disqualify Yucca Mountain, about 100
miles northwest of Las Vegas.
   Another is how quickly moisture might dissolve waste and carry
radioactive atoms into groundwater supplies.
   Rogers said he was concerned that once construction gained a
certain momentum, ``a really fundamental question somehow gets lost
in the dust.''
   Initial construction work is scheduled to start in November, and
the Energy Department is to decide by 1994 whether the site is
suitable. If the NRC granted a license, wastes would start moving
into the site in 2003.
   Robert Bernero, commission director of nuclear materials safety
and safeguards, said in an interview that Energy Secretary James D.
Watkins was reconsidering that timetable as part of a ``fresh look''
at the entire program.
   The Nevada government is strongly opposed to the program. Gov.
Bob Miller recently signed a bill making it illegal for any
government body to store high-level radioactive waste in the state.
   Bernero said the NRC had concluded that the Energy Department had
produced a ``fundamentally useable'' plan for collecting and
analyzing the data necessary to decide whether Yucca Mountain was a
suitable site.
   He said the staff had two key objections to the plan: It didn't
include an adequate means of assuring the quality of the data
collected and there may be flaws in the design of an experimental
shaft to be drilled on the site.
   In a related development, the Energy Department ordered Sandia
National Laboratories, one of the major contractors on the project,
to stop work until it corrected a technical flaw in its
quality-control program.
   Meanwhile, Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, introduced legislation to
give states authority over cleanup of hazardous wastes from the
department's nuclear weapons plants without going to court. The bill
would demand a concrete cleanup schedule whenever government weapons
plants are closed.
   The bill was aimed at Ohio's Fernald uranium-processing plant and
radioactive wastes at the Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant.
   Glenn also proposed increasing the power of the Defense Nuclear
Safety Board, protecting the Energy Department's Office of
Environmental Safety and Health from future administrative
reorganizations and repealing a provision preventing the Energy
Department from paying environmental penalties.
</TEXT>
