<FIRST>u a AM-SecondAbduction 2ndLd-Writethru a0763 07-11 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0763,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Indicted on Murder Charges in Purported Abduction of Her Child</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Mrs. Sims' arrest, her mother's testimony,
explanation of charges, background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury returned a murder
indictment Tuesday against a woman whose two infant daughters were
killed three years apart under nearly identical circumstances, a
prosecutor said.
   In both cases, Paula Sims, 29, had told police the babies were
abducted by a masked gunman while their father was away at work.
   The Madison County grand jury charged Mrs. Sims with two counts
of first-degree murder in the suffocation death last spring of
6-week-old Heather Sims, said State's Attorney William Haine.
Multiple murder counts in a single death are not unusual in Illinois.
   Heather's body was found May 3 in a trash can near West Alton,
Mo., about 10 miles north of St. Louis.
   Mrs. Sims was arrested at her parents' home shortly after the
indictments were returned, said county sheriff's Sgt. Don Wein.
   She had been free on $250,000 bond after being charged earlier
with concealing Heather's death. She also was out on $100,000 bond
after being charged in neighboring Jersey County with concealing the
death of her first daughter, Loralei, who disappeared 13 days after
her birth in 1986.
   Circuit Judge Edward Ferguson granted a prosecution request that
Mrs. Sims be held without bond, Haine said.
   The first count in Heather's case alleges that Mrs. Sims intended
to kill the girl, said Assistant State's Attorney Don Weber. The
second count alleges that Mrs. Sims committed an act she knew had
the strong probability of ending in death or great bodily harm,
Weber said. The second charge is a backup in case the defense
contends there was an accidental element in Heather's death, he said.
   The grand jury is still investigating Heather's death and the
involvement of her father, Robert, 37, the prosecutor said.
   Police have said Sims told them he believes his wife may have
killed their daughters accidentally. Witnesses have said Mrs. Sims
wanted to give birth to sons and was unhappy about the girls.
   Heather was suffocated by someone who placed a hand over her
face, the pathologist who performed an autopsy on the infant has
concluded.
   In June 1986, the Simses told police that a masked gunman broke
into their home and abducted Loralei. The decomposed remains of a
baby believed to be Loralei were found several days later near the
couple's home in Brighton, a rural Jersey County community.
   Earlier Tuesday, Mrs. Sims' mother, Nylene Blew, was ordered for
the second time to testify before the grand jury after being granted
immunity from prosecution.
   She spent about two hours behind closed doors in the grand jury
room, but it was not clear whether she testified.
   Mrs. Blew refused to testify Monday, citing her constitutional
right against self-incrimination.
</TEXT>
