<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-DiscoveryChannel ADV12   07-11 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Discovery Channel, ADV 12,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday PMs, July 12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Documentary-Based Discovery Channel Growth Fastest In Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With its ``guilt-free'' programming of
documentaries, travelogues, literary adaptations and news, The
Discovery Channel has become the fastest-growing cable channel in
the nation in the past two years.
   Unlike network television, which relies on ratings to attract
advertisers, The Discovery Channel is partially underwritten by
cable operators.
   ``We have a very discriminating audience, and we want to get as
many people into that discriminating audience as possible, but we're
not willing to sacrifice the word `discriminating,''' said Greg
Moyer, senior vice president in charge of programming for the
Maryland-based channel.
   ``People have written us who say, `At last I can watch TV all
night long and not feel guilty,''' said John Hendricks, the
channel's founder.
   The Discovery Channel, which broadcasts 18 hours of mostly
foreign-produced programs daily, went on the air in 1985 with a
viewer base of 156,000 homes.
   Now it is available in 40.6 million U.S. homes, according to
figures from the A.C. Nielsen Co. The channel is available in 78
percent of cable homes and 45 percent of all homes. It has
maintained the fastest growth rate of any cable channel for two
straight years, according to Nielsen.
   The Discovery Channel is a boon to cable operators looking to
bring in new viewers, because, says Hendricks, TDC programming tends
to appeal to viewers who aren't particularly avid television
watchers. The channel is promoted in print through TDC, a monthly
magazine that features background articles relating to Discovery
Channel programs.
   Hendricks, a former university fund-raiser, conceived the idea
for the channel while researching a fund-raising project and
discovering the wealth of documentaries available to programmers.
   Among the programs viewers may see on any given day are
documentaries focusing on travel, adventure and nature. Hendricks
said programs on animals known to eat people, such as sharks and
bears, have been among the most popular. The channel's ``Shark
Week'' of programming proved sucessful enough to merit a repeat this
month.
   The channel's answer to the nightly news, ``World Monitor,''
produced by the Christian Science Monitor, takes a global approach
to current events and has received critical acclaim.
   The channel became the first U.S. television outlet to present
the Soviet news program, ``Vremya,'' nightly for a week during the
Gorbachev-Reagan summit. The channel has also presented a critically
praised, seven-part historical look at the Bible and given viewers a
live look at a coral reef in the Red Sea.
   ``We've defined the whole niche of documentary television,''
Hendricks said.
   ``When I first put together a proposal there were some people
exploring a travel channel, a science channel and others. Those were
all subniches. What we've done is define an entire niche, especially
with the word `discovery'.''
   ``The Discovery Channel is very good television, although I think
it's somewhat limited in scope,'' said Art Chapman, television
critic for the Fort Worth (Texas) Star-Telegram and president of the
Television Critics Association.
   ``I would not want my television (dial) welded to The Discovery
Channel ... but if you're saying you can rely on it for good,
dependable quality programming, yes, in that way it is guilt-free
television.''
   Hendricks and Moyer both said they take a free-wheeling approach
to programming. A live shot from an African watering hole, where
viewers would pop in from time to time to see what is happening, is
planned for September.
   ``I think there is something magic about live TV,'' Hendricks
said. ``I remember the first moment when there were live
coast-to-coast shots side by side. I think it's something to be able
to sit in your living room and be on the plains of the Serengeti.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   SUITS HIM _ Italian fashion designer Giorgio Armani has become a
benefactor of the critically acclaimed PBS series ``American
Masters,'' an anthology of documentaries saluting leading figures in
the creative arts. The agreement marks Armani's first venture into
television. ``Mr. Armani wanted to demonstrate his enormous respect
for American public television and for the spirit and achievement of
American creative artists as celebrated in this series,'' said Lee
Radziwill, who is head of special events for Armani. ...
   YO, JOE _ Bob Hope, Milton Berle and Billy Crystal are among the
stars coming out to salute veteran talk-show host Joe Franklin in
the syndicated special, ``Joe Franklin's 1st Annual 40th Anniversary
Special.'' Others include Telly Savalas, Jack LaLanne, Phyllis
Diller, Dick Clark, Valerie Harper, Douglas Fairbanks Jr. The
special will air July 21 on New Jersey-based superstation WWOR.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, July 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
