<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-AnotherLook:BirminghamRacial Adv17   07-11 0974</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Another Look: Birmingham Racial, Adv 17,0996</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Mon PMs, July 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Battles Once Fought in Streets Now Fought in Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights battles no longer are being
fought in the streets of Birmingham, where snarling police dogs and
fire hoses trained on black demonstrators made the city a symbol of
segregationism in the 1960s.
   Today the battlefield is the courtroom, and civil rights leaders
view with alarm U.S. Supreme Court decisions threatening
affirmative-action and minority business set-aside plans and
limiting challenges to racial harassment.
   The high court ruled 5-4 in June that white Birmingham
firefighters have the right to go to court to challenge as reverse
discrimination an affirmative action plan that helped increase the
number of black firefighters and officers.
   The ruling is part of ``a carefully designed plan to turn the
clock back on affirmative action, period, everywhere,'' says Richard
Arrington, Birmingham's first black mayor. ``It's going to be a
long, hot summer.''
   The city also will be among those affected by a Supreme Court
ruling that a Richmond, Va., set-aside program was reverse
discrimination. In a third ruling that worried civil rights leaders,
the court prohibited, in a North Carolina case, the use of an
anti-discrimination law by victims of racial harassment.
   The legal battle over Birmingham's affirmative-action plan could
last 10 to 15 years, said Arrington, who wants Congress to let
cities continue affirmative action ``and put behind us this old
bitter fight about race.''
   Birmingham, a city of 276,000, 55 percent black, began its
program eight years ago. Now 118 of 497 firefighters are black, as
are 38 of 151 officers.
   The city contended it has acted under a court-ordered consent
decree and that whites had a chance to complain when the plan was
being considered but did not. White firefighters say they weren't
party to the lawsuit that led to the plan, and the Supreme Court
ruling allows them to challenge it in court.
   ``We were happy with it,'' said Lt. Charlie Brush, president of
the Birmingham Firefighters Association local. A number of those who
originally challenged affirmative action are still in the department
and many haven't been promoted; others left because they were passed
over in favor of blacks.
   ``We know this doesn't end the case necessarily,'' Brush said.
   Jackie Barton, a black captain, withdrew from the union when it
hired attorneys for the white firefighters. ``I realize union
members aren't going to agree with everything the union does, but I
didn't want to pay dues to help keep myself down.''
   Barton, who was hired in 1977, said that without affirmative
action he probably wouldn't have been promoted to captain since he
was 39th on a test for applicants. He called the ruling ``a
wrongdoing to all city employees.''
   Basing promotions only on seniority would be unfair to blacks,
Barton said, because the city did not start large-scale minority
hiring until the 1970s.
   ``Firefighters can miss more questions on qualifying tests if
they have more seniority,'' he said. ``When I received my first
promotion, candidates received one point for each year of seniority.
Blacks haven't had the opportunity to be on the job as long as some
firefighters.''
   Union attorney Ray Fitzpatrick said the ruling was a step toward
ending ``race-based quota promotions'' that discriminate against
whites. The union has not developed an alternate hiring plan, he
said. ``Birmingham has never been willing to engage in any
meaningful discussions with the white employees.''
   The firefighters' case is expected to go to U.S. District Court
here for trial, but no date has been set. Fitzpatrick said the white
firefighters would like to work with the city to settle the case and
avoid a trial. ``Perhaps now that they have this additional guidance
from the court they will be willing.''
   Any settlement would have to include back pay, seniority and
promotions for those who have been passed over, he said. ``People
are being denied advancement in their jobs solely on the basis of
race and that's wrong.''
   Birmingham also is trying to settle issues raised by the Supreme
Court's ruling in the Richmond case.
   A contractors' group, Associated General Contractors, has been
fighting a program that sets aside 35 percent of city work for
minority companies. AGC won a state court ruling overturning the
program but the state Supreme Court halted implementation of the
lower-court order pending a city appeal. The sides are talking to a
mediator in an effort to settle the matter.
   The city has considered changing from voluntary goals to a
program that would set aside a fixed percentage of contracts for
disadvantaged firms instead of just black-owned firms. The idea is
that this would survive legal challenges since it would give no
preferences based on race.
   AGC claims the city has coerced white contractors into using
black-owned businesses as subcontractors on city projects. City
officials deny this, claiming the city is trying to correct decades
of discrimination.
   During the state court hearing, AGC attorney Jim Starnes said his
clients were at a disadvantage because ``almighty Big Brother
government over here can do anything it wants to do.''
   Arrington said it was important to try to help its black
businesses. ``The need is not only tied to the issue of fairness and
justice,'' he said. ``The need is also tied to the city's need for
economic development.''
   Birmingham discriminated against blacks in the 1960s and before
in housing, business, employment and voting, Arrington said.
   Citing the tests once given to discourage blacks from registering
to vote, he added, ``I grew up watching my mother and father and a
number of adults study a long list of questions they hoped they'd
know the answers to when they got to the Board of Registrars.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs July 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
