<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv12   07-11 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 12 ,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, July 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Slowdown Isn't Always Stressful: Sometimes It Brings Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In some ways economic slowdowns get a bad rap.
Ask your next-door neighbors, who probably are thanking their stars
that the slowdown has brought down interest rates.
   Like millions of others, these neighbors probably have an
interest-sensitive home mortgage that was beginning to scare the
wits out of them. Over the past couple of years it has been rising,
along with their fears.
   With good reason. Many homeowners have mortgages that, at the
upper rate limits, are capable of consuming half their take-home
pay. That, say most financial advisers, leaves an insufficient
amount for other necessities.
   It didn't begin that way. When they obtained the mortgage it was
at a rate that probably took no more than 28 percent of their
take-home pay. But even at that rate they knew it would be a
struggle, because they had other bills.
   As recently as last spring, some forecasters were talking about
even higher rates, spreading terror among homeowners. In some
instances, higher rates would mean negative amortization _ instead
of being reduced, the loan would enlarge.
   A survey in April for the International Association of Financial
Planning showed that fears of inability to pay the home mortgage
became the chief financial concern of American households.
   Asked to name their two or three biggest financial concerns, the
households interviewed put ``payments on the house'' first. A year
earlier it had ranked behind monthly bills, medical bills and
inflation.
   Among households with incomes of $50,000 and up, mortgage fears
more than tripled, according to the survey, which was conducted for
the IAFP by The Gallup Organization.
   While the survey didn't say so, many of these home loans were
obtained at first-year rates, or rates that would be suddenly
adjusted upwards for subsequent years.
   Many borrowers didn't mind that. They would have a year to
prepare, and in that time they looked forward to the value of their
property soaring. That was a soothing thought. It's the way people
think when times are good.
   The real estate market changed in the meantime. Housing prices
have actually fallen in some areas, especially where prices are high
and incomes have failed to keep pace. And interest rates are sharply
higher.
   In the three years the IAFP survey has been conducted, ``payments
on the house'' has always ranked among the top sources of anxiety.
It was listed first by 19 percent of respondents, but by 21 percent
of the higher-income segment.
   That survey showed a great deal of other financial stress in the
lives of Americans.
   Forty-three percent, for example, said they were concerned with
outliving their retirement money. When asked what plans they had for
retirement, 25 percent of the respondents said they didn't know. And
a third of them said they expected someone in their families to need
long-term medical care.
   In such a stressful environment, an economic retrenchment that
brings down the monthly mortgage payment can't be all bad.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, July 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0205 </DOCNO>
