<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ArtificialHeart ADV16-1stAdd-SUB b0insightatthishourforWednesdayAMs
07-11 0857</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Artificial Heart, ADV 16-1st Add-SUB, b0750,0876</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 15-17, Copeland has ... of view.'', to update with
donor found for heart patient; picks up 18th graf, Each of .. . The 1st
Take, b0749, will not be retransmitted.</HEAD>
<HEAD>TUCSON, Ariz.: widespread use.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   He says there is only limited desire to use the J-7 permanently.
   ``Dr. DeVries is still approved by the FDA to do three more
permanent implants and hasn't done a case in more than three
years,'' Jarvik says. ``He seems to have little further interest in
doing it.''
   Jarvik is now in New York working on a new permanently
implantable artificial heart, the Jarvik-2000.
   The National Institutes of Health, under political pressure,
announced last July that it was reversing its planned suspension of
a $20 million program to develop a self-powered, permanent
artificial heart.
   Unlike the current devices, they would not require bulky external
drive units and infection-inducing external lines. They would be
powered by transducer belts or vests and would allow the user to
move around.
   But such heart pumps are not expected to be ready for
experimental use for at least a few years. That's what prompted
Copeland to call for interim measures.
   Permanent implants would be a reasonable response to dealing with
the growing number of end-stage heart patients too sick or too old
to qualify for transplants, Copeland says.
   ``Admittedly, they wouldn't play tennis, go swimming, be too
active. They'd be tethered, but they'd be alive,'' the surgeon says.
   Copeland also says numerous questions, such as whether infection
necessarily develops inside a permanent artificial heart, need
answering before development of a new-generation device.
   Copeland says the public views permanent artificial hearts as
science fiction. If another round of permanent implants began, he
says, it would draw the kind of media attention focused on DeVries
and the first modern artificial implant patients _ Barney Clark in
December 1982 and William Schroeder in November 1984.
   As of mid-May, 106 of 146 artificial heart bridge-to-transplant
patients went on to receive transplants. Seventy-three of them
survived, says Gary Cole, executive vice president of Salt Lake
City-based Symbion Inc. An additional 35 patients did not survive to
have subsequent surgery, and the others were awaiting transplants.
   In March 1985, Copeland implanted an unauthorized device known as
the Phoenix Heart in a patient who had rejected a transplant. The
man lived on the device for 11 hours before receiving a second donor
heart but died about 36 hours later of complications unrelated to
the device.
   On Aug. 29, 1985, Copeland implanted the first Jarvik-7 to be
used as a temporary bridge, and nine days later patient Michael
Drummond received a transplant. Drummond works in a grocery store
today.
   Copeland says surgical teams have learned a great deal about
heart bridging from their limited experience.
   Copeland's team has a 34-year-old patient who on Feb. 28 received
a J-7-70 intended as a bridge, but no suitable donor heart was found
until June 20. The man has been making a slow recovery.
   A transplant optimally should be performed within three weeks
after the artificial heart is implanted because of the rapid growth
of scar tissue around it, which must be cut through and bleeds
profusely during transplantation, Copeland says.
   He speculated that such adhesions probably would be good in the
long term for a permanent implant because they bring blood around
the artificial heart ``and police it from a microbiologic point of
view.''
   Each of DeVries' permanent implant patients bled massively,
suffered the destruction of red blood cells that led to kidney
failure or developed infections that led to endocarditis, or
inflammation of the heart's lining membrane, Copeland says.
   But he says Bernadette Chayrez, his patient who survived for 244
days in 1986 on a second Jarvik-7-70, after her body rejected a
tranplant following an initial Jarvik implantation, suffered neither
endocarditis nor severe stroke.
   She did sustain a localized stroke 218 days after the second
implant and developed a chest infection a week later, neither of
which proved fatal, Copeland says. In the autopsy, the Jarvik-7
showed no sign of infection, he says.
   There are ways to prevent infections, ``and we're going to try
some of those ways. I'm not sure that we've got the answers right
here to hand out, but I think that we need to try this,'' he says.
``I don't think there's any reason for not doing it.''
   Jarvik says the question is whether more research energy and
money should be invested in compressed air-driven hearts.
   While there is ``good evidence'' that many people would live for
years, Jarvik says, the emphasis should be put on ``making something
that's really practical available. And I don't think that that's
going to be accomplished with compressed air-driven hearts.''
   ``I do think Dr. Copeland is terrific and he's done really
excellent work, and I understand his point, but I'd like to see that
energy and urgency that he suggests because of the lack of donors
directed into electric artificial heart research,'' Jarvik adds. ``I
think it would do more good in the long run.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
