<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-11 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0907</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chase Manhattan Bank has trimmed its prime
lending rate a half percentage point to 10.5 percent, and although
no other major banks immediately followed suit, experts predicted
they would do so soon as interest rates continued dropping.
   ``I'll be surprised if we go through the week and some of the
other major money center banks didn't enter the fold,'' Robert A.
Brusca, chief financial economist for Nikko Securities Co.
International, said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of an important court hearing,
Paramount Communications Inc. said it would add interest to its
hostile $12.2 billion offer for Time Inc. if certain delays prevent
it from closing the deal.
   Paramount said it had amended its offer of $200 per share in cash
for all of Time's stock to provide an interest payment of 9 percent
annually if it is unable to close the deal within 60 days after Time
either agrees or is ordered to refrain from interfering with
Paramount's efforts to obtain needed cable regulatory approvals.
   A scheduled hearing today in Delaware Chancery Court could
determine whether Paramount can acquire Time or whether Time can
complete its own takeover of Warner Communications Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury has convicted a Wall Street
brokerage of an insider trading-related charge in a 1986 stock deal
but acquitted the firm of charges in three other deals and cleared a
trader of all counts against him.
   The verdict Monday against Marcus Schloss &amp; Co. for dealings with
jailed inside trader Ivan F. Boesky's company was the first
conviction of a New York Stock Exchange-registered firm in the
government's three-year Wall Street insider trading crackdown.
   The firm faces a total fine of $1 million. Sentencing was set for
September, on a date to be set later.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CVN Companies Inc. has agreed to be
acquired by the smaller QVC Network Inc. in a deal officials hope
will make the companies more competitive against Home Shopping
Network Inc. in the video shopping industry.
   The agreement announced Monday, valued at more than $400 million
in cash and stock, is subject to approval by shareholders of both
companies as well as federal regulatory approval.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. lowered
its bid for LIN Broadcasting Corp. by about $400 million, citing a
New York court decision that was unfavorable to LIN.
   The new offer disclosed Monday reduces to about $5.36 billion,
from $5.85 billion, the total value of McCaw's bid for the 90
percent of LIN shares it does not own. Both companies are major
operators of cellular phone services.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady has
spurned a proposal from a top bank regulator to create a new
international insurance fund that would partially protect banks
against defaults by Third World debtors.
   ``We don't think that is necessary at this point in time,'' Brady
said in a briefing Monday with reporters before his departure this
week for an economic summit meeting in Paris.
   But Brady did not completely rule out the idea, offered by
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman L. William Seidman.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas' Hunt brothers did the best they could in
an ``atmosphere of panic'' after the silver market collapse in 1980,
their attorney says, denying at the start of their tax-claim trial
that they had set up ``a colossal sham'' partnership.
   However, Internal Revenue Service attorney Deborah Butler told
the judge Monday that the partnership was created to provide
``financial relief to the petitioners at a time when they needed it
very badly'' and was subject to taxes when it was dissolved in 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp. said its board had approved a
leveraged employee stock ownership plan for salaried employees and
the repurchase of roughly 11 percent of the company's common stock.
   Xerox said the employee stock ownership plan for 57,000 salaried
employees would be financed in part by forfeited merit raises and
the loss of company contributions to a 401(k) retirement plan.
   The company said Monday it will implement the plan by issuing
$785 million worth of new series B convertible preferred stock and
using the proceeds to repurchase 11 million of its 103 million
outstanding common shares.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial markets have stabilized
in response to new austerity measures imposed by President Carlos
Menem to reduce 1 million percent annual inflation and a massive
budget deficit.
   Economic measures announced Sunday night devalued the national
currency by one-half and increased gasoline prices by as much as 610
percent. The plan also envisions cutting back government spending,
selling many state-run industries, reducing subsidies and tax breaks
for private companies and enforcing widely ignored tax laws.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose Monday amid expectations of further
declines in interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
rose 14.80 to 2,502.66, extending its gain since the start of last
week to 62.60 points.
   The dollar declined against several foreign currencies.
   Bond prices rose, nudged upward by sharp declines in prices of
some key commodities.
   Corn, soybean, oat, wheat and oil futures prices all fell.
</TEXT>
