<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Pubs     07-11 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pubs,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brewers Won't Have to Sell Off Pubs After All, Government Decides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has decided that Britain's biggest
brewers won't have to sell off 22,000 pubs as had been recommended
as a way of fostering competition in the nation's mostly
brewer-owned taverns.
   Trade Secretary Lord Young announced measures Monday to encourage
competition in the supply of beer and other drinks, but they were
not as drastic as those recommended this year by the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission.
   Britain's brewers are allowed to own pubs and to require that
their tenants only buy beer and other drinks from the owner.
Industry critics have called on the government to force competition,
which would bring cheaper prices and wider choices for consumers.
   Lord Young said brewers would be allowed to own more than 2,000
pubs each but that they would have to keep at least half of those
above that limit as ``free houses,'' which can sell beer of their
choice.
   The commission recommended in March that no brewer should be
allowed to own more than 2,000 pubs. This would have meant that
Allied-Lyons PLC, Bass PLC, Elders IXL, Grand Metropolitan PLC,
Scottish and Newcastle PLC and Whitbread PLC would have had to sell
off 22,000 of their ``tied houses.''
   Britain has 82,000 pubs, a majority of which are tied. Tied
houses are either tenanted houses owned by brewers but rented to
tenants, or are managed houses, which are owned and operated by the
brewers.
   Young had said when the report was published that he was inclined
to accept the commission's recommendations. On Thursday, he met the
brewers to discuss the report.
   Young, speaking Monday in the House of Lords, said his decision
would add 11,030 free houses to the existing 15,000.
   ``These proposals should enable a major freeing of the market
without the compulsory divestment originally recommended by the
MMC,'' he said.
   Lawmaker Bryan Gould, the opposition Labor party's spokesman on
trade matters, condemned the measures as ``craven and complete
capitulation'' of government to the big brewers.
   The national Consumers Association said it was disappointed the
trade secretary didn't break up ``the big brewers' stranglehold over
the supply of beer.'' His compromise decision won't benefit
drinkers, it said.
   The Brewers' Society, which represents Britain's brewing
industry, said it was studying the decision.
   The tenants of the national brewers also are to be free to buy
ciders, wines and spirits as well soft drinks, and low alcohol and
non-alcoholic beer from any source, Young said.
   Young has said the commission's recommendation that tenants
should be allowed to offer a ``guest'' beer should only apply to the
national brewers.
   The trade department said the new rules would be put in place
following a 42-day consultation period, during which details of the
regulations would be finalized.
   Young doesn't plan to meet with brewing industry leaders again,
the department said.
   The brewers are to be given two years to implement the changes.
One year after that, the director general of fair trading is to
review the situation.
   Young said that the measures he had announced would involve
``significant structural changes to the market,'' and that it was
important to review whether they had had the effect of increasing
competition in the brewing industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time-DelawareDecisions     07-11 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Delaware Decisions,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delaware Court Decisions Have Helped Determine Outcome of Takeover
Battles</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are some of the Delaware court decisions
that have helped decide recent takeover battles:
   Polaroid Corp. vs. Shamrock Holdings Inc. _ On March 24, 1989,
the Delaware Supreme Court upheld a Chancery Court ruling allowing
Polaroid to proceed with a stock repurchase plan. Shamrock, unable
to gain enough shareholder support for its hostile bid, dropped its
$3.2 billion offer.
   Pillsbury vs. Grand Metropolitan PLC _ On Dec. 16, 1988, retired
Justice William Duffy, sitting on the Delaware Chancery Court,
blocked two key parts of Pillsbury's defense, its ``poison pill''
shareholder rights plan and the spinoff of its Burger King
subsidiary. Pillsbury agreed two days later to a $5.68 billion
buyout by Grand Met.
   Macmillan Inc. _ On July 14, 1988, Chancery Court Judge Jack B.
Jacobs blocked a restructuring Macmillan proposed as a defense
against an unwanted $1.9 billion bid from the Robert Bass Group.
Bass later dropped his bid after competing offers from Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. and British publisher Robert Maxwell were
launched.
   On Nov. 2, the Delaware Supreme Court blocked a merger agreement
between Macmillan and Kohlberg Kravis, calling the bidding process
tainted. The next day, the Macmillan board gave its support to the
Maxwell tender and Kohlberg Kravis dropped its bid.
</TEXT>
