<FIRST>r f PM-TimeChronology     07-11 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time Chronology,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Dates in Time-Warner-Paramount Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   These are some of the key developments in the
takeover battle surrounding Time Inc.:
   Nov. 10, 1988 _ Time Chairman J. Richard Munro, hinting at plans
for an acquisition or merger, tells securities analysts Time intends
to become a global media conglomerate.
   March 4, 1989 _ Time and Warner Communications Inc. announce they
will merge in a friendly stock swap to form Time Warner Inc., the
world's largest communications concern.
   April 9 _ Gulf &amp; Western Inc. says it put its consumer finance
segment, The Associates, up for sale, allowing the company to focus
on its entertainment and publishing businesses. Gulf &amp; Western says
it will use some of the proceeds _ projected at $2.5 billion _ to
finance acquisitions.
   May 22 _ Time and Warner schedule July 23 meetings for their
shareholders to vote on the planned merger.
   June 5 _ Gulf &amp; Western, noting its focus on entertainment and
media, announces it is changing its name to Paramount Communications
Inc.
   June 6 _ Paramount announces a $10.7 billion, or $175 a share,
offer for Time and files suit in Delaware Chancery Court against the
Time-Warner merger.
   June 16 _ Time rejects Paramount's offer as inadequate and highly
conditional, announces it will pursue a $14 billion outright buyout
of Warner and postpones its shareholders meeting until June 30.
   June 23 _ Paramount raises its bid for Time to $12.2 billion, or
$200 a share.
   June 26 _ Time rejects Paramount's sweetened bid and reiterates
its intention to acquire Warner.
   June 28 _ Delaware Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen refuses
to block Time's annual meeting.
   June 29 _ Paramount says seven banks have agreed to help raise
the financing for its Time bid, although the company does not have
commitments for all of the required backing.
   June 30 _ At Time's annual meeting, Munro states that the company
is not for sale as shareholders press company officials on their
decision not to consider the Paramount bid.
   July 7 _ Time announces it has financing commitments from 40
banks for its Warner bid.
   July 8 _ Time announces it has completed the financing
commitments for the Warner offer with agreements from two investment
firms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EEC-MonetaryUnion     07-11 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EEC-Monetary Union,0359</SECOND>
<BYLINE>EEC Finance Ministers Set Timetable For Monetary Union</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic and finance ministers from the
12 Common Market nations have set a timetable for preparatory work
on the first stage of European monetary union.
   The officials also ruled out for the time being a realignment of
currencies within the European Monetary System as a way to address
trade imbalances among the 12 nations.
   According to French Finance Minister Pierre Beregovoy, the 12
ministers agreed Monday that preparatory work for the first stage of
Common Market monetary union should be completed by December.
   That would give member states six months to make the necessary
adjustments before the July 1, 1990 deadline for the beginning of
``stage one'' of monetary union.
   That phase, as agreed to by Common Market heads of state and
government in Madrid last month, will include the removal of
exchange controls, closer coordination of economic and monetary
policies, and the eventual adherence of all Common Market currencies
to the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System.
   Currently, Italy, France, and Spain still have exchange controls.
Britain, Portugal, and Greece do not participate in the exchange
rate mechanism, which limits fluctuations of Common Market
currencies against one another.
   In a session restricted to ministers and one aide each, the
officials also discussed a quarterly report by the European Economic
Community's executive commission on members' economies and agreed
that inflation was the most prominent threat to those economies.
   According to the report, prices in the 12-nation trade bloc rose
5.4 percent in the 12 months leading up to April, compared with a
3.2 percent increase in the 12 months to April 1988.
   The ministers, however, did not make any decisions on how to
address the issue.
   British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said after the
meeting that a Community-wide stance on inflation was not necessary.
The 12 nations ``are all pursuing very much the same policies'' to
curb inflation, ``so joint action is already being taken,'' he said.
   The policies center on a tighter money supply, Lawson added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0215 </DOCNO>
