<FIRST>r f PM-McCawCellular     07-11 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McCaw Cellular,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Lowers Bid for LIN Broadcasting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc. has
lowered its bid for LIN Broadcasting Corp. by about $400 million,
citing a New York court decision that was unfavorable to LIN.
   The new offer, announced Monday, reduces to about $5.36 billion,
from $5.85 billion, the total value of McCaw's bid for the 90
percent of LIN shares it does not own.
   A spokesman for the New York-based LIN Broadcasting, wehich has
rejected the original bid as inadequate, said, ``We regard the McCaw
move as a cynical tactical manuever.''
   ``We continue to be excited by the prospects for LIN and will do
everything possible to protect the shareholders from the threat of
an abusive takeover,'' the LIN statement said.
   In late-afternooon trading in the over-the-counter market, LIN
was down $3.25 a share at $112 while McCaw was unchanged at $37.75 a
share.
   If successful, McCaw's takeover attempt would result in the
largest cellular telephone market in the country. The ``regional
supersystem'' that McCaw has been seeking would be more than twice
the market size of McCaw's closest competitors.
   McCaw said its new $110 per share offer will expire at midnight,
New York time, on July 21. The offer could be extended beyond that
date, McCaw said. All other terms and conditions of the offer remain
the same, it said.
   The two companies held discussions over the weekend about the
status of the previous $120 per share offer for all outstanding
shares of LIN common stock. The discussions did not result in any
agreement or understanding, McCaw said.
   To date, only a nominal number of shares have been tendered in
the offer, McCaw said.
   The New York Court of Appeals late last month denied LIN's claims
to certain cellular interests of Metromedia Co. in the New York City
and Philadelphia markets.
   Some analysts had estimated that if LIN had won the case, the
addition of the cellular interests could have added $40 a share to
LIN's stock price.
   In its statement, LIN confirmed that it had met with McCaw
officials last weekend at McCaw's request but that the talks were
inconclusive.
   ``Although nothing came of the discussions, it was clear from our
meeting that they valued LIN at higher than $120 per share. McCaw
has now had a more than ample opportunity to express itself and we
can focus on other opportunities,'' LIN said in its statement.
   McCaw first announced its bid to acquire LIN in early June.
</TEXT>
