<DOCNO> AP890711-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 0141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CleanCoal     07-11 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Coal,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Foresees Big Cuts in Pollutants From Coal Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New technologies being developed to burn coal
more cleanly could reduce pollutants from old power plants linked to
acid rain by nearly one-half, the Energy Department said.
   The department is in the early stages of a projected $5 billion
program with private industry to develop those ``clean coal''
technologies.
   The technologies are not expected to be ready for commercial use
before the turn of the century.
   The department said Monday that a draft analysis of the
environment effects of the new technologies concludes that they
could reduce national emissions of sulfur dioxide from existing coal
plants by as much as 45 percent by the year 2010.
   Nitrogen oxide emissions could be cut by as much as 33 percent
over the same period, it said.
   Both pollutants are precursors of the acids that form and fall as
acid rain when smokestack gases are carried long distances by the
wind.
   The analysis said clean coal technologies could result in a 5
percent to 12 percent reduction in carbon dioxide emissions when
used to refurbish older conventional power stations. Carbon dioxide,
an inevitable combustion product from any carbon-based fuel, is the
major gas responsible for the predicted ``greenhouse effect''
trapping of heat in the atmosphere and warming of the earth.
   While the air pollutants could be reduced, the Energy Department
study said the effects on solid waste were less clear. It said the
amount of solid waste generated could range from a 22 percent
reduction to a 23 percent increase.
   It did not explain the disparity in projected solid waste
generation, but said these wastes would be in a dry form that is
more easily handled than the wet sludge generated by the scrubbers
used to remove sulfur dioxide from smokestack gases of newer
coal-burning power plants.
   ``The commercialization of clean coal technologies would have a
substantial beneficial effect on air quality in the year 2010
compared to the no-action alternative,'' the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0220 </DOCNO>
