<HEAD>Delta to Sell Shares to Swissair, Form ESOP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delta Air Lines announced Monday that it has
entered into an agreement with Swissair to sell 2.5 million shares
of Delta common stock to the Swiss carrier for $193.3 million, or
about $77 a share.
   The agreement includes a reciprocal purchase by Delta of up to
100,000, or 5 percent, of Swissair's shares.
   Delta said the cross investments are intended to promote
cooperation between the two airlines. In March, the two carriers
announced cooperative marketing and operating agreements.
   Delta on Monday also announced the formation of an employee stock
ownership plan as part of its existing family savings plan.
   Under the plan, nearly 7 million shares of Delta preferred stock
were purchased for about $500 million, the company said. The shares
will be allocated to employees in lieu of existing cash
contributions to the plan, but they can be converted into common
stock shares worth $86.40 each.
   The preferred stock will pay 6 percent a year in dividends.
   ``We are pleased to enhance our Family Care Savings Plan with the
addition of the ESOP,'' said Ronald W. Allen, Delta's chairman and
chief executive officer. ``By more closely aligning the interests of
our personnel with those of our stockholders, the ESOP should also
enhance stockholder values.''
