<FIRST>u f AM-ExxonValdez 1stLd-Writethru f0279 07-11 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0279,0759</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Slick Sighting Coincides With Valdez's Arrival</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with pieces of steel discovered
dragging from Valdez's bottom; results drug tests for tanker crew in Delaware
River spill, ADD quotes from Coast Guard; picks up 5th graf, `An aircraft...'
SUBS 11th graf, `In Providence ...,' with 3 grafs to ADD details on drug
test results; picks up 12th graf, `Less than ...'. Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mysterious, 18-mile-long oil slick sighted
near the Exxon Valdez and the discovery of huge slabs of steel
hanging from the crippled tanker will delay its entry into San Diego
Bay, the Coast Guard said Monday.
   ``Things have gotten complicated,'' said Coast Guard Cmdr. Jack
Scarborough.
   In other developments, tests showed no traces of drugs in the
captain and crew of a Uruguayan tanker that spilled more than
300,000 gallons of oil in the Delaware River two weeks ago, their
lawyer said in Philadelphia. In Providence, R.I., officials
downgraded their estimate of the amount of oil spilled when a tanker
ran aground off Newport.
   A Coast Guard inspection Monday revealed potential navigational
problems from pieces of steel partially torn loose during the
vessel's voyage from Alaska, where the Valdez was involved in the
nation's worst oil spill.
   The steel pieces were hanging 20 feet to 30 feet below the ship's
bottom and could drag in harbor shallows, Scarborough said.
   The Valdez arrived off San Diego late Sunday but must be
certified by the Coast Guard as environmentally safe before it's
allowed into San Diego Bay.
   The ship, which had been scheduled to enter the bay Tuesday, is
to be repaired at National Steel and Shipbuilding Co., where the
vessel was built in 1986.
   ``We have a couple of things to do,'' Scarborough said. ``We have
to make sure she's not leaking, and we have to get this excess
baggage removed.''
   An aircraft spotted an oil slick near the Valdez, which is about
30 miles off San Diego. But Coast Guard officials who boarded the
vessel Monday morning to inspect it found no signs of leakage from
the tanker, Scarborough said.
   ``One of the things we're looking for is to make sure there's no
oil coming from the'' Valdez, he said. ``The oil slick was close
enough to the ship where it could be the source.''
   The slick is a sheen 18 miles long and about a mile wide,
Scarborough said. ``It sounds like a huge amount of oil but it
really isn't. Certainly, it's enough to worry about,'' he said.
   The California Fish and Game Department also was trying to
determine whether the Valdez was the source of the slick, Coast
Guard officials said.
   Exxon Shipping Co. spokeswoman Carrie Chassin, speaking from
Thousand Oaks, Calif., said she was not sure when the Valdez would
be cleared to enter the harbor.
   The Valdez smashed into a reef in Alaska's Prince William Sound
on March 24, spilling nearly 11 million gallons of crude. Hundreds
of miles of coastline were stained and thousands of animals died in
the spill, and the cleanup is continuing.
   In Philadelphia, attorney Raymond Letulle said Monday the Coast
Guard received the negative drug test results by phone last week.
   The tests were performed June 25, the day after the tanker
accidently dropped anchor, causing it to run aground in the river,
Letulle said.
   In Providence, officials downgraded the amount of oil spilled
when a Greek tanker ran aground off Newport to one-fifth the
original estimate of 1.6 million gallons.
   Less than 300,000 gallons of No. 2 heating oil spilled from the
World Prodigy when it struck a reef off Benton Point on June 23,
said Gary Ott, a National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
official assigned to the Coast Guard in Boston.
   The Exxon Valdez, towed by two tug boats and accompanied by a
third tug and salavage ship, left Alaska on June 23 for the
2,500-mile journey to San Diego.
   About 42 million gallons of crude oil that remained on board
after the accident was transferred to other tankers.
   Before departing, the ship's crude oil tanks were washed to
eliminate residual cargo. The Valdez, however, is carrying fuel oil,
which will be needed when the ship comes into San Diego Bay on its
own power.
   The repairs are expected to cost $25 million and take nine months.
</TEXT>
