<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-11 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Tokyo, Stocks Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen and the
key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange also rebounded in thin trading
today.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 70.75 points, or 0.21
percent, closing at 33,746.77. The index had fallen 27.95 points
Monday.
   The dollar closed at 139.62 yen, up 0.34 yen from Monday's
139.28-yen finish. It opened at 139.47 yen and ranged narrowly
between 139.47 yen and 139.78 yen. The dollar had declined 0.37 yen
on Monday.
   Ichiro Ikeda, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said trading
was quiet in the absence of fresh market-affecting news.
   He said the dollar rose today mainly because many New York
investors who had sold dollars earlier were buying them back in
position adjustments.
   Most Japanese market players remained on the sidelines to await
the release Friday of the U.S. wholesale price index, Ikeda added.
   ``Expectations that the United States will make a further move to
relax its monetary policy no longer are affecting the Tokyo market
because it has been expected for quite some time already,'' Ikeda
said.
   But lower U.S. interest rates could discourage dollar-buying, he
said.
   Following Friday's prime lending rate cut of 0.5 percentage point
by Southwest Bank, Chase Manhattan Bank also cut its rate Monday by
0.5 percentage point from 11 percent.
   On the stock market, trading was thin because most investors had
little buying incentive before the July 23 elections for half the
seats in Parliament's upper house, said Daiwa Securities dealer
Kenji Ishizuka.
   Analysts predict the governing Liberal Democratic Party will
suffer major losses, and investors expect such a defeat for the
pro-business party would push down stock prices.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 550 million shares,
up from Monday's 500 million. Among gainers were steel, securities
and bank issues.
</TEXT>
