<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     07-11 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed in lively trading today,
supported by short-covering that began the previous day when the
Federal Reserve let short-term interest rates slip only 1@4 point,
currency dealers in Europe said.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Most of the dollar's upward movement came on short-covering in
late U.S. trading Monday and in early Asian trading today, dealers
said.
   ``The Far East brought it up on a technical reaction to the fall
over the last few weeks,'' said a trader at a large U.S. bank in
Frankfurt.
   ``It had really come off over the last few weeks and this
correction was actually overdue.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.34 yen to a closing 139.62 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 139.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8755 West German marks, up from 1.8575; 1.6150
Swiss francs, up from 1.5960; 6.3570 French francs, up from 6.3005;
2.1148 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0988; 1,363.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,354.50; 1.1905 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18835.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6263 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6410 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $380.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $381.75. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $381.35.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $381.35, down from $383.45 late
Monday.
   Bullion dealers said gold has been hurt by investors' interest in
a variety of other investment instruments, as well as by signs that
inflation is peaking or has peaked in some major economies such as
the United States.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.49 to close at a bid $381.78.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.23 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $5.21.
</TEXT>
