<FIRST>r f PM-Brady-Summit     07-11 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brady-Summit,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady Says US Satisfied With Allies' Economic Coordination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's treasury secretary says the
president will not offer any broad new initiatives to shore up
international economic coordination at the economic summit this week
in Paris.
   ``What we ought to take out of this summit is that the world
economy is doing well and the economic policy coordination process
is one that works,'' said Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady.
   ``I don't think there needs to be too much added to the process
at this point in time,'' he said Monday.
   Bush, along with the leaders of Britain, France, Japan, West
Germany, Italy and Canada, will attend the economic summit of the
world's largest industrial democracies from Friday through Sunday.
   Brady, meeting with reporters before his own departure for the
summit, disputed contentions that the economic coordination process
had stalled.
   Many economists are worried the surge in the value of the dollar
that began in the spring will send America's trade deficit soaring
again as U.S. goods are priced out of overseas markets.
   But Brady said the dollar is now back where it stood when he last
met with finance ministers from the other summit countries in April
and the group expressed a desire to stabilize the U.S. currency's
value.
   To those who contend the coordination process is not working,
Brady pointed to the improvement in America's trade deficit, which
declined by 27 percent last year and has shown further improvement
this year.
   Brady said the administration hopes to get a commitment from the
other summit nations to support moves toward democracy in Communist
Eastern Europe.
   Bush on Monday pledged in a speech to the Polish parliament that
the United States would provide $100 million in assistance to that
country and would push for aid from other Western nations at the
Paris summit.
   The Polish trade union Solidarity has said $10 billion in aid was
needed to rescue the Polish economy, but Brady said that much
assistance would not be forthcoming.
   ``Countries always ask for an amount of money that would solve
their problems and the donor nations try to do the best they can,''
he said.
</TEXT>
