<FIRST>r f PM-GreekBankFraud     07-11 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greek Bank Fraud,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Bank Sued for $1.5 Billion By Depositors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for depositors in a Greek bank raided
by federal authorities last month filed a lawsuit alleging the bank
bilked immigrant Greeks out of hundreds of millions of dollars.
   The class-action lawsuit, filed Monday in U.S. District Court,
seeks $1.5 billion in damages and restitution for thousands of Greek
depositors in the National Mortgage Bank of Greece.
   Attorney Constantine Kangles said the bank, which advertised in
Greek-language newspapers in the United States, promised customers
interest rates as high as 18 percent that would be paid in Greek
drachmas and would not be disclosed to U.S. authorities.
   He said about 300 people are behind the lawsuit, but their ranks
could swell to as many as 3,000. The $1.5 billion represents treble
damages based on an estimate of about $500 million in deposits, he
said.
   Barry Slotnick, a New York attorney representing the bank, did
not comment on the lawsuit in a statement issued through a spokesman
Monday.
   Slotnick instead urged depositors in the bank not to panic. He
said in the statement all U.S. representative offices of the bank
were being staffed and American depositors would have access to
their funds next week.
   The civil lawsuit against the bank and 14 of its officers came
less than a month after federal authorities raided seven bank
branches in Illinois, Massachusetts, New York and Pennsylvania,
seizing documents and arresting the officers.
   The bank is charged with illegally accepting more than $700
million in deposits from customers in the United States and sending
the money overseas to avoid taxes, according to a complaint filed in
U.S. District Court in New York.
   The National Mortgage Bank of Greece is a separate entity from
the National Bank of Greece, which also operates in the United
States. The National Bank of Greece owns about 47 percent of the
mortgage bank, according to federal authorities.
   The mortgage bank's branches were not legally authorized to
accept money from customers in the United States, authorities say.
Rather, the U.S. branches were opened with the ostensible purpose of
encouraging investment in Greece.
</TEXT>
