<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Time 2ndLd-Writethru f0067 07-11 0825</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0067,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time, Warner Head to Delaware For Showdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with hearing remarks, UPDATE stock
prices. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Also Monday ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys asked a Delaware judge today to
block Time Inc.'s attempt to acquire Warner Communications Inc. and
allow Time shareholders to vote on a takeover bid by hostile suitor
Paramount Communications Inc.
   In a hearing considered pivotal in the 5-week-old battle for
Time, attorneys for Paramount maintained the media giant put itself
up for sale when it agreed to a friendly merger with Warner earlier
this year, and as such should be forced to consider Paramount's
hostile $12.2 billion bid.
   Paramount attorney Melvyn L. Cantor told Chancery Court Judge
William T. Allen that Time's board knew in March when it agreed to
merge with Warner in a stock swap that the deal could put Time on
the auction block.
   Time subsequently changed the to a $14 billion tender offer for
Warner's stock and the companies exchanged stock in each other to
seal the deal.
   Cantor pointed to the exchange of stock as proof the companies
knew they were opening themselves up to possible third-party bids.
   Michael R. Klein, an attorney representing investor Robert M.
Bass and other major Time shareholders, made the same point.
   Klein said the stock exchange was ``done to defend the
transaction...it was understood that the market reaction might be to
perceive that both Time and Warner were up for grabs.''
   Both attorneys asked that Time shareholders be allowed to vote on
the $200 a share Paramount offer. Time has proposed to complete the
offer for Warner without a shareholder vote.
   Time's attorney's, scheduled to present their case after a lunch
break, were expected to argue that its board never contemplated
selling the company and that the agreement with Warner stemmed from
the ordinary conduct of Time's business.
   Nearly 200 people crowded into the Chancery Court for the hearing
before Judge William T. Allen. Absent were most top executives from
the companies.
   Allen's ruling, which is not expected until later this week,
could affect more than just these three companies since many of the
biggest U.S. corporations are incorporated in Delaware and subject
to its laws and court rulings.
   On the eve of the hearing, Time stock rose $1.12{ to close at
$152.62{ a share Monday on the New York Stock Exchange. Warner stock
rose 25 cents to $62 a share and Paramount dipped 25 cents to $56.75
a share.
   Time fell $2.62{ a share to $150 in early-afternoon trading
today, while Warner lost 25 cents to $61.75 and Paramount rose 50
cents to $57.50.
   Also Monday, Paramount said it had amended its $200-per-share
offer for Time to add interest under certain conditions.
   Paramount said it would add interest at a rate of 9 percent a
year if the deal were not completed within 60 days after Time either
agrees to the deal or is ordered to refrain from interfering with
Paramount's efforts to obtain government approval to transfer Time's
cable television licenses.
   ``Our willingness to pay interest if the company cannot close its
deal within 60 days underscores our confidence that regulatory
approvals can be obtained within that period if Time's
obstructionist tactics are stopped,'' said Donald Oresman,
Paramount's general counsel.
   Time offered no comment on the new terms, but a source close to
Time, speaking on condition he not be identified, said Paramount's
interest offer ``represents a belated admission that it will take
Paramount a substantial period of time to obtain the necessary
regulatory approvals.''
   Time has rejected Paramount's bid as inadequate and highly
conditional, saying it could take a year or more for Paramount to
secure the needed regulatory approvals for cable license transfers.
   Paramount has said it could win the necessary approvals within a
few months, but has complained that Time has been drumming up
opposition among local cable regulators to Paramount's efforts.
   The issue in today's court hearing, according to Duke University
Law School professor James D. Cox, is whether entering into
negotiations with Warner ``triggers the auctioneer role for the
(Time) directors, or can their conduct merely be judged by the
business judgment rule.''
   The business judgment rule, a widely-followed legal concept,
allows decisions made by directors in the normal course of business
to stand. Courts generally are reluctant to disturb such decisions.
   Time Chairman J. Richard Munro hinted that the company was
considering a merger when he told securities analysts last November
that Time intended to be among the growing ranks of global media
conglomerates.
   Paramount Chairman Martin S. Davis has indicated he raised the
possibility of a merger between Paramount and Time ``on several
occasions during the past several years.''
   That raises the question of whether Time entered into the merger
agreement as a defensive step. If that were the case, Time would be
forced to consider buyout offers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0042 07-11 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0042,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites thruout with closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices soared Tuesday following an unexpected
$21 billion takeover bid for the conglomerate BAT Industries PLC.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 55.7
points, or 2.5 percent, higher at 2,250.9.
   Earlier in the afternoon, the closely watched index hit a
post-crash high of 2,260.8. At its lowest, prior to the bid for BAT,
the index was down 7.5 points at 2,187.7.
   Volume totaled 639.3 million shares, up sharply from 417.6
million Monday.
   The bid by an investor group including Anglo-French financier Sir
James Goldsmith, British financier Jacob Rothschild and Australia's
Kerry Packer was quickly rejected by BAT which said it was of
``dubious value.''
   Nonetheless, it inspired the market.
   ``The BAT bid was very important,'' said Kenneth Inglis, equity
strategist at UBS Phillips and Drew. ``We're likely to see similar
takeover attempts in the near future.''
   The market's leap forward prompted many equity analysts at London
brokerages to forecast further robust gains in the market during the
third quarter. Continuing takeover speculation, high institutional
liquidity, and a lack of selling pressure are seen leading the
market higher in the near term.
   The market received additional upward impetus from a robust
showing on Wall Street. At the London close, the Dow Jones
Industrial Average was up 17.64 points at 2,520.30 points.
   ``Today's bid now suggests that no U.K. company is immune from a
potential takeover,'' one equity trader noted.
   If successful, a BAT takeover would put British takeovers into
the big league, nearing last year's $25 billion buyout of RJR
Nabisco Inc. by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co., the largest company
purchase ever.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
