<DOCNO> AP890711-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Marriott-Sale     07-11 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Marriott-Sale,0262</SECOND>
<UNK>Marriott Sells Airline Catering Unit to Investor Group</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marriott Corp. announced Tuesday that it has
agreed to sell its airline catering business to an investor group
that includes members of the unit's senior management.
   The purchase price was not disclosed, but analysts have estimated
that the business would fetch $550 million to $700 million. The
business will retain its current name, Marriott In-Flite Services.
   Proceeds from the sale, which is expected to be closed before the
end of the year, will be used to pay debts, the hotel giant said in
a news release.
   The investor group, called Caterair International, is led by
Daniel J. Altobello, an executive vice president of Marriott Corp.;
Frederic V. Malek, a Washington banker and former Marriott
executive; and several members of Marriott In-Flite Services' senior
management.
   Carlyle Group, a Washington investment firm which includes former
defense secretary Frank Carlucci, is acting as financial advisor to
the investor group.
   Marriott said In-Flite Services is the world's leading provider
of airline meals, serving 150 airlines through 108 flight kitchens
at 45 U.S. and 38 foreign airports. The business, with nearly 19,000
employees worldwide, had revenue of around $800 million in 1988.
   ``The airline catering division is a sound, profitable
business,'' Marriott said in a statement. ``However, the division's
role as a supplier of food products and services for airlines is not
compatible with Marriott's long-term strategy of focusing on high
potential growth markets in lodging, food and related services
provided directly to consumers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
