<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Paper     07-11 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Paper,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Paper Reports 22 Percent Rise In Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Paper said Tuesday its
second-quarter earnings rose 22 percent from a year ago, due to
strong sales and acquisitions.
   For the three months ended June 30, International Paper's
earnings totaled $229 million, or $2.04 a share, compared with $188
million, or $1.64 a share, in the comparable 1988 quarter.
   Revenue jumped 25 percent to $3 billion from $2.4 billion.
   Chairman John A. Georges said the latest quarterly results
reflected several new acquisitions, including the French paper
company, Aussedat Rey.
   ``The strong performances of these businesses compensated for a
softening in the uncoated white papers markets,'' Georges said.
   He also attributed the results to the company's strong businesses
in pulp, paperboard and packaging.
   The company further announced authorization of an additional
purchase of 4 million shares of common stock, which it said would be
used in connection with employee benefit plans and general corporate
purposes. The announcement expanded a previously disclosed
repurchase authorization to 5.8 million shares.
   The company has more than 100 million shares outstanding.
   For the first half of 1989, earnings were up 30 percent to $452
million, or $4 a share, compared with $347 million, or $3.02 a
share, in the year-earlier period.
   Sales totaled $5.6 billion vs. $4.7 billion, up 19 percent.
</TEXT>
