<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1453EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     07-11 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Europe, Gold Falls In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in choppy European trading
Tuesday. Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said the dollar was boosted largely by internal market
influences. But it also got a lift, they said, from comments by the
West German Bundesbank President Karl Otto Poehl that the
dollar-mark rate was now at a level he viewed as ``welcome.''
   European dealers said interest was concentrated largely in the
trading of the mark against Britain's pound sterling and the
Japanese yen.
   ``We tend to think that it's not been so much a dollar play as a
lot of cross trading that at times has made the dollar look
strong,'' said a senior dealer at a U.S. bank in London.
   A dealer with a major West German bank in Frankfurt said until
Friday, when new U.S. economic data is due, the market doesn't
expect any substantial moves. The U.S. producer price index,
industrial production, retail sales and capacity utilization figures
for June are scheduled for release on Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.34 yen to a closing 139.62 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 140.25 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6270 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6410 dollars late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.8795 West German marks, up from 1.8575; 1.6160 Swiss francs, up
from 1.5960; 6.3740 French francs, up from 6.3005; 2.1180 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0988; 1,364.50 Italian lire, up from 1,354.50;
and 1.19025 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18835.
