<HEAD>Grain Futures Tumble Again On Rainy Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed sharply
lower Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, tumbling for the second
straight day in response to improved crop-growing conditions.
   Analysts said morning showers in downtown Chicago probably
prompted even more selling than the National Weather Service's
latest six-to-10-day outlook, which predicted normal rainfall and
sub-normal temperatures in the Midwestern Corn Belt from Sunday
through Thursday, July 20.
   The condition of the U.S. corn and soybean crops deteriorated
slightly in the past week due to lack of moisture, according to the
Agriculture Department's weekly crop progress report.
   The USDA listed 6 percent of the corn crop in poor or very poor
condition as of Sunday compared with 3 percent in the previous week.
   The agency ranked 9 percent of the soybean crop poor or very poor
as of Sunday compared with 6 percent a week earlier.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 8 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.91{ a bushel; corn was { cent to
5{ cents lower with July at $2.58{ a bushel; oats were 2\ cents to
2} cents lower with July at $1.44\ a bushel; soybeans were 18} cents
lower to 1 cent higher with July at $7.25 a bushel.
