<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     07-11 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0254</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved higher today as the market
extended its advance for a sixth straight session.
   Optimism about the outlook for further interest rate declines has
set a positive tone on Wall Street while interest in buying stocks
considered takeover candidates also has contributed to bullish
sentiment.
   Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.,
said activity in the bond market appeared to have a direct impact on
stocks today.
   Stock traders became enthusiastic about buying when the yield on
the widely watched 30-year Treasury bond temporarily dropped below 8
percent for the first time since the spring of 1987.
   When the key bond's yield bounced back above 8 percent, stock
traders took it as a cue to sell and collect some profits, said
Johnson.
   ``Probably the No.1 feature today was the assault that the bond
market made on the 8 percent yield,'' he said. ``It hit a lot more
resistance, or selling of bonds, than most people expected, which
was a touch demoralizing for the bond market.''
   ``When it started to back off from that 8 percent wall, the stock
market saw that occur and started some measured profit-taking,''
Johnson added.
   Meanwhile, the market appeared to get a lift from wordof a
surprise $21 billion bid for Britain's BAT Industries. BAT, a big
conglomerate with numerous American holdings, immediately rejected
the bid and analysts said a higher one might be forthcoming.
</TEXT>
