<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose Tuesday, partly
recovering from losses in the previous session.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate rose 17 cents to finish at $20.53 a barrel. The
benchmark U.S. crude grade fell 39 cents on Monday.
   Other contract months also rose.
   Refined petroleum products traded on the exchange showed
across-the-board gains. The August contract for home heating oil
jumped 0.49 cent to close at 49.28 cents a gallon after falling 0.98
cent in the previous session.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for August delivery rose 0.16 cent to
56.62 cents a gallon, after declining 0.13 cent on Monday.
   Peter Beutel, assistant director of the energy group at Elders
Futures Inc. said buying was relatively light as traders anticipated
inventory statistics from the American Petroleum Institute.
   ``There were no features in today's market,'' Beutel said.
``People are waiting for the numbers.''
   Beutel said the latest weekly API figures could indicate
significant changes in supply and demand. U.S. refineries are
operating at 91.2 percent, the highest capacity since August 1980,
he said.
   Some analysts had predicted that a surge in summer gasoline
demand could eventually strain U.S. refineries and push prices
closer to the highs reached earlier in the season.
   Energy futures prices also have fluctuated in recent days in
response to labor problems affecting North Sea oil operations.
</TEXT>
