<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   07-11 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS Monday yen-dollar level in New York in 8th graf to
139.20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended higher Tuesday against key
foreign currencies after major banks again failed to follow Chase
Manhattan Bank's cut in the prime lending rate.
   Gold prices eased. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery fell $3.10 to $381.50 a troy ounce.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold at
$379 an ounce, down from $382.50 Monday.
   Zlatko Glamuzina, chief dealer at the New York office of Banco di
Sicilia, said the fact that other big U.S. banks didn't trim their
prime a half percentage point to 10.5 percent, as Chase did on
Monday, indicated that interest rates weren't falling as rapidly as
previously thought.
   Economists said many banks probably were awaiting further signs
that the Federal Reserve was loosening credit policies in reaction
to an economic slowdown before they lowered their prime.
   ``The Fed seems to be easing (credit) extremely cautiously,''
Glamuzina said.
   Currency dealers said a spate of economic data due out Friday
should shed further light on the economy's direction. The government
is set to release the producer price index, industrial production,
retail sales and capacity utilization figures for June.
   Also helping the dollar Tuesday was an increase in trading of the
mark against Britain's pound sterling and the Japanese yen.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.34 yen to 139.62 yen. It was quoted at 140.25 yen
in London, and at 140.75 yen in New York, up from 139.20 yen Monday.
   The dollar was stronger against the British pound. It cost
$1.6270 to buy one pound in London, cheaper than $1.6410 late
Monday. Sterling fetched $1.6235 in New York, down from $1.6390.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday,
included: 1.8835 West German marks, up from 1.8638; 1.6190 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6015; 6.3840 French francs, up from 6.3155;
1.19055 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18925; and 1,365.025 Italian
lire, up from 1,354.50.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, vs. Monday: 1.8795 marks, up from
1.8575; 1.6160 Swiss francs, up from 1.5960; 6.3740 French francs,
up from 6.3005; 2.1180 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0988; 1.19025
Canadian dollars, up from 1.18835; and 1,364.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,354.50.
   Gold eased in London to a late bid price of $380.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $381.75. In Zurich, it fell to $379.75
an ounce from $383.45 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.49 to close at a bid $381.78
an ounce.
   Silver prices gained.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled
at $5.257 a troy ounce, up 2.8 cents from Monday. Silver rose in
London to $5.27 an ounce from $5.21.
</TEXT>
