<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices climbed higher Tuesday as the market
extended its advance for a sixth straight session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials finished with a gain of
11.95 at 2,514.61, which was significantly lower than its best level
of the day.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 8 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 926 up, 579 down and
500 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 171.59 million
shares, up from 131.87 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 209.10 million shares.
   Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.,
said activity in the bond market had a direct bearing on the stock
market's movements.
   Stock traders became enthusiastic about buying in the early going
when the yield on the widely watched 30-year Treasury bond
temporarily dropped below 8 percent for the first time since the
spring of 1987.
   When the key bond's yield bounced back above 8 percent, stock
traders took it as a cue to sell and collect some profits, said
Johnson.
   ``Probably the No.1 feature today was the assault that the bond
market made on the 8 percent yield,'' he said. ``It hit a lot more
resistance, or selling of bonds, than most people expected, which
was a touch demoralizing for the bond market.''
   ``When it started to back off from that 8 percent wall, the stock
market saw that occur and started some measured profit-taking,''
Johnson added.
   The market got some help in prolonging its winning streak from a
surprise $21 billion bid for tobacco giant BAT Industries.
   BAT, a big British conglomerate with numerous American holdings,
quickly turned down the proposal and analysts said a higher one
could be forthcoming. The hostile offer from financiers Sir James
Goldsmith, Jacob Rothschild and Kerry Packer, was worth about $13.86
in debt securities per BAT share.
   Stock of BAT was the most heavily traded issue on the American
Stock Exchange, with volume of more than 7 million shares. BAT rose
215-16 to 14].
   The surge in BAT ignited a rally in other tobacco stocks. Philip
Morris rose 2[ to 143} and American Brands went up 1{ to 71].
   Besides Philip Morris, another gainer among the blue chips
included International Paper, up } to 47\, which announced improved
second-quarter income.
   UAL, recently pushed aloft by takeover talk, pulled back by 2~ to
165|. Flight attendants of UAL's United Airlines have voted to
authorize a strike. But the negotiations between the union and
United are under the supervision of a federal mediator who would
have to declare an impasse and call for a 30-day cooling-off period
before a strike could be called.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market rose $15.32 billion, or 0.48
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks went
ahead by 0.92 to 183.62.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index increased 1.65 to 374.77, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index closed 1.71 higher at 328.78.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
1.81 to 444.50. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 366.03, up 1.59.
