<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-11 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pork Belly Futures Plunge; Glut Persists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Frozen pork belly futures sank below 30 cents a pound Tuesday on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange amid renewed concern about the glut
of bellies clogging the nation's commercial freezers.
   Hog futures also retreated while cattle futures rose.
   On other markets, grains and soybeans were sharply lower; energy
futures advanced and precious metals were mixed.
   Frozen pork bellies settled .43 cent to 1.80 cents lower with the
contract for delivery this month at 28.97 cents a pound, matching
the nine-year low reached May 31.
   The trading reflected expectations that a weekly exchange report
would show no significant decline in the amount of pork bellies in
cold storage outside of Chicago.
   The report, issued after the close, showed an unexpectedly large
drawdown of 4.6 million pounds, which analysts said could prompt
some buying of futures on Wednesday.
   But frozen stocks of bellies, which are cured and sliced to make
bacon, still are believed to be at near-record levels as the end of
the heaviest usage period approaches.
   Charles Levitt, chief livestock market analyst for Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc., said he expects the Agriculture Department's
July 21 cold-storage report to show about 128 million pounds of
frozen bellies on hand as of July 1, which would be the
second-highest total on record for that date and 1{ times the
10-year average.
   The July 1 record high was 133.2 million pounds in 1964.
   Levitt said traders fear there will be little significant
drawdown in frozen stocks by fall, when hog slaughters typically
increase and fresh bellies grow more abundant.
   ``This is the time of year we're supposed to be taking the chunk
of bellies out of storage and using them in consumer channels,''
Levitt said.
   ``If you get into the fall and start the seasonal increase in
slaughters again, what are you going to do if you've got a lot of
bellies still left in storage? They'll be worthless or near
worthless.''
   Hog futures prices fell in spillover selling from the belly pit,
while cattle futures advanced on expectations for dwindling supplies
this fall.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .65 cent higher with August at
70.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .60 cent higher
with August at 81.47 cents a pound; hogs were .50 cent to 1 cent
lower with July at 46.87 cents a pound.
   Corn and soybean futures fell sharply for the second straight day
on the Chicago Board of Trade as showers relieved crop-withering
heat and dryness in the Midwest. Wheat and oat futures also declined.
   Analysts said a morning downpour in downtown Chicago may have
steepened the sell-off, which was linked initially to Monday's
National Weather Service six-to-10-day outlook calling for normal
rainfall and sub-normal temperatures in the Corn Belt from Sunday
through July 20.
   Wheat settled 2 cents to 7} cents lower with July at $3.91} a
bushel; corn was { cent to 4{ cents lower with July at $2.59 a
bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 2} cents lower with July at $1.44\ a
bushel; soybeans were 17} cents lower to 1 cent higher with July at
$7.26 a bushel.
   Oil futures prices rose on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
partly recovering from losses in the previous session.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 9 cents to 17 cents
higher with August at $20.53 a barrel; heating oil was .40 cent to
.55 cent higher with August at 49.28 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .16 cent to .55 cent higher with August at 56.62 cents
a gallon.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $3.20 to $3.40
lower with August at $383.30 a troy ounce; silver was 0.7 cents to
2.8 cents higher with July at $5.257 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
