<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AnsweringSystem     07-11 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Answering System,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>NET to Pack an Answering Machine Into Regional Telephones</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLISON J. PUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New England Telephone is readying a new answering
service it hopes will captivate the market, rendering personal
answering machines obsolete, but one machine manufacturer says the
industry won't suffer greatly.
   The service, which is being tested and introduced by the American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. spinoff throughout the country, enables
subscribers to use only their telephones to answer, record and hold
their calls, with the telephone company storing all messages.
   Subscribers can leave recorded greetings on the central system
and retrieve messages by punching into their touch-tone phone a
seven digit phone number, followed by a personal code of between
four and 10 digits.
   Because voice messaging can forward calls to be recorded if a
subscriber's line is busy, company officials say they expect the new
service will eliminate the need for answering machines, which do not
have that capability.
   ``That's my wish. Answering services will never become obsolete,
because some customers need and desire the personal touch we can't
provide, but yes, this could make machines completely obsolete,''
Anne Kemerer, a product manager for New England Telephone, said
Tuesday.
   Services employ personal operators to take calls, who can then
relay different messages to certain callers.
   A leading manufacturer of answering machines said it was unlikely
they would be edged out by a voice messaging service.
   ``We feel people don't want their messages kept in a big computer
downtown. Issues of privacy, cost and complexity are viable enough
so that it's not going to be an overwhelming threat to the
industry,'' said Jim Oblak, who is the director of marketing for
PhoneMate Inc.
   ``Yes it will take a certain amount of our business away, but
that will be small, with nowhere near the ramifications of kicking
us out of the business,'' he said.
   New England Telephone estimates that one-third of its residential
and business customers own answering machines.
   Kemerer also said that voice messaging was just the beginning of
a host of expanded services planned by the company.
   Jim Stork, a telecommunications industry analyst for the Chicago
consulting firm Duff &amp; Phelps Inc., said the advent of digital
networks had enabled ventures such as voice messaging, and predicted
an onslaught of new services from telephone companies.
   Voice mail is not subject to the strict rate regulation of
regular telephone services, and New England Telephone can charge
whatever subscribers will pay.
   The service costs $6 per month for residential customers, with a
one-time activation charge of $12.37. Business subscribers will pay
$18.43 up front and $12 a month thereafter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890711-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-NorthwestPilots     07-11 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest Pilots,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots to Meet with Buyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union pilots of Northwest Airlines will meet
with Alfred Checchi on Wednesday to review details of his group's
proposed $4 billion takeover of the carrier's parent, a union
spokesman said Tuesday.
   The pilots, the only labor group at Northwest without a contract,
are dismayed with the debt that would be imposed on the company
under the proposed deal, which is subject to shareholder and
government approval.
   Financial advisers to the 5,000-member Air Line Pilots
Association have said they favor a proposed recapitalization of the
airline drafted by management as a backup to Checchi's $121-a-share
tender offer. The backup plan would involve less borrowing and a
lower payment to shareholders.
   ``We'll give him a chance to raise our comfort level on this,''
pilots' union spokesman Andy Murphy said of the meeting, to be held
in New York.
   Meanwhile, contract negotiations between the pilots and Northwest
resumed Tuesday for the first time since NWA Inc.'s board of
directors accepted Checchi's offer in mid-June.
   The mediated session began about 1 p.m. at NWA's Eagan
headquarters. The talks will be extended on a day-by-day basis,
Murphy said.
   The two sides have been negotiating for more than two years over
wages and benefits in the aftermath of NWA's acquisition of Republic
Airlines in the fall of 1986. The process is complicated by the need
to bring pilots of the airlines under the same agreement.
</TEXT>
