<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-DowJones     07-11 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Dow Jones,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts 2.3 Percent Decline in 2nd-Qtr Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc. said Tuesday its
second-quarter profit slipped 2.3 percent despite a 5.8 percent rise
in revenue.
   The company, which publishes The Wall Street Journal and Barron's
magazine as well as providing financial information services, said
it earned $48.4 million, or 48 cents per share, in the three months
ended June 30 compared with $49.5 million, or 51 cents a share, a
year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose to $437.7 million from $413.8 million
a year earlier.
   The company said operating income fell 8.8 percent to $35.0
million in its business publications segment as revenue edged up 0.1
percent, reflecting a slump in financial advertising. Ad linage at
the Journal was off 5.7 percent in the quarter and 16.7 percent at
Barron's.
   Operating income at the information services segment, which
includes its 67-percent owned Telerate Inc., rose 7.1 percent in the
quarter to $58.8 million on a 14 percent increase in revenue.
   For the first six months of the year, Dow Jones said its profit
rose 62.2 percent to $248.4 million, or $2.47 a share, from $153.1
million, or $1.59 a share, a year earlier.
   First-half revenue rose 4.7 percent to $844.5 million from $806.4
million a year earlier.
   The latest first-half results included an after-tax gain of
$164.1 million from the January sale of the company's holdings in
Continental Cablevision Inc.
   The first-half results a year ago included an after-tax gain of
$64.5 million from the sale of a book publishing subsidiary.
</TEXT>
