<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-JunkBonds-Recession     07-11 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Junk Bonds-Recession,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: High Returns from Junk Bonds in Recession Offset Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study of the performance of junk bonds in
a recession, released Tuesday, concludes that while some bonds would
default, high returns from the remainder would offset any losses.
   ``It showed that the argument that the next recession will spell
doom for high-yield bond issuers and investors is a red herring,''
said David Wyss, senior financial economist for DRI@McGraw-Hill, a
Lexington, Mass., business forecasting firm that conducted the study.
   The study of 573 high-yield bond issuing companies was
commissioned by the Alliance for Capital Access, a junk-bond trade
association here. It assumes a well-diversified portfolio of
high-yield securities held from 1988 to 1993.
   Junk bonds, often used to finance corporate takeovers, are
riskier than investment-grade corporate bonds, but are designed to
compensate investors for more frequent defaults by paying higher
interest rates. They've become popular only since the start of the
current economic expansion and critics say they would fare poorly in
a recession.
   The study used four negative economic scenarios including the
so-called ``soft-landing'' _ slower but continued growth _ currently
being sought by the Federal Reserve as it attempts to contain
inflation.
   The other scenarios were small and big recessions and a deep
recession accompanied by inflation such as occurred in 1981-82.
   In each instance, the study said, high-yield bonds would produce
returns superior to those of medium-term Treasury bonds,
mortgage-backed securities and investment-grade bonds even after
defaults are taken into account.
   The study found that the default rate for high-yield bonds in
each case would rise, ``though not significantly.''
   `What we also find is that the current yields of junk bonds are
attractive enough to offset the risk of default,'' Wyss said at a
news conference.
   The study emphasized that investors should hold a widely mixed
portfolio of junk bonds.
   ``Diversification remains the key,'' it said. ``The amount of any
one issue should be watched, since exposure to one company or one
industry remains dangerous for junk bonds, just as for commerical
loans.''
   The study found the cumulative default rate over the five years
would be 13.16 percent in the soft-landing scenario, 13.14 percent
during a small recession, 13.34 percent during a large recession and
18.82 percent in the deep inflationary recession.
   It said these default rates are similar to those found in other
recent studies including one released earlier this year by the
Harvard Business School.
   At the same time, the study said the total rate of return over
the five years would be 72.50 percent in the soft-landing scenario,
70.44 percent during a small recession, 80.32 during a big recession
and 54.45 in the deep inflationary recession.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
