<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 2016EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-KraftContest     07-11 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kraft Contest,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Allows Class-Action Lawsuit for 20,000 Winners of Botched Contest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kraft attorney said the company's botched
``Ready to Roll'' promotional game was just an innocent mistake, but
a judge ruled Tuesday that the estimated 20,000 winners are entitled
to seek relief in a class-action lawsuit.
   Many of the winners may have rushed out to buy Kraft cheese after
learning of the highly publicized mistake, attorney Robert Johnson
told Circuit Judge Kenneth Gillis.
   Those people should not be able to seek the same relief as those
who played the game before the mistake was publicized, Johnson said.
   The players' intent in buying the product is irrelevant,
countered plaintiffs' attorney Burton Weinstein, who accused Kraft
USA of ``taking advantage of that great American obsession with
gambling to sell cheese.''
   Gillis granted a motion by Weinstein and several other attorneys
seeking to certify the winners as a class. Doing so allows all
20,000, and anyone else who comes forth with a winning game piece on
or before Oct. 31, to seek the relief.
   The contest involved matching left-side game pieces from
specially marked packages of Kraft cheese singles with right-side
pieces available in newspaper inserts distributed in the Chicago and
Houston metropolitan areas.
   More than 10,000 people claimed they had won what was intended to
be the single grand prize _ a $17,000 Dodge van.
   The suburban Chicago-based company maintains that a printing
error resulted in a total of about 21,000 winners for four different
prizes, rather than the 8,600 it anticipated for 8,000 packages of
cheese; 500 skateboards; 100 bicycles; and, at odds of
15-million-to-1, a 1990 Dodge Caravan LE.
   Kraft nullified the game June 12 after learning of the error and
ordered the specially marked packages of cheese pulled from store
shelves. The company contended it was not legally liable for any of
the prizes because of the errors.
   On June 15, the company offered to quadruple the number of prizes
originally offered and to add cash prizes and special drawings. The
proposal came after Kraft entered into agreements of voluntary
compliance with the attorneys general of Illinois and Texas.
   Under the new payout plan, players who matched game pieces for
the van and submitted them by a June 16 deadline would receive $250
and be eligible for a drawing scheduled for Friday, in which four
vans will be awarded.
   But eight winners have already filed lawsuits, and thousands more
are expected to, Weinstein said.
   The eight lawsuits have been consolidated and will become part of
the class-action case, to be filed within a seven-day time frame set
by the judge, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
