<FIRST>r f BC-SEC-Galanis     07-11 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SEC-Galanis,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jailed Tax Shelter Criminal Agrees To Order Barring Him From Securities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jailed tax shelter scam artist John Peter
Galanis consented to a permanent court order Tuesday that bars him
from involvement with registered investment companies or advisers.
   The injunction, issued at federal court in San Francisco, also
prohibits Galanis, 46, formerly of Del Mar, Calif. and Greenwich,
Conn., from trading securities for anyone other than himself or his
immediate family.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission brought the action in a
civil complaint that charged Galanis and four other men with an
alleged 1986 fraud and embezzlement plot that involved the theft of
$4 million from ISI Corp., an Oakland, Calif.-based investment
advisory company.
   Without admitting or denying guilt, Galanis, who is serving a
27-year sentence at the Federal Correctional Institution in Tucson,
Ariz., consented to the injunction.
   In addition to his federal prison term for a 1988 conviction in
New York on numerous securities law and related violations, he also
was convicted in New York state court of grand larceny.
