<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-China-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0119 07-11 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0119,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokesman: Protests Did Not Seriously Hurt Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CLARIFY. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-democracy protests that paralyzed Beijing and
other cities did not hurt the economy badly, but longstanding
problems such as inflation remained serious, a government spokesman
said Tuesday.
   Yuan Mu told a news conference retail prices rose 25.5 percent in
the first six months of the year over the same period of 1988.
   He said most of the increase actually took place at the end of
last year, when inflation peaked at about a 36 percent annual rate,
the highest in 40 years of communist rule and a factor in widespread
public dissatisfaction with the government.
   ``The momentum of inflation has been checked but ... in the
second half of the year we will have to make great efforts to keep
prices visibly lower than last year,'' he said.
   The government adopted harsh austerity measures last fall to curb
inflation, including a ban on new construction and halt to many
projects already under way. New taxes were introduced on China's
tiny but prosperous private sector and on luxury imports.
   Yuan said investment in fixed assets had been cut 7 percent from
the first half of last year, to $12 billion. The pace of growth in
retail sales has fallen, he said, and the money supply has been cut.
   Economists have blamed China's inflation on a combination of too
much investment, especially in luxury hotels and office buildings,
too much consumer spending and easy credit.
   ``The economic situation is still not rationalized,'' Yuan said.
Problems, he added, remain ``quite serious.''
   Official reports last week said processing industries continued
to grow faster than raw material production, creating shortages that
also have contributed to price increases.
   Recent reports also put the trade deficit at $5.7 billion for the
first half of the year. However, Yuan said the actual deficit was
$3.8 billion, taking donations into account and deducting from the
import figure equipment brought into the country as foreign
investment.
   He said actual foreign investment was up 32.7 percent, to $3.76
billion, while contracts were signed for an additional $1.7 billion
in investment.
   He said the figures showed that the impact of the seven weeks of
protests in Beijing and June 3-4 army crackdown were ``not very
serious.'' Foreign disapproval expressed in the form of sanctions
could hurt China's economy in the short term, he added, but in the
long run would only ``inspire a spirit of plain living and hard
struggle and relying on our own efforts.''
   Beijing city officials have put direct economic losses from the
protests and fighting at $347.5 million.
   Yuan said prospects for the summer harvest were good after four
straight years of poor agricultural performance. He said all summer
crops were expected to yield 93 million tons, up more than 2 tons
from last year.
   Official media reports in the past two weeks have acclaimed the
crop that is being harvested now as a bumper one, due largely to
good rainfall in regions hit by a serious drought last year.
   But the harvest presents the state with a new dilemma: how to pay
for grain that the peasants are required to sell directly to the
government. Last fall, lacking cash, the state gave many peasants
IOUs, but it has pledged not to do so this year.
</TEXT>
