<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Strikes 1stLd-Writethru f0293 07-11 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Strikes, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0293,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Tuesday in Britain, More Planned for Wednesday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with talks breaking down; pickup
5th, ``Once again...'; SUBS 10th pvs, `Even if...' to conform; pickup 11th,
`The transport...''. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Railways, docks and city hall services were
disrupted on Tuesday in the most severe week of strikes for higher
pay since Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher took office 10 years ago.
   Meanwhile, a survey of public opinion polls by the British
Broadcasting Corp. showed Mrs. Thatcher trailing in popularity for
the first time.
   Late Tuesday, the first direct negotiations since May between
state-run British Rail and unions broke down when union
representatives walked out after the two sides failed to agree on a
pay raise.
   Speaking to Parliament, Mrs. Thatcher condemned the city hall
walkouts.
   ``Once again it is some of the extreme left wing in the trade
unions who never think of serving the public or of their duty to the
public,'' Mrs. Thatcher said.
   The prime minister spoke hours after the BBC's Poll of Polls
reported Neil Kinnock's Labor Party had a 10-point lead over Mrs.
Thatcher's governing Conservative Party.
   Commuters struggled to get home Tuesday as hundreds of trains
were canceled nationwide on the second day of a ban on overtime by
the train workers' union, the Associated Society of Locomotive
Engineers and Firemen.
   Unions want a 10 percent pay raise, but British rail has offered
them 7 percent. They say a major cause of this summer's labor unrest
is an annual inflation rate of 8.3 percent _ the highest in seven
years _ which has eaten into wages.
   Rail workers also want British Rail to continue its national pay
bargaining, which the company has said will be replaced on Oct. 31
with regional negotiations.
   The National Union of Railwaymen said it would go ahead with
Wednesday's 24-hour strike, the fourth in as many weeks. Subway
train drivers were also to strike Wednesday in the 10th stoppage
since April 5th.
   The Transport and General Workers Union said 96 percent of its
9,400 dock workers stayed away on the first day of an indefinite
strike for job guarantees at 60 ports nationwide. But the National
Association of Port Employers said the dock workers were split, with
18 of the 60 ports operating normally.
   A 48-hour pay strike by the National Association of Local
Government Workers, the second in two weeks, closed libraries, day
care centers for the handicapped and mentally ill, museums,
municipal colleges, and local inspection and tax offices.
   The union said 90 percent of its nearly half a million members
were out, paralyzing city halls. The union threatened a three-day
strike next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
